<FIRST>r a PM-Lites     05-08 0415</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lites,0431</SECOND>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LACONIA, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Just call Joe Bean Mr. Jalapeno.
   Bean blazed past the competition at Sunday's jalapeno-eating
contest in Laconia for a victory worth $200.
   The contest at the Nothing Fancy restaurant pitted Bean against
three others. He ate 20 of the hot peppers in a minute, while his
closest competitor managed to swallow 16.
   The so-called Final Four on Sunday earned their positions by
winning preliminary rounds earlier last week. In the opening round,
Bean shocked the crowd by downing 24 peppers, but wasn't quite up
to such a display on Sunday.
   ``I had stomach cramps,'' he said.
   Bean came prepared as he showed up with a bottle of stomach
medicine ``just in case.'' Contest organizers made sure the
contestants would be in the right mental frame by hanging two $100
bills in front of them as they ate.
   The contest was the brainchild of Nothing Fancy owner Al
Giguere, who hopes to make the contest an annual event.
   Giguere said he had hoped the world record of 29 jalapenos eaten
in one minute would fall at his inaugural event.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>EL RENO, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of people cheered when workers
flipped a 9-foot onion burger, but they were even happier when it
was ready to eat.
   City officials say the small community outside Oklahoma City is
famous for its onion burgers, and they set out to prove it in a
colossal way Saturday. Chefs toiled about two hours over a burger
consisting of 150 pounds of meat and an equal amount of onion.
   ``This is uniquely El Reno,'' City Manager Larry Palmer said of
the town's Onion-Fried Burger Day.
   Five people began patting the hamburger meat on a grill welded
together by Canadian Valley Vo-Tech School students. Next came the
sliced onions, evenly spread over the monster patty.
   Moments later, spectators caught a whiff of the burger while a
quartet belted out songs about burgers.
   When the burger was ready to be flipped, the grill was taken off
the coals and the top half of the lid was lowered with pulleys.
Workers carefully flipped the grill and returned it to the coals,
and crowd whistled and applauded.
   People soon began to fight for position in line for a sample.
Chefs used bottomless coffee cans like cookie-cutters to slice the
burger.
   ``This is good for El Reno, this is just what we need,'' Fire
Chief Ron Martin said. ``We need to do this every year.''
</TEXT>
