<FILEID>AP-NR-05-08-89 0118EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-High-DefinitionTV     05-08 1016</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-High-Definition TV,980</SECOND>
<HEAD>High-Definition TV Star of Broadcasters Show</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   High-definition television was the
undisputed star of this year's National Association of
Broadcasters' convention, dominating conversations around hotel
lobbies, at restaurants and in numerous technical and policy
sessions.
   A dozen companies laid out advanced television displays,
covering 22,000 square feet, as they tried to convince TV station
owners and engineers that crisper, wide-screen TV images and
compact disc-quality sound will be worth the large investment in
new equipment.
   Some estimates have put the cost at $3 million to $18 million to
convert a TV station to full HDTV capability.
   At the same time, no one knows if TV viewers will pay the
$3,000-$4,000 that HDTV sets are expected to cost when they first
appear in this country, probably by 1995.
   But no matter how HDTV develops, many members of Congress want
to make sure it's an American show. Those congressional proponents
see HDTV, which is expected to be a $50 billion business in 20
years, as a means of revitalizing a U.S. electronics industry that
was decimated by competition from low-cost Asian imports in the
1970s.
   ``American industrial competitiveness in advanced electronics,
especially consumer advanced electronics, is not what it should be,
is not what it could be ... and high-definition television does
offer a vehicle to combat'' that loss of competitiveness, Rep. Don
Ritter, R-Pa., told an NAB session.
   Ritter has introduced a bill to pump at least $100 million a
year in federal grants or loans into HDTV research, as well as
revising antitrust and trade laws to spur a U.S. HDTV industry.
   And he said the Japanese have no right to criticize this ``Team
America'' approach.
   ``I don't think it's appropriate to be lectured to by the
Japanese on how to deal with important technological advance when
it comes to one's own national interests,'' he said to an
appreciative audience of broadcasters.
   Although it will be at least two years before the Federal
Communications Commission decides on standards for over-the-air
HDTV broadcasts, companies such as NBC, Zenith, Japan's NHK
broadcasting network and others are beating the drums for their
competing approaches to advanced television.
   The FCC has said a U.S. HDTV system must not make the nation's
existing 160 million TV sets obsolete. That means manufacturers
must find ways to give viewers both the standard signal, called
NTSC, and the new HDTV signal for those who have special TV sets to
receive them.
   HDTV signals typically pack seven times as much information as
do NTSC signals.
   No one has yet demonstrated a way to fit that much information
into current TV channels without causing interference with
neighboring channels.
   HDTV probably will need more space, and it will be up to the FCC
to decide whether to give HDTV a bigger chunk of the already
crowded airwaves.
   Some are proposing that stations broadcast two signals _ the
standard NTSC signal, and then a second high-definition signal on a
channel that isn't being used currently.
   Older sets would receive the NTSC signal, while new HDTV sets
could receive both the old and new signals.
   Others want stations to send a standard NTSC signal that when
combined with another signal on an adjacent channel would create
HDTV.
   Others, such as NBC, are taking a more cautious approach. Its
Advanced Compatible Television system provides an ``enhanced'' TV
image that NBC is promoting as a low-cost interim step towards true
HDTV.
   The ACTV system, which is being developed by NBC, RCA and the
David Sarnoff Research Center, was demonstrated at the NAB meeting.
   NBC also demonstrated computer simulations of the proposed
second generation of ACTV, which would provide double the clarity
of existing TV displays and very high-quality sound _ considered
true HDTV.
   Zenith officials at NAB claimed they had found a way to fit
their Spectrum Compatible HDTV signal into the amount of space _
six megahertz _ that TV stations need for each channel, without
causing interference with adjacent channels.
   Zenith doesn't have such a system yet, but it proposes to
transmit its signal on the so-called taboo channels that aren't
being used on the TV dial.
   FCC regulations require that stations in a single market
separate their signals by one channel in order to avoid
interference. If, for instance, a community has stations on
channels 7, 9, 11 and 13, channels 8, 10 and 12 would be open.
   Zenith says there are enough empty channels to allow 99.7
percent of all U.S. broadcasters to transmit HDTV signals. It
expects to have hardware available for testing by the end of the
year.
   NHK was promoting its enhanced-definition system, MUSE-6, that
will provide a better picture to existing TVs, and it also showed
an HDTV system, MUSE-9, that would require 1.5 channels to transmit.
   HDTV sets would combine the 1.5 channels into one to produce an
HDTV picture, while older sets would receive only the one standard
channel.
   A small California company, Faroudja Laboratories, says others
are barking up the wrong tree in their pursuit of HDTV. Faroudja
has found a way to dramatically improve current NTSC TV signals to
create what Faroudja calls SuperNTSC.
   Faroudja's system was used to broadcast an enhanced TV signal at
NAB, and it was used on a videotape of the movie ``Indiana Jones
and the Temple of Doom.''
   The Faroudja exhibit attracted large numbers of spectators at
the HDTV demonstration area at the Las Vegas Convention Center,
where a large Barco video projector displayed very high-quality
images of the movie on a screen 8.5 feet wide and 12 feet high. But
scenes shot on video cameras were not nearly as good.
   Faroudja achieves its improved picture by removing flaws from
the standard NTSC signal and by doubling the number of lines of
horizontal dots used to ``paint'' a picture on a TV screen from 525
to 1,050.
   Faroudja officials say their system can be installed at TV
stations for a fraction of the cost of competing HDTV systems and
that it even will improve the picture on older TV sets.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
