<FILEID>AP-NR-05-08-89 0120EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-ProtestVigil     05-08 0625</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Protest Vigil,620</SECOND>
<HEAD>Protestor Conducts Seven-Year Vigil in Front of White House</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENICE ARMSTRONG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When Concepcion Picciotto immigrated to the
United States from Spain in the early 1960s, she saw America as a
place to be anything she wanted.
   And for a while, it was. Picciotto says she settled in New York
City, got a job as an interpreter for an office of the Spanish
Embassy, married, gave birth to a daughter and lived out the
classic American dream.
   But somewhere along the way, that dream fell apart. Now, she
lives in Lafayette Park across the street from the White House
where she protests injustices in the American political system.
   ``I never dreamed to be a protester in my life,'' she said. ``I
found out that the United States is not an ideal country.''
   Flanked by large signs decrying nuclear arms, Picciotto spends
her days painting rocks with doves and messages of peace, and
passing out anti-nuclear literature to tourists and passersby.
   ``We have to assure that we have a world. We are on the brink of
having a nuclear holocaust,'' she said. ``All they (government
officials) care about is just building weapons.''
   Along with her partner William Thomas, Picciotto has been in
Lafayette Park since 1981. She claims to have kept up the longest
vigil of any demonstrator in the park.
   To comply with park rules which prohibit camping, Picciotto gets
by with the bare minimum. Local charities give her food. Tourists
give her donations for her rocks. Picciotto said she leaves her
post only for an infrequent shower or to use a bathroom.
   Her bed is an afghan-covered box next to a sign where she
perches at night, lest a passing policeman find her asleep and
accuse her of camping.
   She is required to stay within three feet of her demonstration
signs or else risk a $50 citation. She keeps up on current events
with secondhand newspapers from trash cans.
   ``You have to learn how to survive,'' Piocciotto said.
   Picciotto said she moved to Washington from New York in 1978,
when she was attempting to get help from federal officials to
prevent her husband, whom she was divorcing, from gaining custody
of her daughter.
   ``My husband had a very vicious and cruel lawyer,'' she said.
``I was railroaded by the courts. I felt that I was persecuted.''
   She lost custody of her daughter and hasn't seen the child in 10
years. Picciotto, who has no other family in the United States,
said she was told that her ex-husband and daughter have left the
country but she doesn't believe it.
   ``I'm very bitter,'' she said, but she added that from the
experience she realized that the American judicial system is
flawed. ``I just can't stand injustice. It was like my eyes had a
bandage.''
   Picciotto said some people call her anti-American or paranoid,
but she's not. ``I'm not a communist. Immediately they label you
communist or crazy when you tell the truth,'' she said. ``I'm
defending the Constitution.''
   Picciotto says she has endured taunts and beatings from young
conservatives and military servicemen late at night.
   ``They terrorize me every time I see them,'' she said. ``The
police won't even do anything to them. They protect them.''
   The United States Park Police, who oversee Lafayette Park,
confirmed that Piocciotto has had problems with harassment from
off-duty military personnel and from Republican youth groups. But
police denied that they, too, had mistreated Piocciotto as she
claims.
   ``Connie's rendition of events is slanted at the very least and
is a pack of lies at the most,'' said police Lt. Hugh Irwin. ``And
it's because her world is so small sitting on the sidewalk,
associating with the people she does.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
