<FIRST>r a PM-Bush-BlackCollege Bjt   05-08 0469</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Black College, Bjt,0487</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rural Black College Prepares for Bush Visit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY EYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LORMAN, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The president of Alcorn State University
has asked every president since Lyndon Johnson to speak at the
black college's commencement. He was a bit surprised when one
accepted.
   Alcorn State, one of the smallest of Mississippi's eight public
universities, hasn't had a lot of limelight over the years.
``Roots'' author Alex Haley _ who never graduated _ is by far its
best known student. It also has produced some pro football players.
   Getting President Bush to address Saturday's commencement was
quite a coup, and some are hailing the visit as a historic sign of
racial progress.
   When Bush arrives, he will be ``in the boondocks,'' said school
President Walter Washington, who proudly adds that the president
will tour an important place in black history.
   Nestled in the rural hills of southwestern Mississippi, the
campus is seven miles west of ``downtown'' Lorman _ an
unincorporated hamlet consisting of a post office, two service
stations, an old-time general store and a few houses.
   The campus originally was Oakland College, a Presbyterian school
founded in 1830 to educate white males.
   However, that school never reopened after the Civil War, and
during Reconstruction, the state purchased the land for a black
college. Hiram R. Revels, the first black to serve in the U.S.
Senate, was Alcorn's first president.
   The school, renamed Alcorn Agricultural and Mechanical College,
became the first black land-grant college in the United States,
Washington said. That was in 1878.
   Today, the 2,757-student campus is overwhelmingly black and
Democratic.
   Bush's visit ``speaks well of him,'' said James McDonald,
21-year-old leader of Alcorn State's 100-member chapter of the
Young Democrats.
   The school is not without Republicans. A dozen students belong
to Alcon State's College Republicans, a group formed just last
semester. Member Keith Washington, 21, said he expects the group to
boom over the next few years.
   The Republican president also will travel Saturday to much
larger Mississippi State University in Starkville to give another
graduation speech. The predominantly white school has about 12,000
students.
   Several Alcorn State students said they were overjoyed to have a
president visit _ no matter what his party affiliation.
   However, 19-year-old Thomas Lewis of Natchez was among the few
not enthusiastic.
   ``Personally, I'm a Democrat,'' he said. ``I don't agree with
his views on stuff, so it's no big deal to me.''
   Others said they just hope Bush actually comes _ unlike former
Democratic presidential candidate Jesse Jackson, who scratched
Alcorn State from his campaign itinerary at the last minute.
   ``We were standing around outside waiting for Jesse Jackson for
a couple of hours,'' said 20-year-old Lutrenda Smith of Greenwood.
``We got excited for nothing. I'll believe Bush is here when I see
him.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
