<FIRST>u i AM-Panama 5thLd-Writethru a0745 05-08 0869</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Panama, 5th Ld-Writethru, a0745,0898</SECOND>
<HEAD>Opposition, Government Claim Victory; Fraud Charges Leveled</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES thruout with both sides claiming victory, quotes from
Duque, government poll. EDITS to tighten.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos PAN1, PAN3-7</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD HERZFELDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The opposition and the government
both claimed victory Sunday before most votes were counted in a
presidential election considered a referendum on the de facto rule
of Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega.
   The opposition claimed that forces loyal to Noriega had
perpetrated widespread fraud and some U.S. observers reported
witnessing irregularites.
   Turnout was high in Sunday's largely peaceful balloting, which
pitted Noriega's hand-picked candidate, Carlos Duque, against the
opposition's Guillermo Endara.
   ``The triumph of the opposition is indisputable,'' Endara said
after polls closed but before any results had been announced. He
claimed there were ``serious irregularities'' and called for a
protest march on Monday.
   Endara told a news conference that he had won by a two-to-one
margin.
   The government coalition countered in a statement that ``we can
affirm that our triumph is decisive, just, honest, and perfectly
clear.''
   ``We are satisfied and grateful for the support of the people,''
Duque told a news conference. He called opposition talk of fraud
``childish.''
   The victory speeches came as workers tallied paper ballots at
polling places, and both sides released exit polls that favored
their side.
   The opposition said its poll gave Endara 55.1 percent of the
vote to 39.1 percent for Duque; the government poll showed Duque
with 50.9 percent of the vote to 44.7 percent for Endara.
   In the only reported incident of violence, the Roman Catholic
church said a Dutch priest was shot and seriously wounded by
soldiers as he urged people over a loudspeaker to go to the polls
in the western city of David.
   Voters began lining up at some polling stations at 5 a.m., two
hours before the scheduled opening. At one booth, more than 100 of
348 registered voters were in line by 8 a.m. The lines were gone by
late afternoon.
   The government promised official results within 24 hours.
   The opposition accused the government of making arrangements for
its supporters to vote ``early and often''.
   Opposition vice-presidential candidate Ricardo Arias Calderon
charged that many members of Noriega's 15,000-strong Defense Forces
had voted more than once.
   Opposition leaders noted that soldiers were allowed to jump to
the front of voting lines and that they could vote at any booth.
   They said hundreds of opposition supporters who went to the San
Juan Bautista de la Salle College to vote were told they were not
registered. The college is in a wealthy district and the opposition
enjoys wide support among the business community.
   Arias Calderon, one of the leaders calling for a protest march
on Monday, also claimed three foreigners invited by the opposition
were detained for several hours Sunday before being freed.
   Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., part of a 13-member uninvited
delegation sent by President Bush, said earlier: ``The general
belief is that the election will be stolen sometime tonight.''
   ``We've seen many irregularities, but it is difficult to judge
the extent of the irregularities,'' he said.
   Former President Jimmy Carter, however, said he had seen no
irregularities. ``The only problem I've seen is with the number of
voters,'' he said. Carter was invited by the Panamanian government
along with former President Gerald Ford.
   Daniel Nunez, the Roman Catholic bishop of David, said the Rev.
Nicolas Van Cleef was arrested by the Defense Forces while urging a
high voter turnout and criticizing fraud over a car loudspeaker.
   Van Cleef was shot while inside the car and was in ``grave''
condition, the church said. Telephone calls to government spokesmen
for comment were not returned.
   The government contends the opposition has joined forces with
the United States in an effort to abrogate the 1977 Panama Canal
treaties, which call for the United States to give the canal to
Panama on Dec. 31, 1999.
   Duque cited damaging U.S. economic sanctions, U.S. drug charges
against Noriega and reports that the United States provided the
opposition with $10 million in campaign assistance.
   The opposition denies the government charges, and says Noriega
must be eased out if democracy is to progress in Panama.
   Endara, 52, and Duque, 59, are businessmen. The new president
takes office Sept. 1.
   A pro-government newspaper, La Republica, published official
Election Tribunal figures showing pro-government parties with
611,000 registered members out of 1.18 million registered voters.
   Arias Calderon repeated accusations that the electoral register
included 100,000 extra names and that out of a sampling of 3,000
recent deaths, the names of 27 percent of the dead were still on
the register.
   Noriega's hold over the Defense Forces has effectively given him
control of the government since 1983, and he has been able to
remove presidents at will.
   In the last election, in 1984, Nicolas Ardito Barletta was
narrowly elected over Arnulfo Arias Madrid amid cries of fraud.
Noriega had Barletta resign and installed Eric Delvalle as
president in 1985.
   When Delvalle tried to fire Noriega in February 1988 after the
general was indicted in the United States on drug charges, Noriega
engineered Delvalle's ouster and installed Solis Palma as acting
president.
   Noriega denies the drug charges.
</TEXT>
