05-08 0350</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ritual Slayings-Victim's Father, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0401,0356</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kilroy's Father Expected Constanzo To Surface, But Sorry He Died</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Ritual Slayings, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to CORRECT that Constanzo apparently was
killed by companion's bullets, sted in shootout with police; picks up 8th
graf pvs, `Kilroy said...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA FE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The father of a Texas student slain and
mutilated by members of a drug-smuggling cult said he was not
surprised to see the ringleader slain.
   ``The world wanted him caught,'' said James Kilroy, father of
Mark Kilroy, whose remains were found in a mass grave April 11.
``There were very few people would would put up with a guy like
him.''
   Adolfo de Jesus Constanzo, 26, who was accused of leading the
drug-smuggling ring that killed Kilroy and 14 others, was one of
two men killed when Mexico City police closed in on them Saturday.
   Constanzo apparently ordered one of his followers to kill him
when he realized arrest was imminent.
   Kilroy said late Saturday it was inevitable that Constanzo would
surface.
   It was the disappearance of Mark Kilroy on a spring break
drinking foray into Matamoros, Mexico, that set off a massive
police investigation that eventually alerted authorities to the
deadly drug smugglers.
   The cult was led by Constanzo and his girlfriend, Sara Aldrete,
who was described as the ``witch,'' police said.
   Ms. Aldrete, 24, was being held by Mexico City police. She was
arrested along with four other men following Saturday's shootings.
   Kiloy said he was disappointed when he first heard of
Constanzo's violent end.
   ``It's unfortunate in a way that he was killed,'' said Kilroy.
``He could have revealed a lot of drug information. He could have
revealed a lot of drug sources.''
   Kilroy said he and his wife, Helen, have tried not to think
about the savage death of their son, instead concentrating on a
non-profit foundation they have created in his name to fight drugs.
   ``We're definitely putting our feelings and energy into the
fight against drugs,'' Kilroy said. ``For that reason, we don't
look back. We try to look forward.''
</TEXT>
