<FILEID>AP-NR-05-08-89 0319EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-China-Jobless     05-08 0312</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-Jobless,0320</SECOND>
<HEAD>China's Unemployment Rate to Jump This Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China's unemployment rate of 2 percent will rise
to about 3.5 percent this year as more people compete for fewer
jobs, an official newspaper said today.
   The China Daily quoted Xi Zhongsheng of the State Commission for
Restructuring the Economy as saying 10 million people will be
looking for work this year with just 5 million jobs guaranteed by
the state.
   Jobs are scarce this year mainly because the government, in an
austerity program to combat inflation and too-rapid economic
growth, has canceled or suspended thousands of construction
projects and cut off credit for new investment.
   Factory managers also have been given greater authority to hire
and fire workers, and have been encouraged to reduce the number of
employees.
   It has been estimated that 20 million to 30 million of China's
135 million workers are not really needed by their employers.
Workers are rarely fired and get paid regardless of whether there
is work to keep them busy.
   The actual number of unemployed is thought to be far higher than
government estimates because official figures apply to the nation's
urban workers, not rural laborers who have left farms in search of
jobs.
   Millions of people have given up farming to find work in rural
enterprises during the past decade of economic reforms, and
millions more have flocked to cities for jobs in the booming
construction and service industries.
   Since the austerity program was put into effect last fall,
however, construction jobs have dried up and many rural industries
have gone bankrupt because of a lack of credit and materials.
   According to government figures, about 2.7 million workers were
jobless last year. If 10 million additional people enter the work
force this year and the unemployment rate rises to 3.5 percent,
more than 5 million people would be without jobs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890508-0026 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-08-89 0319EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets 2ndLd-Writethru a0471 05-08 0210</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0471,0213</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Gains, Nikkei Post Another Record High</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to UPDATE with closing Nikkei, dollar figures;
pickup 7th graf pvs: `The political...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar gained against the yen on Monday, and
the Tokyo Stock Exchange's main index topped the 34,000 mark for a
record high.
   The dollar finished trading at 134.52 yen, up 0.67 yen from last
Tuesday's closing of 133.85. It opened at 134.43 yen, and ranged
between 134.40 and 134.70.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average, the stock market's main
barometer, closed at 34,135.24, up 180.25 points or 0.53 percent.
   The political situation is now seen as more stable following
Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita's announcement two weeks ago that
he will resign, said a trader at an American securities firm.
   ``The political situation doesn't seem to be affecting the
market that much,'' he said, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Traders described the dollar-yen currency market as quiet. ``The
dollar was strong for commercial reasons,'' said Midori Takeuchi, a
trading officer at Chemical Bank's Tokyo office. ``As usual for a
Monday, importers drove up the market buying dollars for the week's
transactions.''
   Both markets had been closed since Tuesday for several national
holidays and the regular weekend break.
</TEXT>
