<FILEID>AP-NR-05-08-89 0345EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-SecondAbduction     05-08 0515</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Second Abduction,0530</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Say Husband Implicated Wife In Babies' Deaths</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL DE LA GARZA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALTON, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man whose two infant daughters died under
similar circumstances within three years told police his wife was
upset after giving birth, apologizing both times for not having
boys.
   Robert Sims implicated his wife in the deaths, and said he
thought the deaths were accidents, authorities said Sunday. The
couple had told police the infants were abducted from their home.
   Police Sgt. Rick McCain said investigators may have enough
evidence to file charges against Sims and his wife, Paula, but
added, ``I want to make sure we have all our ducks in a row.''
   McCain has said the Simses are the prime suspects in the
suffocation death April 29 of their 6-week-old daughter, Heather
Lee, but that officials were awaiting the results of FBI tests on
evidence before making arrests.
   The Simses also are suspects in the 1986 death of their
13-day-old daughter, Loralei, according to Jersey County Sheriff
Frank Yocom.
   McCain said Sims, 37, told him the night of April 29, when Mrs.
Sims reported Heather had been abducted, that Sims was ``somewhat
suspicious'' of her story but that both deaths were accidental.
   In the latest case, Mrs. Sims, 30, told police that a masked
gunman knocked her unconscious April 29, and that she believed he
took Heather. She said her husband was at work.
   A fisherman found Heather's body in a trash can Wednesday across
the Mississippi River in Missouri. The child's body had been
refrigerated since her death, about the time Mrs. Sims reported her
abducted, McCain said earlier.
   Mrs. Sims' account was nearly identical to one the couple gave
authorities in Loralei's case.
   The remains of a child believed to be Loralei's were found about
a week after her disappearance near the couple's home in nearby
Brighton, where the couple then lived.
   McCain said that Sims on Thursday night said ``he was unsure of
his wife's masked gunman story and that his wife might be involved
in the deaths of both his daughters.''
   The couple, who have been staying with Mrs. Sims' parents in
nearby Cottage Hills, have refused to comment. A person who
answered the phone at the home Sunday hung up when a reporter
identified himself.
   The Simses' attorney, Donald Groshong, was not at home Sunday
and could not be reached for comment. Groshong, however, has said
his clients are innocent.
   The Simses' 15-month-old son, Randy, was taken into state
custody on Friday after Sims told police the boy might be in
danger, McCain said.
   Yocom said Sunday that after Loralei's birth, Mrs. Sims asked
her roommate at the hospital what sex child she had had.
   When the roommate said she had had a boy, the sheriff said, Mrs.
Sims said, ``I wish we would have had a boy.''
   ``The next day she made an apologetic call to her husband,
crying, saying she was sorry she did not have a boy,'' Yocom said.
   McCain said Mrs. Sims made similar statements after giving birth
to Heather.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
