<FILEID>AP-NR-05-08-89 0414EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-RitualSlayings-US     05-08 0477</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ritual Slayings-US,0493</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cult Leader's Death, Arrests Bring Some Relief on Border</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Ritual Slayings, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOEL WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MATAMOROS, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Residents of this border city say the
woman believed to have been the ``high priestess'' in a
drug-running cult that sacrificed 15 people should be severely
punished.
   ``The people here want her to be burned in the plaza,'' said
farmer Jose Luis Martinez.
   Sara Maria Aldrete, a Texas college honor student described as
the ``godmother'' or ``witch'' of the cult, was arrested Saturday
night in Mexico City along with four others suspected of belonging
to the drug ring.
   The drug cult's ``godfather,'' Adolfo de Jesus Constanzo, was
shot to death, apparently ordering one of his followers to kill him
when he realized he was going to be arrested.
   Mexican officials last month located 15 bodies at or near a
ranch west of Matamoros. The dead, including a U.S. college
student, are believed to be the victims of a cult that performed
human sacrifices and mutilations to bring magical protection to
drug smuggling.
   The father of one victim said he was not surprised Constanzo was
slain.
   ``The world wanted him caught,'' said James Kilroy, father of
Mark Kilroy, whose remains were found in a mass grave April 11.
``There were very few people who would put up with a guy like him.''
   ``It's unfortunate in a way that he was killed,'' said Kilroy
from his home in Sante Fe, Texas. ``He could have revealed a lot of
drug information. He could have revealed a lot of drug sources.''
   Kilroy said he and his wife, Helen, have tried not to think
about the savage death of their son, instead concentrating on a
non-profit foundation they have created in his name to fight drugs.
   ``We're definitely putting our feelings and energy into the
fight against drugs,'' Kilroy said. ``For that reason, we don't
look back. We try to look forward.''
   Ms. Aldrete, brought out into public for questioning by
reporters in Mexico City, said Sunday she had nothing to do with
the killings and learned about them on television.
   Mexican officials say some of the men in custody in the case
have reported that she played a major role in the cult's activities.
   Across the river in Brownsville, Sheriff Alex Perez said,
``Whatever she gets (in punishment), it won't be enough.''
   Of Constanzo, the sheriff added, ``I think that he should have
maybe died a little slower death, because that guy, he was a very
dangerous man.''
   The savagery with which the cult went about its drug-running
business stunned this border city's populace once the macabre,
ritual-tinged activities became known.
   Some say they'll regularly look back over their shoulders for a
while.
   ``It won't be as tranquil as before,'' Martin Cortez Alvarez,
25, said Sunday. ``Never, or at least not for a while.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890508-0030 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-08-89 0523EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r p PM-PittsburghMayoral     05-08 0506</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pittsburgh Mayoral,0523</SECOND>
<HEAD>Six Democrats Vie for Mayor's Job</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER MATTIACE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A self-described Jewish grandmother and a
no-nonsense Italian-American attorney top a crowded Democratic
primary field fighting for the legacy of the late Mayor Richard S.
Caliguiri.
   Sophie Masloff, a city councilwoman who succeeded Caliguiri
after his death last May, has been reported in recent polls to be
running neck-and-neck with Allegheny County controller Frank
Lucchino. Four other candidates trail.
   The winner of the May 16 primary should be the favorite in the
November. Democrats make up 82 percent of the city's 220,000
voters, compared to just 13 percent who are Republicans.
   The GOP hasn't held the mayor's office since 1933 and there are
no Republicans candidates for mayor yet.
   The Democratic contenders are battling for the right to continue
the work of Caliguiri, who was credited with transforming
Pittsburgh from a sickly steelmaking town to a proud and
progressive service-oriented city of 365,000.
   The popular Caliguiri held the office for 11 years and twice won
re-election by landslides before dying at 56 of a rare protein
buildup in his heart.
   Mrs. Masloff, 71, a Democratic loyalist for more than 50 years,
was city council president before succeeding Caliguiri.
   She often invokes her predecessor's memory, proudly proclaiming
their ``shoulder-to-shoulder'' work in City Hall, particularly in a
1985 drive to keep the Pittsburgh Pirates baseball team in town.
Caliguiri's widow, Jeanne, has endorsed her.
   In her year at the helm, Mrs. Masloff has cut the city's wage
tax to 3.5 percent from 4 percent, paved selected streets and put
more police officers into the fight against drugs.
   In addition to stressing her experience, Mrs. Masloff seeks to
exploit her grandmotherly image and neighborhood folksiness.
   ``I'm Sophie to everybody,'' she says. ``Nobody says mayor and
nobody says Mrs.''
   
   Lucchino, 50, is a third-term controller and former city
councilman who also emphasizes his blue-collar and neighborhood
roots. But he counters Mrs. Masloff's grandmotherly image with that
of a no-nonsense administrator.
   ``My number one priority is economic development and jobs,''
Lucchino said.
   Using a large campaign chest that opponents charge was garnered
from rich and Republican supporters, Lucchino has aired television
spots showing him in rolled-up shirtsleeves fighting for steel
workers and other industrial jobs.
   Lucchino has won the endorsement of the city's two daily
newspapers.
   City Controller Tom Flaherty, 38, has the local party's
endorsement, but his campaign hasn't caught fire. Polls have shown
him drawing the support of 15 percent or less of likely Democratic
voters, behind Masloff and Lucchino at between 20 percent and 30
percent each.
   The other candidates include Byrd R. Brown, 59, an attorney and
self-described liberal who led the local branch of the National
Association for the Advancement of Colored People in the 1950s and
'60s; and Thomas J. Murphy Jr., 44, a state representative who
talks about neighborhood service and a high-technology future for
the city.
   Gary Henderson, 45, a little-known committeeman, stopped
campaigning for lack of funds but remains on the ballot.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890508-0031 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-08-89 0449EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Markets     05-08 0225</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0231</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar at Seven-Month High Against Yen</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar rose to a seven-month high against the
yen, and the Tokyo Stock Exchange's main index closed at a record
high today after a long holiday.
   The dollar closed at 134.52 yen, up 0.67 yen from last Tuesday's
close of 133.85 yen. After opening at 134.43, it ranged between
134.40 yen and 134.70 yen.
   The dollar, which has gained 3.35 yen since April 25, closed at
its highest level since 134.58 on Sept. 27.
   Takaharu Murayama, a dealer at Sumitomo Bank, said the Bank of
Japan had intervened by selling about $200 billion, but that did
not seem to curb the dollar's advance.
   ``The Bank of Japan's intervention was not so much to keep the
dollar at a certain price, but to compensate for a shortage'' of
dollars due to the long weekend, he said.
   Japan celebrated a series of holidays last week, and financial
markets were closed Wednesday through Friday in addition to the
usual weekend closing.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average, the stock market's main
barometer, closed at 34,135.24, up 180.25 points, or 0.53 percent.
   Kenji Ishizuka, a stock trader at Daiwa Securities, said, ``In
the morning, large manufacturing operations like steels and ship
building were traded heavily, but in the afternoon the action
shifted to electricals and financial issues.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
