<FIRST>u i PM-Dollar-Gold     05-08 0299</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0317</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Mixed, Gold Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar was mixed in European trading late this
morning, and gold prices moved up.
   Traders said foreign exchange trading was calm with the dollar
moving within a narrow range. One Rome trader said ``movements were
minimal.''
   The dollar remained well supported by expectations that U.S.
interest rates would not fall and may even rise a bit because U.S.
economic growth is not slowing enough for the U.S. Federal Reserve
to ease monetary policy, they said.
   Another Rome trader said central banks would almost certainly
intervene to stem the dollar's advance, but that they would have to
increase their intervention significantly to have any effect.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar closed at 134.52 yen, up 0.67 yen from last
Tuesday. The Japanese market was closed the rest of the week for
holidays.
   Later, in London, the dollar was quoted at 134.60 yen.
   Other dollar rates at mid-morning, compared with late Friday:
   _1.8979 West German marks, down from $1.8988
   _1.6965 Swiss francs, down from $1.6985
   _6.4055 French francs, down from $6.4080
   _2.1374 Dutch guilders, up from $2.1285
   _1,385.20 Italian lire, up from $1.379.00
   _1.1838 Canadian dollars, down from $1.1842
   In London, the British pound fell to $1.6739, compared with
$1.6740 on Friday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $376.95 a troy ounce, up
from $376.25 bid late Friday. At midmorning today, the city's five
major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $377.15.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $377, up from $375.85 bid late
Friday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose 48 cents to close at a bid
$378.41.
   Silver was quoted in London today at a bid price of $5.61 a troy
ounce, up from Friday's $5.60.
</TEXT>
