<FILEID>AP-NR-05-08-89 0628EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Korea     05-08 0572</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Korea,0588</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Arrests Top Dissident Leader, Military Warns Strikers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY RENFREW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police arrested a top dissident leader
today as part of a crackdown on anti-government groups to curb
violent protests, and the Defense Ministry warned it would block
strikes in key industries.
   Police officials announced the arrest of Lee Chang-bok, a leader
of the nation's main dissident alliance, the United National
Democratic Movement, on charges of violating national security laws.
   Officials said Lee had supported communist North Korea and
organized strikes and violent demonstrations.
   The arrest is part of a crackdown that follows the deaths last
week of six riot troopers in a clash with radical students in the
southern port of Pusan. Lee was the fourth alliance leader to be
arrested along with dozens of other suspected extremists.
   President Roh Tae-woo warned May 3 that he would invoke
emergency measures to halt a wave of violent protests and strikes.
He charged that dissidents were attempting to stage a leftist
revolution under the control of rival communist North Korea.
   Roh was to hold a Cabinet meeting Tuesday to discuss further
measures to curb protests and break up anti-government groups,
officials said.
   The Defense Ministry warned today it would use ``strong
countermeasures'' to keep strategic industries running if they are
hit by strikes. It did not specify any action, but officials have
said troops could be used to keep defense and other important
industries running.
   Defense officials, who declined to be named, said strikes in
defense industries are illegal and warned anyone organizing labor
unrest would be ``severely punished.''
   South Korea has been hit by a wave of violent anti-government
protests and labor strikes. The government has warned that efforts
by radicals to build an alliance with workers could threaten
political and economic stability.
   The government says strikes have cost the economy almost $4
billion in lost production so far this year.
   South Korean newspapers reported today that Roh would remove
some Cabinet ministers for failing to handle violent protests and
labor unrest. Government officials indicated a shakeup was
expected, but declined to provide details.
   Opposition leader Kim Dae-jung called over the weekend for the
entire Cabinet to resign to accept responsibility for the political
situation. Top officials in Korea traditionally resign to accept
moral responsibility for problems or failures even if it is not
their fault.
   The main opposition parties, which generally do not support the
dissidents, have called for curbs on violent protest but also
charged the government is trying to use the unrest as an excuse to
crack down on all opponents.
   Education Ministry officials said today that they would close
university student newspapers and other publications that publish
leftist or pro-North Korean articles.
   The officials, who also declined to be named, said they were
considering allowing riot police to raid college campuses to end
protests or to halt manufacture of firebombs and other weapons.
   Radical students and the anti-government dissident groups have
little support because of their violent tactics and extreme
political views. The radicals have been calling for the overthrow
of Roh and the creation of a leftist state ruled by workers and
farmers.
   Roh, a former general, won presidential elections in late 1987
after rival opposition candidates split the anti-government vote.
He has helped introduce democratic reforms but many Koreans
distrust the government because of its ties to the authoritarian
regime of former President Chun Doo-hwan.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
