<FIRST>d a PM-BRF--O'Connor-Lucy     05-08 0145</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--O'Connor-Lucy,0151</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cardinal Loved Lucy for Her Portrayal of Marriage</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cardinal John O'Connor, who last month blasted
television as ``radioactive filth,'' says Lucille Ball's program in
the 1950s provided ``decent laughter.''
   O'Connor said Ball's ``was a TV marriage that was a good
marriage.'' He said that with her on-air pregnancy in 1953, ``she
made married pregnancy the sacrament that it is.''
   ``I was a real fan,'' he said.
   O'Connor said Sunday that Ball, who died two weeks ago in Los
Angeles, was owed a great deal for providing ``decent laughter.''
   The cardinal described her show as ``decent, human and
entertaining.''
   ``I'm not proposing her for canonization'' O'Connor said. ``She
had personal problems. She was a woman who overcame adversity.''
   A memorial Mass was scheduled for tonight in New York City.
Memorial services were also planned in Chicago and Santa Monica.
</TEXT>
