<FIRST>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     05-08 0511</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0524</SECOND>
<HEAD>Showers Dampen Midwest; Record Snow Falls in Upstate New York</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A record snow continued to fall on upstate New York early today,
while rain showers fell across the middle part of the nation and
frost and freeze advisories extended from Michigan to South
Carolina.
   In western New York, more than 11 inches of snow had fallen by
early today in Rochester, and more than 8 inches had blanketed
Buffalo, setting snowfall records in both cities for May. The snow
was mixing with rain early this morning, leaving only an inch of
snow on the ground in both cities by 3 a.m. EDT.
   Frost and freeze advisories were in effect today over lower
Michigan, Indiana, western Ohio, eastern Kentucky, West Virginia,
southwest Virginia and inland areas of the Carolinas.
   Record-low temperatures were broken or tied Sunday in more than
30 cities, with temperatures fluctuating widely in some areas.
Temperatures at Manhattan, Kan., climbed from a low of 30 degrees
on Sunday morning to an unusually warm high of 88 degrees in the
afternoon.
   More record lows were expected today. Asheville, N.C., was down
to 30 degrees at 3 a.m. EDT.
   Elsewhere today, rain showers fell from Minnesota to Nebraska
and scattered showers dampened the northern Rockies and parts of
northern California.
   Skies were clear across most of the southern half of the nation
and much of the Pacific Northwest.
   Today's forecast called for showers extending across New
England, New York and northern Pennsylvania; scattered showers and
thunderstorms across the eastern Plains and much of the Mississippi
Valley, with possible severe thunderstorms over the eastern part of
Kansas and Oklahoma and most of Missouri and Arkansas; and mostly
sunny skies elsewhere.
   Highs were expected to be in the 40s over western New York; in
the 50s and 60s from the northern Plains across the upper
Mississippi Valley, the Great Lakes and much of the Ohio Valley to
the northern and middle Atlantic Coast; in the 90s over western
Texas and much of New Mexico and California; in the 100s in the
desert Southwest; and in the 70s and 80s elsewhere.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 28
degrees at Marquette, Mich., to 87 degrees at Blythe, Calif., and
Phoenix, Ariz.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 49 fair; Boston 47 fair; Buffalo 37 drizzle;
Charleston, S.C. 48 fair; Cincinnati 36 fair; Cleveland 45 cloudy;
Detroit 40 partly cloudy; Miami 66 fair; New York 44 fair;
Philadelphia 46 fair; Pittsburgh 42 cloudy; Portland, Maine 43
foggy; Washington 45 partly cloudy.
   _Central: Bismarck 55 partly cloudy; Chicago 44 fair;
Dallas-Fort Worth 68 fair; Denver 66 partly cloudy; Des Moines 52
cloudy; Indianapolis 38 fair; Kansas City 59 fair; Minneapolis-St.
Paul 52 cloudy; Nashville 44 fair; New Orleans 66 fair; St. Louis
52 fair.
   _West: Albuquerque 67 fair; Anchorage 44 rain; Las Vegas 80
fair; Los Angeles 57 foggy; Phoenix 83 fair; Salt Lake City 61
cloudy; San Diego 62 partly cloudy; San Francisco 57 cloudy;
Seattle 56 fair.
   _Canada: Montreal 41 cloudy; Toronto 39 windy.
</TEXT>
