<FIRST>r i PM-DemandingAudience     05-08 0240</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Demanding Audience,0247</SECOND>
<HEAD>At La Scala, American Succeeds Where Spurned Italian Failed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MILAN, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American soprano Kalle Esperian won over the
demanding public at La Scala Opera House, returning for curtain
call after curtain call to the stage where Italy's Katia
Ricciarelli met rejection.
   Repeatedly booed and whistled during two performances last week,
Ms. Ricciarelli irately withdrew from the opera, saying ``I'll
never sing at La Scala again.''
   The 28-year-old American received rousing applause and shouts of
``bravo'' for her role in Giuseppe Verdi`s ``Luisa Miller'' on
Sunday night.
   ``Sensational success for Esperian, the new Luisa Miller,'' the
Milan newspaper Corriere della Sera said today, reporting that the
American singer received nine consecutive curtain calls.
   ``She conquered the audience with the quality of her voice and
her dramatic charge,'' Corriere della Sera added.
   Ms. Esperian, a pupil of Italian opera star Luciano Pavarotti
and a winner of the Philadelphia opera contest in 1985, said ``it
was an unbelievable experience. I was very tense for a debut in
extremely difficult conditions. Now I am overjoyed.''
   Ms. Ricciarelli, the wife of Italian television entertainer
Pippo Baudo, had been scheduled to sing three more nights at La
Scala through May 31.
   Her appearance was also marred by clashes between Baudo and some
fans who had been critical of his wife's performance.
   Baudo confirmed in a radio interview last week that he had
kicked one man who had insulted his wife.
</TEXT>
