<FILEID>AP-NR-05-08-89 0809EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Lebanon     05-08 0504</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon,0515</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shelling Resumes In Lebanon, Arab League Envoy to Return</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RIMA SALAMEH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Civilians scrambled for their bunkers
today when Moslem and Christian forces resumed heavy shelling
across the city after a brief morning lull.
   Police said Syrian and allied Druse Moslem gunners pounded the
coast near the ports of Jounieh and Byblos, blocking the only
escape routes for 1 million people trapped in the besieged
Christian enclave. Christian gunners struck back with barrages of
155mm howitzer fire aimed at west Beirut's seaside districts and
around the international airport, police said.
   Thousands of residents had left their basements and underground
bomb shelters during the lull to replenish food and water supplies.
   Police said 21,500 shells and rockets were fired on Beirut's
Moslem and Christian sectors from dusk Saturday to midnight Sunday,
ending a cease-fire negotiated by the Arab League.
   A police spokesman, who cannot be named under standing rules,
said 22 people were killed and 120 wounded in the 30-hour barrage.
   Since the current round of fighting in Lebanon's 14-year-old
civil war began on March 8, 300 people have been killed and 1,131
wounded.
   Lakhdar Ibrahimi of Algeria, the Arab League assistant
secretary-general, was to return to Beirut on Tuesday to try to
revive the cease-fire, Beirut newspapers reported. The papers said
he will be accompanied by Brig. Gen. Ali Al-Momen, the Kuwaiti
commander of a 321-man observer force that will be drawn from six
Arab nations to monitor the truce that was called on April 28.
   ``The Arabs face the difficult task of shoring up the
cease-fire. Otherwise the observers will have nothing to monitor,''
the police spokesman said.
   Gaping holes were blown in scores of apartment buildings on both
sides of Beirut's Green Line, which divides the city's Moslem and
Christian sectors. Hundreds of cars smoldered on streets blanketed
with debris, glass shards and dangling power cables.
   ``They've destroyed everything I own,'' said Mahmoud Younis, a
30-year-old Moslem as he stared at his gutted electrical tools shop
in west Beirut. ``I hope they will roast in hell, all of them.''
   One shell tore through the building that houses the west Beirut
office of the British Reuters news agency and caused extensive
damage. No one was injured the agency's staff reported.
   Another shell struck the newsroom of the state-run television
station in a building in west Beirut. ``It was a miracle no one was
hurt,'' said announcer Leena Saidi. ``We're now operating from the
station's bunker.''
   The fighting pits army commander Gen. Michel Aoun's 20,000
troops, most of whom are Christians, against Syrian army forces and
the 7,000-strong militia of Druse warlord Walid Jumblatt's
Progressive Socialist Party.
   The latest round began after Aoun's troops blockaded illegal
harbors run by Moslem militias south of Beirut. He said the ports
cost the state about $100 million a year in customs levies.
Jumblatt retaliated by shelling the 310-square-mile Christian
enclave north of the capital. The Syrians later joined the fighting
and sealed off the enclave's land exits.
</TEXT>
