<FILEID>AP-NR-05-08-89 0812EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-LottoQueen     05-08 0333</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lotto Queen,0342</SECOND>
<HEAD>Record Lotto Winner Helping Less Fortunate With Her Millions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sure, winning $55 million in a lottery
changed Sheelah Ryan's life. She bought a new house and a car. But
much of money goes to a foundation that helps single mothers,
abused women and lonely senior citizens.
   ``A year ago I wished I could win the lottery so I could buy
whatever I want and never have to look at another price tag again.
My wish came true, but I still look at the price tags,'' she said.
   She won $55.2 million in Florida's lottery last year, the
nation's largest individual jackpot.
   ``I guess I've disappointed a lot of people,'' she said. ``I
could be traveling all over the world, or have a beautiful mansion
on the ocean or have a chauffeur-driven Rolls Royce. ... But that's
not my style.''
   The former real-estate saleswoman heads the Ryan Foundation.
Formed in Decembver, it is building low-cost housing in
north-central Florida and is paying overdue rents to spare single
mothers and their children from eviction.
   Ryan, who lives in Winter Springs, about 10 miles from Orlando,
also wants to create a fund to grant wishes to elderly people with
only a few months to live.
   ``I don't have enough money to solve the world's problems, or
Florida's problems or even Seminole County's problems,'' she said
recently at the foundation's modest office. ``But I can make a
difference. I can help people who are going through devastating
times.''
   Ryan's spends her days meeting with the directors of charities,
politicians and clergymen to discuss projects and scouting sites
for low-cost housing.
   The lottery prize pays out $2.7 million a year for 20 years, cut
to about $1.8 million a year by taxes.
   Part of the money is invested, part goes to the foundation and
Ryan lives on an allowance. She will not disclose how much of her
winnings go to the foundation, saying only that it is a
``substantial amount.''
</TEXT>
