<FILEID>AP-NR-05-08-89 0855EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-UtahFusion     05-08 0231</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Utah Fusion,0236</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fusion Researchers To Present Case To Their Electrochemical Peers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two scientists under fire to prove their
claims of ``cold fusion'' go before a jury of their peers tonight
at a chemists' conclave in Los Angeles.
   University of Utah chemist B. Stanley Pons and Martin
Fleischmann of the University of Southampton in England hoped to
bolster their claims that they achieved nuclear fusion in a jar at
room temperature _ a breakthrough that, if confirmed, could open
the door to a cheap and virtually inexhaustible source of energy.
   Pons said Sunday that he and Fleischmann would present their
evidence at the Electrochemical Society's biannual meeting.
   Last week in Baltimore, scientists at a meeting of the American
Physical Society discounted the fusion claims, accusing Pons and
Fleischmann of errors.
   Physicists have been the pair's chief critics since they
announced March 23 that experiments had produced fusion using rods
of palladium in electrically charged coils of platinum immersed in
deuterium-rich heavy water.
   The two said their experiment yielded more than four times the
energy needed to produce it. Pons said he and Fleischmann would
report on later research, including ``new results that exhibit very
large amounts of excess heat.''
   If confirmed, Utah's cold fusion claims would undercut the
long-held belief that fusion, which powers the sun and hydrogen
bombs, occurs only at extremely high temperatures.
</TEXT>
