<HEAD>Explosion Damages White Legislator's House In South Africa</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bomb extensively damaged the
home of a white legislator, but caused no injury to his wife and
daughters, who were asleep at the time, police said today.
   ``It was the first terrorist attack on the home of a white
member of Parliament,'' state Radio South Africa said after the
explosion Sunday night at the house of B.L. ``Boy'' Geldenhuys in
Randfontein Park, west of Johannesburg.
   Police said right-wing extremists may have laid the blast.
   The explosion occurred next to a concrete pillar at the entrance
to the two-story house, causing damage estimated at $9,000-$14,000,
police said.
   Geldenhuys, who is senior director of information for the
governing National Party, was flying to Cape Town at the time. His
wife, Kallie, said one of the pillars at the front door was blown
away, the ceiling collapsed, the family room door was blown out of
its frame and windows were shattered.
