<FIRST>r a PM-SutherlandTrial     05-08 0260</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sutherland Trial,0268</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hide-and-Seek Murder Trial to Begin This Week</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OLNEY, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Reporters have had to play hide-and-seek with
the judge and stand up through jury selection in a child-murder
case.
   Cecil Steve Sutherland, 33, is charged with sexually molesting
and slashing the throat of a 10-year-old who had left her house to
look for her dog.
   Testimony begins this week in the trial, which was moved here
from Mount Vernon, 60 miles away, because of publicity.
   Despite the change of venue, Judge Lehman Krause imposed a gag
order on participants and did not reveal the location of the
proceedings to the press.
   Journalists said they traced subpoena requests to find where the
trial was being held. They said that Krause let them attend jury
selection only after a lawyer for the reporters complained but that
he refused to let them sit.
   ``It's outrageous,'' said David Bennett, director of the
Illinois Press Association. ``We think what he is doing is clearly
unconstitutional.''
   Krause denied violating the Constitution and said reporters were
not barred from jury selection; he said they never tried to enter
the chamber. The judge said reporters have not been able to sit
because there are not enough chairs.
   However, a reporter was told to stand Thursday even though a
chair was empty except for a clerk's purse, said The Sunday Courier
in Evansville, Ind.
   The judge said publicity has tainted potential jurors, even in
Olney. He said half of 120 potential jurors have been disqualified,
many because they had already decided Sutherland is guilty.
</TEXT>
