<FIRST>r i PM-Greece-Explosion     05-08 0332</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Greece-Explosion,0343</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Socialist Minister Injured by Car Bomb in Greece</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto ATH3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK QUINN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A car bomb this morning injured a former
Cabinet minister in the Socialist government as he was being driven
to work in Athens.
   Former Public Order Minister George Petsos, 42, a senior member
of the governing party, was rushed to a nearby hospital, where
doctors removed glass shards from his face and upper body. A
hospital spokesman, who requested anonymity, said Petsos was not
seriously injured.
   Police officials said the bomb, a remote-controlled device
hidden in a parked sedan, was nearly identical to one that killed
U.S. Navy Capt. William E. Nordeen in Athens in June.
   No one immediately claimed responsibility for today's blast, but
police said they suspect November 17, an extreme Marxist terror
organization that said it planted the bomb that killed Nordeen.
   Two police officers in Petsos' car also were treated in the
hospital for slight injuries. Police identified them as driver
Yiannis Karachalios and bodyguard Christoforos Savakis.
   The explosion occurred a few yards from the former minister's
house in plush Philothei suburb.
   The force of the bomb destroyed the booby-trapped car and two
other vehicles parked on the narrow tree-lined street. It also blew
out a front door and shattered windows in nearby homes.
   Police who requested anonymity said Petsos was fortunate to have
survived. They said the explosion was triggered just after his car
passed the bomb.
   A smouldering engine block and an aluminum alloy wheel were all
that remained of the rigged car, pieces of which were found on the
roof of a house more than 100 yards away.
   November 17 has claimed 13 killings in as many years. Besides
Nordeen, the victims included three senior U.S. officials and
several Greek businessmen, publishers and police officers.
   Petsos was dropped from the Cabinet during a reshuffle in March
to rid the government of ministers accused of involvement in a
multimillion dollar financial scandal.
</TEXT>
