<FIRST>r i PM-Japan-Politics     05-08 0508</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Politics,0521</SECOND>
<HEAD>Takeshita Resumes Search For Successor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TETSUO JIMBO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita, back from a
nine-day overseas trip, turned today to his last major task in
office: finding a successor who will help restore his party's
tainted image.
   Takeshita, who returned from Southeast Asia late Sunday, held a
series of meetings with government and governing party officials to
discuss the selection of a new prime minister.
   ``We will settle this matter as soon as we can. The procedures
are being decided in today's meetings,'' Kyodo News Service quoted
him as saying.
   Takeshita asked Shintaro Abe, secretary-general of the governing
Liberal Democratic Party, to coordinate the selection process, the
Japan Broadcasting Corp. reported. It said Abe would meet with
party elders on Tuesday in an attempt to form a consensus on a new
leader.
   Takeshita, 65, indicated in the Philippines on Sunday that he
hopes to be succeeded by former Foreign Minister Masayoshi Ito, 75.
But Ito has refused the post when approached by party officials,
citing his age and poor health.
   Takeshita announced on April 25 that he would resign after the
fiscal 1989 budget passes Parliament because of the Recruit bribery
scandal that has decimated his party's popularity and dominated
Japanese politics.
   Four days later, he went ahead with a scheduled visit to five
Southeast Asian nations, a move intended to show continuity in
Japanese foreign policy despite the impending leadership change.
   But opposition parties today refused to proceed with debate on
the budget in Parliament's upper house, renewing a demand that
former Prime Minister Yasuhiro Nakasone testify under oath about
his links to the scandal.
   The government has been operating on a 50-day provisional budget
since the fiscal year began April 1.
   Discussions about who will succeed Takeshita as head of the
governing party, who routinely becomes prime minister because of
the party's large majority in Parliament, continued to center
around Ito, who chairs the party's policy-making Executive Council.
   Ito is seen as one of the few senior members of the governing
party who is untainted by the scandal, in which the Recruit Co.
made massive donations to Takeshita and other leading politicians
and sold bargain-priced stock shares to about 160 politicians,
businessmen and others.
   With an election for half the seats in the upper house slated
for this summer, the Liberal Democrats hope they can find a leader
who can project a better image for the party, analysts say.
   In a new development today, Japan Broadcasting reported that
Katsuya Ikeda, former deputy secretary general of the opposition
Clean Government Party, received about $100,000 in donations from
Recruit in 1985-87.
   Ikeda, who has not appeared in public for several months, made
statements in Parliament on several occasions that were favorable
to Recruit. Prosecutors are said to have questioned him last week.
   So far, 14 bureaucrats and businessmen have been arrested on
bribery and other charges in the Recruit scandal, and prosecutors
reportedly are investigating several politicians. Three Cabinet
ministers also have resigned because of links to Recruit.
</TEXT>
