<FIRST>r w PM-US-WHO 2ndLd-Writethru a0517 05-08 0541</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-WHO, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0517,0553</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Campaigns to Head off PLO Entry to U.N. Agency</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Eds: Subs 4th graf pvs, ``Secretary of...'' with 1 graf to CORRECT
U.S. contribution to WHO, adds 1 graf after 9th, ``Zaire's health...''
to UPDATE with chairman elected. Pickup 10th, ``The New...'' ^By SUSANNE
M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States is waging an uphill fight to
prevent the Palestine Liberation Organization from being admitted
as a state member of the World Health Organization.
   The U.S. health secretary, Dr. Louis W. Sullivan, met the WHO
director-general, Dr. Hiroshi Nakajima, in Geneva today to stress
U.S. concern. Sullivan declined to comment on the possibility of a
last-minute compromise.
   The meeting came as the 166-member agency opened its annual
assembly _ a gathering which may be dominated by the PLO's bid to
have it upgraded from non-voting observer to state member.
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III threatened last week to
strip the international health organization of U.S. funds if it
admits the PLO. Washington this year contributed $71 million to the
WHO, a quarter of the total budget for the agency which sponsors
public health programs throughout the developing world.
   U.S. officials were working feverishly to persuade other member
nations the PLO request should be withdrawn, deferred, or as a last
defense, voted down.
   The PLO mission to the United Nations in Geneva on Friday said
compromise proposals are ``sugar-coated bait'' and called on all
countries to oppose moves to delay a decision.
   Nakajima, who has warned a cutoff of U.S. funds would
``destroy'' the agency, made an unpublicized trip to Tunis,
Tunisia, on Saturday in an attempt to get PLO Leader Yasser Arafat
to change his mind and avert a showdown.
   ``I understand he got nowhere,'' a senior West European diplomat
said in Geneva today. ``Further developments now depend largely on
the moderates among the Third World nations.''
   Zaire's health minister, Dr. Ngandu-Kabeya Dibandala, opened the
meeting in Geneva by warning the agency ``must avoid questions
alien to health'' in its efforts to improve health throughout the
world. But Dibandala, president of last year's assembly, made no
direct reference to the controversy.
   China's health minister, Professor Chen Min-Zhang, was elected
to preside over the 1989 assembly. He told the 1,200 delegates that
they face ``important questions'' but that he is ``deeply
convinced'' these will be resolved.
   The New York Times reported that Nakajima _ who consulted with
U.S. officials in Washington last week _ is pushing a compromise
under which the WHO would offer more medical aid to Palestinians in
Israeli-occupied territories but defer consideration of the PLO
application until next year.
   This would keep the United States from cutting off aid to WHO.
   Arafat last year declared a Palestinian state on Israeli-held
land and about 100 of the 166 WHO members already have recognized
the ``State of Palestine'' or acknowledged its proclamation of
statehood.
   However, the Dec. 15 U.N. General Assembly resolution that
changed the Palestine Liberation Organization's nameplates to
``Palestine'' stressed this did not change its status as a
non-voting observer to the world body.
   In the WHO, only a simple majority is required for PLO
admission. The assembly is expected to deal with the issue by
Wednesday.
</TEXT>
