<FILEID>AP-NR-05-08-89 1148EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a PM-MoonlightingEnds     05-08 0401</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Moonlighting Ends,0412</SECOND>
<HEAD>ABC Cancels `Moonlighting'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ABC is pulling the shade on ``Moonlighting'' as
of May 14.
   The offbeat detective series, once a major hit for ABC, suffered
creative struggles and schedule overruns the last two seasons and
was moved last month to a Sunday time period, where its ratings
have been abysmal. In last week's Nielsen ratings, ``Moonlighting''
was the seventh lowest-rated show of the week.
   ``We feel the show has reached a creative conclusion and that
this is the appropriate time to end the series,'' ABC said in a
statement today.
   ``We are quite proud of the innovation which `Moonlighting'
brought to television during the past four years, and appreciative
of the program's tremendous contribution to ABC's program schedule
during that time.''
   ``Moonlighting'' debuted in the spring of 1985 as a mid-season
replacement. It rejuvenated Cybill Shepherd's career and made an
instant star of Bruce Willis.
   Audiences were wowed by the chemistry and sexual tension between
Shepherd's Maddie Hayes, a straight-laced former model whose
accountant ran off with her money, and Willis' David Addison, a
be-bopping, hang-loose private eye who ran a detective agency Hayes
didn't know she owned.
   The show broke tradition and television's ``fourth wall'' by
having the characters acknowledge behind-the-scenes realities such
as commercial breaks and scriptwriters.
   One episode paid homage to Shakespeare in a full-blown, costumed
send-up of ``The Taming of the Shrew.'' Another parodied film noir
with a black-and-white episode titled ``The Dream Sequence Always
Rings Twice.''
   Because of the complexity of the stories and the creative
control exerted by creator Glenn Gordon Caron, ``Moonlighting'' had
trouble staying on schedule, its season run often interrupted by
reruns. The problems were exacerbated two years ago when Shepherd
became pregnant.
   Audiences turned against a contrived storyline that had Hayes
pregnant and unsure whether Addison or another love interest (Mark
Harmon) was the father. A quickie marriage to an entirely new
character (Dennis Dugan) only made matters worse. Then the marriage
was annulled and Hayes suffered a miscarriage.
   Gordon had left the series for feature films, and new executive
producer Jay Daniel struggled to get the show back on track this
season, but to no avail. It had already lost its audience.
   ``We are extremely grateful to Glenn Caron, Jay Daniel, Cybill
Shepherd, Bruce Willis and the entire cast and crew for their
efforts,'' said ABC.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890508-0075 </DOCNO>
