<FIRST>r i PM-NorthernIreland     05-08 0184</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Northern Ireland,0188</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bomb Injures Two Soldiers In Northern Ireland, Civilian Shot</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bomb blew an unmarked
military van off a road today, slightly injuring two soldiers,
police said. A civilian was shot in the head near the scene of the
bombing minutes later.
   It was not known immediately whether the two incidents near the
rural Northern Ireland town of Clogher were linked.
   Police said a bomb, possibly a land mine, went off under the van
outside Clogher, 45 miles west of Belfast.
   Twenty minutes later, a civilian was gunned down as he and a
second man pulled up on a motorcycle outside a farmhouse near the
scene of the bombing, police said. The civilian was hospitalized in
serious condition, they said, giving no indication who opened fire.
   There was no immediate claim of responsibility, but soldiers are
a prime target of the Irish Republican Army in its campaign to rid
Northern Ireland of British rule and unite it with the Irish
Republic.
   On Saturday, nine soldiers were injured in two separate
explosions in County Armagh, police said.
