<FIRST>r i PM-India-Bhopal     05-08 0183</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-India-Bhopal,0191</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bhopal Gas Victims to Receive Compensation on Tuesday</HEAD>
<DATELINE>s BHOPAL, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The heirs of 2,000 adults killed in the 1984
Bhopal gas disaster will begin receiving monthly compensation
checks from the government, officials said today.
   Accounts for the victims' descendants will be opened in the
government-owned State Bank of India, and $50 will be credited to
each one monthly beginning on Tuesday, a government statement said.
   More than 3,400 adults and children died and at least 20,000
were injured when on Dec. 2, 1984, poisonous gas leaked from a
pesticide plant operated by a subsidiary of the Union Carbide Corp.
   The Supreme Court ordered the monthly compensation while it
considers petitions contesting a $470 million settlement reached in
February between the government and the Danbury, Conn.-based
multinational company.
   Petitions challenged the government's right to act as the sole
representative of victims in the settlement negotiations. The
Supreme Court has not yet ruled on the issue and compensation
payments from the company have been delayed.
   The court-ordered monthly compensation will be deducted from the
final settlement, the statement said.
</TEXT>
