<FILEID>AP-NR-05-08-89 1216EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w PM-WrightProbe     05-08 0595</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wright Probe,590</SECOND>
<HEAD>Speaker Rented Out Home While Given Free Lodging</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House Speaker Jim Wright collected more than
$25,000 by renting out his Texas home while he and his wife used
rent-free housing provided by the couple's business partner,
according to financial disclosure documents.
   Papers on file with the House show that from 1979 through most
of 1983, the Wrights rented out their Fort Worth duplex for an
annual total of between $5,000 and $15,000 in extra income.
   The extra money is over and above the $53,488 value of the free
housing provided by Fort Worth real estate developer George Mallick
which is the basis of some of the 69 charges of ethics violations
lodged against Wright.
   Wright, D-Texas, sold the residence in August 1983 for more than
$250,000, and continued to use a condominium provided by Mallick
into 1988, the records show.
   Members of Congress are required to report their finances only
in broad ranges, so it is impossible to determine the precise value
of the rental income from the disclosure documents.
   The embattled speaker continued to be pummeled today by news
reports of other suspect financial dealings:
   _The Wall Street Journal reported that Wright accepted a number
of free flights aboard the corporate planes of a financially
troubled nursing home chain in which he had a $100,000 interest.
   The newspaper, citing an unidentified former official of the
company, Jewell Enterprises, said the practice apparently violates
House rules against accepting gifts worth more than $100 from
individuals with a direct interest in legislation. Wright recently
reimbursed $8,000 to a former Texas savings and loan official four
years after he had used the official's plane for a campaign trip.
He termed the failure to pay earlier an ``oversight.''
   _A former Texas S&amp;L official and major Democratic fundraiser,
Thomas Gaubert, collected large political contributions from other
S&amp;L executives for a 1985 special House election in Texas in which
Wright was active.
   One of the officials, David Farmer, testified in federal court
in Dallas on Friday that he was told Wright would block legislation
viewed as unfavorable by the S&amp;Ls in return for $250,000 in
political contributions.
   _Wright in 1981 urged Reagan administration Cabinet members to
consider retaliating against Canada if it sought to restrict energy
exploration by U.S. companies, according to the Dallas Times Herald.
   At the time, Wright was House majority leader and owned stock in
American Quasar Petroleum, a Fort Worth company that was heavily
involved in Canadian oil and gas activities through its subsidiary,
Quasar Petroleum Ltd.
   The developments come as the House ethics committee is
considering whether to expand its case against Wright beyond the 69
original charges to include allegations stemming from his profits
from a 1988 gas well investment.
   Wright is expected to go before an ethics committee disciplinary
hearing late this month. At the proceeding, the panel's special
outside counsel, Chicago lawyer Richard J. Phelan, will present
evidence and Wright will have a chance to defend himself.
   The speaker's office said today that his legal defense team will
include Stephen D. Susman of Houston, expected to handle
questioning at the disciplinary hearing; Rep. Robert Torricelli,
D-N.J., who would be Wright's emissary to House Democrats; and
Robert Altman, a Washington attorney.
   Legal strategy will continue to be mapped by William C. Oldaker,
who has handled the case for Wright thus far. The speaker's backers
hope they will gain public stature and credibility by the
participation on the defense team of Clark Clifford, a former
defense secretary and longtime prominent Democrat.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
