<DOCNO> AP890508-0081 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-08-89 1254EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Hungary-History     05-08 0217</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hungary-History,0224</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gov't Official Confirms Number Executed For 1956 Uprising</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A government official Monday said 247
people were executed for their roles in the 1956 anti-Soviet
uprising _ the first authoritative confirmation of the number of
Hungarians put to death.
   Unofficial sources had estimated the number at between 200 and
300.
   The independent daily newspaper Mai Nap quoted Gyula Borics,
state secretary in the Justice Ministry, as saying the number was
reached following an official review of government records.
   Borics said the figure covers deaths ordered between 1956 and
1961, and that it was believed to be accurate.
   He said the total included 13 executions for which records had
disappeared.
   Hungarians supporting democratic reforms revolted in 1956
against the Stalinist system. Soviet troops and tanks were sent in
to crush the uprising, whose leader Imre Nagy was imprisoned and
later executed.
   Janos Kadar became the new communist leader, surviving until May
1988 when he was replaced by Karoly Grosz. Kadar's role in ending
the revolt has never been spelled out, although there are
increasing demands for it to be clarified.
   The disclosure of the number executed after 1956 is seen as part
of the attempt by Communist Party reformers to tell the full truth
about what happened during and after the revolt.
</TEXT>
