<FIRST>u i PM-Hostages     05-08 0422</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hostages,0439</SECOND>
<HEAD>Freed West Germans Trasnmit Kidnappers' Orders</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By AHMED MANTASH</BYLINE>
<UNK>Associated Press Writer:</UNK>
<DATELINE>AAQBIEH, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two West German relief workers said
today they were freed from brief captivity last week to transmit
the demands of kidnappers holding a third West German hostage in
south Lebanon.
   It was the first time Heinrich Struebig and Petra Schnitzler met
reporters since their reported abduction Thursday night by five
gunmen outside south Lebanon's provincial capital, Sidon. They were
released the next morning.
   They said the kidnappers are holding Markus Quint, who works
with them for Asme-Humanitas relief agency and who was abducted
with them.
   But they refused to detail the kidnappers' demands, saying: ``We
don't want to endanger the life of Markus Quint.''
   Col. Wajih Abu Ali, PLO military police commander in the region,
said on Friday that Struebig and Schnitzler told him the kidnappers
have threatened to kill Quint unless confessed TWA hijacker
Mohammed Ali Hamadi receives a mild sentence after his trial in
West Germany.
   In Frankfurt, West Germany, today, the chief judge at the Hamadi
trial, Heiner Mueckenberger, said of the kidnappings: ``It should
be said that if anyone thinks that this can influence us, they are
wrong.''
   Hamadi, a Lebanese Shiite Moslem, is charged with murder and air
piracy in the June 1985 TWA hijacking in which U.S. Navy diver
Robert Stethem was killed. Another 39 Americans were held hostage
for 17 days after TWA Flight 847 was seized on a flight from Athens
to Rome and diverted to Beirut.
   Prosecutors have demanded a life sentence for Hamadi, who will
hear the court's verdict and sentence May 17, the judge said today.
   Neither Struebig nor Schnitzler would say whether the
kidnappers' demands have been conveyed to the Bonn government.
   The two disappeared and reappeared under similar circumstances
last year, prompting a Bonn spokesman to term the latest incident
``strange.''
   Schnitzler said the two were ``shocked by a statement
insinuating that we've sort of stage-managed or engineered the
affair.''
   West German news reports said Quint, in his early 20s, was the
cook for the six-member Asme-Humanitas team that extends medical
care mainly to Palestinian refugees in Ein el-Hilweh and Mieh Mieh
camps.
   No group has claimed responsibility for kidnapping the three
West Germans.
   In addition to Quint, 15 foreigners are held hostage in Lebanon.
They are nine Americans, three Britons, an Irishman, an Italian and
a Belgian.
   The longest held is Terry A. Anderson, 41, chief Middle East
correspondent for The Associated Press, who was kidnapped March 16,
1985.
</TEXT>
