<FIRST>r i PM-Britain-Nicaragua     05-08 0436</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Britain-Nicaragua,0447</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ortega Meets Thatcher for First Time, Calls Talks Positive</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAGGIE JACKSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher met with
Nicaraguan leader Daniel Ortega for the first time today and
reportedly told him she was disappointed by his country's lack of
progress toward democracy.
   Mrs. Thatcher also made no promises to help Nicaragua improve
relations with the United States, a British source said on
condition of anonymity.
   Ortega is on a 10-nation West European tour to drum up support
for his battered economy and to help persuade the United States to
normalize relations with Nicaragua.
   ``This is the first time I've met the prime minister and that in
itself is a positive action, that the dialogue took place,'' Ortega
told reporters after his 75-minute meeting with Mrs. ``It was a
very frank conversation. We were both frank and direct.''
   After joking that they both wore green to the meeting, Ortega
said, ``On other points we might not have coincided so much, but we
can work toward a convergence.''
   The British source said Mrs. Thatcher voiced disappointment at
an absence of progress toward democracy, which would mean removing
East Bloc advisers from Nicaragua, and cutting the size of the
armed forces. According to U.S. officials, there are 8,000 Soviet
bloc and Cuban personnel in Nicaragua, including 3,500 military and
secret police.
   Ortega signed an accord with four Central Ameican nations in
which he promised electoral and other legal reforms to ensure fair
general elections, which will be held in February. But last week,
the government rejected an opposition demand to negotiate further
reforms.
   Mrs. Thatcher said there were ``doubts about Nicaragua's
commitment to democracy,'' the British source said.
   Ortega told reporters Mrs. Thatcher ``defines her own policy and
is going to be fair in monitoring Nicaraguan developments.''
   Turning to the United States, he said the prime minister's
status as a world leader ``allows her to be ... able to contribute
so that the problems which exist between the United States and
Nicaragua can be overcome.'' The British source said Mrs. Thatcher
``did not make any promises'' on that score.
   Ortega said she also did not promise any financial aid for
Nicaragua, but he added: ``we didn't have much hope for that.''
   Mrs. Thatcher reportedly told Ortega Nicaragua's economic
problems were largely his government's own fault. Ortega blames
them on his long war with U.S.-backed Contra rebels that has left
26,500 people dead and 23,500 wounded.
   Ortega and his delegation have visited France, Belgium, Spain,
Italy, Greece, Sweden and Norway. He leaves Britain on Tuesday for
West Germany and then Ireland.
</TEXT>
