<FIRST>u a PM-Near-Collision 1stLd-Writethru a0486 05-08 0258</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Near-Collision, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0486,0262</SECOND>
<HEAD>Air New Zealand Plane Swerves To Avoid Small Plane</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with planes coming withn 500 feet. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Air New Zealand jumbo jet carrying 350
people swerved to avoid a small plane less 500 feet away over the
Pacific, officials said today.
   A passenger and a crew member of the Boeing 747 suffered minor
arm injuries in the near-collision at 7,000 feet Sunday evening,
said an airline spokesman.
   ``It was close,'' said Gary Mucho, regional director for the
National Transportation Safety Board. He said the incident occurred
about 20 miles offshore.
   ``The Air New Zealand crew was given advisories by air traffic
controllers of conflicting traffic at their altitude and the Air
New Zealand crew took evasive action by making a left evasive turn.
The other aircraft came within less than 500 feet.''
   Air New Zealand Flight TE6 from Auckland to Los Angeles banked
sharply, said the airline spokesman, who declined to be identified.
The twin-engine plane, believed to be a Cessna, swerved to the
opposite side, he said.
   The small plane, which was not under control of air traffic
controllers because it was just outside the coverage boundaries,
wasn't identified, Mucho said.
   The jet landed undamaged at Los Angeles International Airport.
   An air traffic control specialist from Washington was en route
to Los Angeles as part of the investigation.
   Federal Aviation Administration and NTSB officials spoke with
the crew of the jetliner and were given its flight data and cockpit
voice recorders.
