<FIRST>r i AM-Lebanon-Kidnap     05-08 0694</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon-Kidnap,0713</SECOND>
<HEAD>Germans Say They Were Freed to Carry Demands</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Lebanon, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By AHMED MANTASH</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AAQBIEH, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two West German relief workers said
Monday they were freed from brief captivity last week to carry the
demands of kidnappers holding a third West German, but they would
not reveal the demands.
   In Bonn, West German officials said the demands had been relayed
by Lebanese authorities. They also refused to say what the
kidnappers wanted, but a spokeswoman for the relief agency said one
was that Mohammed Ali Hamadi be given no more than five years in
prison.
   Hamadi, a Lebanese Shiite Moslem, is being tried in Frankfurt
for murder and air piracy in the June 1985 TWA hijacking, during
which U.S. Navy diver Robert Stethem was killed and 39 Americans
were held hostage for 17 days.
   Prosecutors have requested a life sentence for the defendant,
who has admitted to the hijacking.
   Monday's meeting with journalists was the first for Heinrich
Struebig and Petra Schnitzler since the report that five gunmen
abducted them Thursday night on the outskirts of Sidon, provincial
capital of south Lebanon.
   They were freed the next morning and said the kidnappers were
holding Markus Quint, another worker for the private ASME-Humanitas
relief organization abducted with them.
   ``We were freed in the early morning of May 5 to transmit the
orders of the kidnappers to the responsible authorities in West
Germany,'' said a statement in English they distributed at a
meeting in the relief group's seaside compound at Aaqbieh.
   In the statement, they said: ``We can't and we don't want to
give any further information about this case now because we don't
want to endanger the life of Markus Quint.''
   Dagmar Nackunstz of ASME-Humanitas, said in Bonn: ``From what
I've heard, they want a mild sentence for Hamadi, not more than
five years. They also want a government mediator to travel to
Lebanon and brief them on the Hamadi case.''
   Col. Wajih Abu Ali, PLO military police commander in the region,
said Friday that Struebig and Ms. Schnitzler told him the
kidnappers threatened to kill Quint unless Hamadi got a mild
sentence.
   Identification of the captive as Quint dispelled confusion that
arose when officials of the Palestine Liberation Organization
initially identified him as Michael Markus.
   West German press reports said Quint, in his early 20s, was the
cook for a six-member ASME-Humanitas medical team that provides
medical care at Ein el-Hilweh and Mieh Mieh, Palestinian refugee
camps in Sidon.
   Neither Struebig nor Ms. Schnitzler would say whether the
demands had been conveyed to the West German government. They
disappeared and reappeared under similar circumstances last year
and an official spokesman in Bonn termed the latest incident
``strange.''
   Ms. Schnitzler said they were ``shocked by a statement
insinuating that we've sort of stage-managed or engineered the
affair.''
   ``We wondered how such a statement could be issued by the
Foreign Ministry, which has not tried to get directly to us for
information,'' she said. ``They have sought information from
various other parties but none directly from us.
   Asked whether the kidnappers had set a 10-day deadline for
compliance with their demands, Ms. Schnitzler, a 26-year-old nurse,
smiled and said: ``We do have a limited time to convey the demands
of the captors.''
   Abu Ali, the PLO commander, said Struebig and Ms. Schnitzler
also told him the kidnappers demanded freedom within 10 days for a
Lebanese jailed in Cyprus. He is believed to be Amin Zaarour,
sentenced to seven years in September 1987 after a suitcase loaded
with grenades was found in his apartment.
   Struebig, 48, is the relief group's administrator. He and Ms.
Schnitzler have spent most of their time inside the two-story
ASME-Humanitas headquarters building since being released.
   Both said they would not leave Lebanon despite their
government's advice that all remaining West Germans do so.
   ``We are a humanitarian organization trying to help people,''
Struebig said. Ms. Schnitzler added: ``We will not leave Lebanon. .
.. We will not leave Markus.''
   Fifteen other foreigners are missing in Lebanon, including nine
Americans. Held longest is Terry A. Anderson, chief Middle East
correspondent of The Associated Press, kidnapped March 16, 1985.
</TEXT>
