<FIRST>r a AM-ToulousePoster     05-08 0245</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Toulouse Poster,0252</SECOND>
<HEAD>Toulouse-Lautrec Poster Fetches Record $220,000</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An original copy of Henri de Toulouse-Lautrec's
famous dance hall poster ``Moulin Rouge'' brought a record $220,000
bid from a private collector, auction officials said Monday.
   The sale Sunday more than doubled the previous record for a
poster, $95,000 paid for another copy of the Moulin Rouge poster in
1987 in Paris, said Jack Rennert of Poster Auctions International,
which conducted the auction.
   ``It was an important poster because of Toulouse-Lautrec _ the
master of the medium of the poster _ and because it was his first
poster and launched his career. It is not only his finest and most
important, brilliant work, but it was his first attempt at
lithography,'' Rennert said.
   It was bought by a New York collector who asked not to be
identified.
   The mint-condition copy dates from 1891 and is said to be one of
only eight copies of the 4-by-6{ foot classic still in private
hands.
   Sunday's six-hour auction _ which included a collection from San
Francisco rock concerts featuring the Grateful Dead and the
Jefferson Airplane and a series of Mobil Oil advertisements for
``Masterpiece Theater'' _ brought in more than $1.3 million,
Rennert said.
   The San Francisco rock posters went for $4,000 for a group of
100.
   Toulouse-Lautrec's lithograph advertising ``concert, dancing
every night'' and ``masked ball on Wednesdays and Saturdays'' shows
the popular entertainer nicknamed La Goulue, or ``The Glutton,''
dancing the cancan.
</TEXT>
