<FILEID>AP-NR-05-08-89 1439EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Korea     05-08 0392</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Korea,0404</SECOND>
<HEAD>South Korea Orders 90 Dissidents Arrested</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL SHIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities seized a dissident leader
Monday and ordered the arrests of 90 other activists in a crackdown
on violent protests by leftist radicals.
   Police announced the arrest of Lee Chang-bok, a leader of the
nation's main dissident alliance, the United National Democratic
Movement. They said he was arrested on charges of violating
national security laws.
   Officials said Lee, 51, had supported communist North Korea and
organized strikes and violent demonstrations.
   Later, police authorized the nationwide roundup of 90 students,
workers and others involved in anti-government strikes and
protests. The number includes 25 student radicals, police said.
   The government began putting more pressure on the leftist
movement after six riot policemen were burned to death in a clash
with radical students in the southern city of Pusan last week.
   President Roh Tae-woo warned May 3 that he would invoke
emergency measures to halt the violent protests and strikes. He
charged that dissidents were attempting to stage a leftist
revolution under the control of North Korea.
   Also Monday, the Defense Ministry warned it would use ``strong
countermeasures'' to keep key defense industries running if they
are hit by strikes. Officials said troops could be used to keep
plants operating.
   Defense officials, who declined to be identified, said strikes
in defense industries were illegal and warned that anyone
organizing labor unrest would be ``severely punished.''
   The government says strikes cost the economy almost $4 billion
in lost production this year.
   Radical students and other radical anti-government groups have
little public support because of their violent tactics and extreme
political views. The radicals have been calling for the overthrow
of Roh, the creation of a leftist state ruled by workers and
farmers, and reunification with North Korea.
   Meanwhile, the National Assembly opens Tuesday for a 20-day
session that will include debate on whether to ban firebombs.
   Ruling and opposition lawmakers have agreed in principle to
enact a new law outlawing firebombs, a weapon commonly used in
anti-government demonstrations. But some opposition parties demand
that tear gas, a riot-control weapon used by police, be also
controlled as well.
   South Korean newspapers reported Monday that Roh, in response to
an opposition demand, may reshuffle his Cabinet and remove some
ministers for failing to adequately deal with the protests.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
