<FIRST>r i AM-Greece-Bomb     05-08 0443</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Greece-Bomb,0458</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Minister Injured in Car Bombing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK QUINN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A car bomb injured a former Cabinet
minister as he was being driven to work Monday, and authorities
blamed a leftist group they said may be trying to disrupt next
month's national elections.
   Former Public Order Minister George Petsos, a senior member of
the government Socialist party, was taken to a hospital in the
suburb of Philothei. Doctors operated to remove glass shards from
his face and body.
   Petsos, 42, was being driven to his office when his vehicle
passed an parked auto rigged with explosives, a police said.
   ``I got out from the right-hand door because the left one was
jammed and ran out to find a car to take me to a hospital,'' Petsos
told reporters from his hospital bed.
   A police driver and a bodyguard were slightly injured, police
said.
   ``We have no real leads in the case except that the (rigged) car
and its license plates were stolen,'' said a senior police
official, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   No group immediately claimed responsibility for the attack, but
police said they believe it was the work of the November 17
terrorist organization, an elusive group that has claimed 13
killings and many bombings since 1975.
   The government said the attack was aimed at disrupting the June
18 general elections.
   Police said the attack was nearly identical to one in June 1988
against U.S. Navy Capt. William E. Nordeen. Nordeen, the U.S.
defense attache in Greece, was killed by a bomb that was in a
parked car and exploded as he drove by in his armor-plated
automobile.
   The November 17 group is named after the day in 1973 when troops
and tanks crushed a student uprising against the 1967-74 military
dictatorship.
   The group aims to overthrow the government through armed
revolution and establish a Marxist regime.
   Petsos claimed the terrorist attack against him was the result
of the ``libel and false reports about me'' in Greek newspapers.
   ``(They) gave the terrorists the tools to justify my
eradication,'' he said.
   Greek newspapers have alleged that Petsos was involved in a
multimillion dollar financial scandal surrounding a Greek banker
who is in custody in the United States awaiting a hearing on a
Greek extradition request.
   The former chairman of the Bank of Crete, George Koskotas, fled
Greece in November after being indicted for fraud, forgery and
embezzlement in connection with $200 million missing from his bank.
   Petsos was dropped from the Cabinet during a March shakeup when
Premier Andreas Papandreou tried to rid his government of ministers
accused of involvement in the bank scandal.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
