<FIRST>r a AM-OldJustice     05-08 0576</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Old Justice,0592</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fight Begins Over Supreme Court Justice Retirement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER GRAFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTPELIER, Vt. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vermont's court administrator said Monday
he has acted to force the retirement of a Supreme Court justice who
is fighting a mandatory retirement provision in the state
constitution.
   Justice Louis Peck turned 70 in December and, according to the
Vermont Constitution, should have retired at the end of the year.
He did not, believing the state constitutional provision violates a
federal act that prohibits age discrimination.
   Thomas Lehner, administrator of the state court system, said
Monday that he had filed state forms ``terminating Justice Peck
from active service as of June 30.''
   ``I am doing this reluctantly to clarify the issue and establish
the clear precedent whether the Vermont Constitution or federal
statute prevails in this case,'' Lehner said.
   Peck said Monday he expects to file a complaint protesting the
move with the federal Equal Employment Opportunity Commission.
   ``My hope is that the commission will act on my behalf and take
on this case,'' said Peck.
   As amended in 1974, the state Constitution says ``all justices
of the Supreme Court and judges of all subordinate courts shall be
retired at the end of the calendar year in which they attain 70
years of age.''
   But in late 1986 Congress amended the Age Discrimination in
Employment Act of 1967 to prohibit age discrimination, regardless
of age. Previously, the law did not apply to anyone older than 70.
   On Peck's side is an opinion from the state attorney general's
office saying the federal act prevails. But a recent federal
appeals court ruling involving a Massachusetts judge rejects that
reasoning.
   In filing the forms to retire Peck, Lehner wrote the state
commissioner of Finance and Management that ``I have delayed the
execution of this personnel action until today because the law in
this area is not clear.''
   However, the court administrator wrote: ``Because the
constitution mandates retirement, I have executed and forward to
you the enclosed personnel action form.''
   Peck is one of five justices on the state Supreme Court,
Vermont's highest court and only appeals court. He was appointed to
the court in 1981, and has three more years in his term and would
then have to seek legislative retention to continue on the court.
   He has said he might consider retiring before his term is up,
but only if the age issue is settled. ``I am not doing this for my
sake,'' he said. ``I'm doing this for the people who will come
after. I am determined to stay on until this is resolved.''
   The 1st U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals said in the Massachusetts
case last year that it could not find any evidence Congress meant
its law to usurp the state power to govern the tenure of judges.
   However, 1st Circuit rulings have no immediate effect in
Vermont, which is under jurisdiction of the 2nd U.S. Circuit Court
of Appeals.
   Peck said he hopes a suit could be decided quickly. ``We will
probably seek an injunction stopping the retirement order from
going into effect,'' he said.
   The uncertainty over Peck's status has prompted a number of
lawyers to file motions challenging orders he has made so far this
year and seeking his disqualification from upcoming cases. The
state defender general's office alone has filed 30 such motions.
   The Supreme Court has tentatively scheduled two sessions next
week to hear all the motions involving Peck.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
