<FIRST>r i AM-Japan     05-08 0502</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan,0518</SECOND>
<HEAD>Takeshita Resumes Hunt For Successor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID THURBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita huddled with
governing party leaders Monday to resume the search for a
scandal-free successor and a way to revive the party's plunging
popularity.
   By all accounts, most party members already have agreed that
former Foreign Minister Masayoshi Ito should replace Takeshita. But
Ito has resisted the overtures.
   Takeshita, who returned Sunday from a nine-day trip to Southeast
Asia, indicated he hopes to be succeeded by Ito, who chairs the
governing Liberal Democratic Party's policy-making Executive
Council.
   But Ito on Monday again refused the post when approached by
party officials, citing his age and poor health.
   Ito, 75, suffers from diabetes and a heart condition and has
been told by his doctor not to work more than three hours a day,
government and party sources said.
   ``I am not inclined to accept the offer,'' Ito told a fellow
Liberal Democrat, according to a source close to the meeting.
   Ito is seen as one of the few senior Liberal Democratic Party
members not touched by the Recruit bribery scandal, which has
severely eroded public support for the party that has dominated
Japanese politics for more than three decades.
   With elections for half of Parliament's upper house due this
summer, party leaders hope that a leader with a clean image will
help it regain lost popularity.
   In a poll reported Monday by the newspaper Asahi Shimbun, only
about 25 percent of those responding said they would vote for
Liberal Democratic candidates in the upper house election, down
from about 45 percent in the previous poll, conducted in May 1986.
   In talks Monday, Takeshita asked Shintaro Abe, the governing
party's secretary-general, to meet with party elders on Tuesday to
seek a consensus on Ito's selection, and then meet with Ito on
Wednesday, news reports said.
   The head of the ruling party routinely becomes Japan's prime
minister because of the Liberal Democrats' large majority in
Parliament.
   In the scandal, the Recruit Co. made large donations to
Takeshita and other leading politicians, chiefly from the ruling
party, and sold bargain-priced stock shares to about 160
politicians, businessmen and others.
   In a new development Monday, the Japan Broadcasting Corp.
reported that Katsuya Ikeda, former deputy-secretary general of the
opposition Clean Government Party, received about $100,000 in
donations from Recruit in 1985-87.
   Ikeda made statements in Parliament on several occasions that
were favorable to Recruit. Prosecutors are said to have questioned
him last week.
   Fourteen bureaucrats and businessmen have been arrested so far
in the scandal, which also has led to the resignation of three
Cabinet members.
   Takeshita announced April 25 that he would resign after the
fiscal 1989 budget passes Parliament to take responsibility for the
scandal's effects.
   But on Monday, the Liberal Democrats and opposition parties
failed to agree to begin budget debate in the upper house. The
opposition renewed a demand that former Prime Minister Yasuhiro
Nakasone testify under oath about his links to the scandal.
</TEXT>
