<FIRST>r i AM-Greece-US     05-08 0204</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Greece-US,0210</SECOND>
<HEAD>17th Round of Bases Talks Begins in Athens</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Greek and U.S. negotiators on Monday began
a 17th round of talks on U.S. military bases in Greece, the last
set of discussions before the June 18 national elections.
   The previous talks ended April 14 with ``no notable progress
made,'' a government spokesman said.
   Premier Andreas Papandreou reiterated Saturday during a
pre-election speech that a national referendum would determine the
future of the bases if an agreement was reached by the two
governments.
   The negotiations on a new Defence and Economic Cooperation
Agreement have stumbled on Greece's insistence that the United
States provide assurances that it will help solve Greece's
differences with its neigbor and NATO ally Turkey.
   Greece and Turkey have longstanding disputes over seabed mineral
rights, military control of the Aegean sea and the war-divided
Mediterranean island of Cyprus.
   The five-year base agreement expired Dec. 20. Under the accord,
signed in 1983, the United States has 17 months to pack up and
leave if a new agreement is not reached.
   The negotiations, which began in November 1987, will be
temporarily suspended at the end of this week for the June 18
national elections, spokesman Sotiris Kostopoulos said.
</TEXT>
