<FIRST>r i AM-Italy-Opera     05-08 0227</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Italy-Opera,0233</SECOND>
<HEAD>American Soprano Makes Successful Debut at La Scala</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MILAN, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American soprano Kallen Esperian succeeded
where Italy's Katia Ricciarelli failed, winning over the demanding
public at La Scala Opera House.
   Ms. Esperian, 28, of Chicago, received rousing applause and
shouts of ``Brava!'' for her role in Giuseppe Verdi`s ``Luisa
Miller'' on Sunday night.
   ``Sensational success for Esperian, the new Luisa Miller,'' the
Milan newspaper Corriere della Sera said Monday, reporting that she
received nine curtain calls.
   ``She conquered the audience with the quality of her voice and
her dramatic charge,'' Corriere della Sera added.
   Ms. Esperian, a pupil of Italian opera star Luciano Pavarotti
and a winner of the Philadelphia opera contest in 1985, said ``it
was an unbelievable experience. I was very tense for a debut in
extremely difficult conditions. Now I am overjoyed.''
   Ms. Ricciarelli, the wife of Italian TV entertainer Pippo Baudo,
irately withdrew from the opera and announced ``I'll never sing at
La Scala again'' after being repeatedly booed and whistled in two
performances last week. She was scheduled to sing three more nights
at La Scala through May 31.
   Her appearance was also marred by clashes between Baudo and
people who had been critical of his wife's performance. Baudo said
in a radio interview last week that he had kicked one man who had
insulted his wife.
</TEXT>
