<FILEID>AP-NR-05-08-89 1540EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Stalin     05-08 0700</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Stalin,0722</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pravda: Stalin Ignored Warnings of Nazi Invasion</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dictator Josef Stalin ignored warnings from Soviet
spies that Nazi Germany was planning to invade and failed to
prepare his country for a war that cost 20 million Soviet lives,
Pravda told its readers on Monday.
   The full-page article in the Communist Party newspaper came on
the eve of the 44th anniversary of the Soviet victory in World War
II. It marked a sharp break from the traditionally patriotic and
positive reminiscences of Soviet heroism.
   The article also contrasted with a festive mood in the capital,
which was festooned with red banners for Tuesday's holiday. On Red
Square, a large banner stated simply, ``1941-1945,'' the years of
the war.
   Western historians have written much about how Stalin ignored
intelligence reports about Hitler's invasion plans, but little has
come out in the Soviet Union. The dictator typically had been
portrayed as a brilliant wartime leader who rallied the nation
against Nazi invaders.
   But under President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's policy of glasnost,
or openness, historians and others have condemned Stalin's
repression of his own people and recently have begun to re-examine
his wartime role.
   Last summer, Pravda published a chapter of a new book about
Stalin that denounced him for signing a friendship treaty with Nazi
Germany, purging the Red Army when the nation was on the brink of
war, and ignoring warnings that war was imminent.
   Monday's Pravda further rewrote an embarrassing page in Soviet
history and gave Soviets a fresh, bone-chilling look at what Soviet
spies learned about Nazi war preparations.
   Pravda said the article's author, history professor A. Baidakov,
gleaned the accounts from classified state security archives. He
said the state security agencies infiltrated the German secret
police, aviation ministry and coding service.
   Baidakov wrote that security officials forwarded concrete
information to Soviet political leaders about Hitler's invasion
plans as early as November 1940. German forces invaded June 21,
1941.
   But, the historian said:
   ``The leadership of the U.S.S.R. people's commissariats
(ministries) of state security and defense did not, in my view, do
everything to convince Stalin and the country's other leaders of
the inevitability of an imminent confrontation with the Germans.''
   Then, he added, ``But the main blame for miscalculating the time
of the start of the war, for the country not being turned into an
armed camp in time, for not being brought into a state of full
military preparedness, lies with the U.S.S.R. political leadership
of that period.''
   Pravda's editors added their criticism, saying in an
accompanying note that the information ``was supervaluable, however
the political situation devalued it.''
   Baidakov revealed several intelligence reports that he said were
sent to Stalin and his foreign minister, Vyacheslav M. Molotov.
   In April 1941, he wrote, Soviet spies learned that Hitler told a
Yugoslav prince that an invasion of the Soviet was planned for
June. Later that month, German troops began massing on the
Romanian-Soviet border later that month.
   In early June, Soviet agents intercepted a Romanian police
telegram directing that ditches be dug by June 15 in
German-populated areas to protect against air bombardment.
   Baidakov also wrote that Stalin was told a source close to
Hermann Goering, a key Hitler aide who founded the Gestapo and
headed the Luftwaffe, had ordered maps of targets in the Soviet
Union.
   Also, Soviet agents in Berlin reported June 12 that aviation
officials had been told a final decision to attack was taken and
that ``therefore an unexpected strike should be considered
possible.''
   Stalin also was told that German reconnaisance planes and agents
had repeatedly violated the Soviet border, Baidakov wrote.
   Then, on June 16, this urgent message was delivered to Stalin
and Molotov:
   ``All military operations of Germany on preparation of a
military aggression against the U.S.S.R. have been completely
stopped, and a blow can be expected at any time.''
   The next day, Baidakov wrote, Stalin asked intelligence
officials whether the sources who wrote the message were reliable.
Stalin was quoted as saying, ``There isn't a German besides Wilhelm
Pieck, who can be trusted. Is that clear?'' Pieck was a German
Communist leader.
   Before the information could be rechecked, the Germans invaded.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890508-0110 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-08-89 1542EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Mauritania     05-08 0633</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mauritania,0654</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mauritania Blames Senegal for Violence</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SHEIKH BEKAYE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NOUAKCHOTT, Mauritania (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Maouya Sidi-Ahmed Ould
Taya blamed Senegal for violence in which more than 250 nationals
of the two West African countries have been killed in each other's
territory.
   In a speech broadcast Sunday night, Taya told Mauritanians ``any
attempt at disturbing public order'' in this country would be
considered ``high treason and treated as such.''
   He apparently referred to rumors in the capital about possible
trouble between white and black Mauritanians stemming from the
recent violence.
   Two-thirds of Mauritania's estimated 1.7 million people are
whites of Arab-Berber descent known as Moors. The other third,
generally living in the southern part of the country, are black
like the Senegalese.
   Violence began after shooting April 9 in the border village of
Diawara, Senegal, in which two Senegalese were killed, some say by
Mauritanian border guards and others in a fight between local
tribesmen.
   Senegalese began attacking Mauritanians in their country and
Mauritanians did the same.
   No official casualty toll has been issued by either country, but
unofficial reports put the number of dead at 200 in Mauritania and
60 in Senegal.
   Taya said Senegalese news media inflamed the situation by
distorting events after the Diawara shooting. He also mentioned
``the remarkable passivity'' of Senegalese authorities and police.
   His accusation that distorted accounts ``instigated
confrontation among nationals,'' apparently responded to a
televised speech a week earlier by President Abdou Diouf of Senegal.
   Diouf cited ``inhuman and degrading treatment'' of Senegalese in
Mauritania and accused the government in Nouakchott of being behind
the violence.
   ``The government statement and the statement of the Senegalese
president gave the impression of an instigation to carry out more
of these acts,'' Taya said.
   An airlift was established between Mauritania and Senegal to
repatriate their nationals. Among countries supplying aircraft were
France, Algeria, Morocco and Spain.
   Mauritanian officials said 50,000 Mauritanians were repatriated,
30,000 by air and 20,000 across the Senegal River border. About
30,000 Senegalese residents of Mauritania were sent home.
   Taya said Sunday night the border shooting was not the cause of
the strife, but a pretext. He demanded compensation for
Mauritanians whose shops were looted in Senegal and the return of
money he said Senegalese authorities confiscated before expelling
them.
   Until the violence, Mauritanians controlled about 80 percent of
the small retail business in Senegal. In Mauritania, Senegalese did
most of the work in the fast-growing fishing industry and served as
drivers and domestic employees.
   Many black Mauretanians in Nouakchott and other northern areas
fear a resurgence of racial friction with the Moors and have begun
moving south toward the Senegal River, where blacks are the
majority.
   Officials deny racism still exists in Mauritania, but it has led
to bloody confrontations in the past between blacks and white
Moors, who have controlled the government since independence from
France in 1960.
   Reports from Senegal said Mauritania used the air shuttle to get
rid of some of its own black citizens, including policemen who
turned up in Dakar with their identity cards and in uniform.
   Mustapha Ould Abedarrahman, Mauritania's information minister,
said no Mauritanians had been sent to Senegal, but he did not deny
some people may have had Mauritanian papers.
   ``In the formation of our young state, a certain number of
papers were made fraudulently,'' the minister said.
   No immediate official reaction to Taya's speech was reported in
Dakar, but the Senegalese press showed no reticence.
   A commentator for Agence de Presse Senegalaise, the official
news agency, said Taya, ``after a long silence since the beginning
of these events, has just made an unfortunate and deplorable
response. Facile denunciation, gratuitous affirmations and
argumentation without proof have always been the arm of those who
are in a weak position in disputes with others.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
