<FIRST>u a PM-TonyNominations 1stLd-Writethru a0573 05-08 0358</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tony Nominations, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0573,0361</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>`Jerome Robbins' Broadway' and `The Heidi Chronicles' Get Tony Nominations</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with other nominations.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Jerome Robbins' Broadway,'' a collection of
songs from old musicals, and the comedy ``The Heidi Chronicles''
received Tony nominations as the best of Broadway 1988-89.
   ``Jerome Robbins' Broadway'' earned 10 nominations, including
best musical, actor and actress in a musical and best director.
``Black and Blue,'' the tap and blues revue, also took 10
nominations, including best musical, actress, director and
choreography. ``Starmites,'' a space-age, comic-book fantasy,
earned nominations for best musical, best actor and best actress
   The Pulitzer Prize-winning ``Heidi Chronicles,'' Wendy
Wasserstein's comedy about the tribulations of an art historian
from the late 1960s to the present, took a best-play nomination.
Others in the category were ``Shirley Valentine,'' Willy Russell's
one-woman play about a bored English housewife; ``Lend Me a
Tenor,'' a farce by Ken Ludwig, and ``Largely New York,'' a comedy
with no dialogue, written, directed and performed by Bill Irwin.
   Irwin also received nominations for best director and best
actor. Also nominated in the acting category were Mikhail
Baryshnikov, ``Metamorphosis''; and Philip Bosco and Victor Garber,
both for ``Lend Me a Tenor.
   Nominated for best actress in a play were Joan Allen, ``The
Heidi Chronicles''; Pauline Collins, ``Shirley Valentine'';
Madeline Kahn, ``Born Yesterday'', and Kate Nelligan, ``Spoils of
War.''
   Nominations for best revival went to four productions that have
closed _ ``Our Town,'' ``Ain't Misbehavin','' ''Cafe Crown'' and
``Ah, Wilderness!''
   Best actor nominees for a musical were Jason Alexander and
Robert La Fosse, ``Jerome Robbins' Broadway''; and Brian Lane Green
and Gabriel Barre, ``Starmites.''
   Top actress in a musical nominations went to Sharon McNight,
``Starmites''; Linda Hopkins and Ruth Brown, both of ``Black and
Blue,'' and Charlotte d'Amboise, ``Jerome Robbins' Broadway.''
   There were only three nominations for best musical. And two
musical categories _ best book and best score _ were eliminated,
reflecting on the poor quality and quantity of this season's
musical productions.
   The winners will be announced June 4 during ceremonies televised
by CBS. The host will be Angela Lansbury.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
