<FILEID>AP-NR-05-08-89 1549EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Japan-US     05-08 0605</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-US,0626</SECOND>
<HEAD>New U.S. Envoy Arrives to Take Up Post</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRIL JONES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NARITA, Japan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael J. Armacost, the new U.S.
ambassador to Japan, arrived Monday to take up his post amid
heightened trade tensions between Tokyo and Washington.
   Armacost, a career diplomat who succeeds Mike Mansfield as envoy
to Japan, arrived from Hawaii, where he held consultations with the
commander-in-chief of U.S. Pacific Forces.
   He was accompanied by his wife, Roberta, and was met at Tokyo's
Narita airport by Ambassador Hajime Nishimiya, a protocol official
from the Japanese Foreign Ministry, and Desaix Anderson, deputy
chief of mission at the U.S. Embassy.
   Mansfield retired in December at the age of 85 after serving as
ambassador to Japan for 11 years.
   Armacost, who served as special assistant to the U.S. ambassador
in Tokyo in 1972-74, said he was delighted to be back in Japan and
looked forward to working with the Japanese people.
   Armacost's arrival comes less than a week after the Office of
the U.S. Trade Representative announced 54 items ranging from
helicopters to cosmetics on which it said it may slap tariffs to
penalize what it called Japan's failure to open its
telecommunications market.
   ``Everybody benefits from trade, the more even the better,''
Armacost said at the airport.
   Asked about the Trade Representative's recent move, he said,
``They really haven't made those decisions yet. We're awaiting the
results of those deliberations.''
   Before leaving Washington, Armacost said he hoped to negotiate
trade issues ``in a mature way which benefits us both,'' avoiding
the emotional attacks sometimes called ``Japan-bashing.''
   He said he wants to ``contribute in some way to discussing these
issues in a kind of low-key, cool, objective way which avoids
histrionics and hyperbole and a lot of unnecessary nationalism on
both sides.''
   The United States registered a trade deficit with Japan last
year of about $52 billion, according to U.S. figures.
   Hiroshi Mitsuzuka, Japan's minister of international trade and
industry, said Monday he was hopeful a solution could be worked out
on U.S. complaints alleging barriers to American products in Japan.
   Mitsuzuka, who returned Sunday from talks with top trade
officials in the United States and Canada, told reporters, ``I
asked the United States to give us more time to study'' the trade
representative's report.
   On April 30, U.S. Trade Representative Carla Hills said her
office was reviewing the trade activities of 34 nations whose
markets were not open to U.S. goods.
   Japan was the nation most frequently cited in her report, which
threatened retaliatory tariffs as high as 100 percent.
   The trade representative has set May 30 as a date by which
foreign governments must start market-opening negotiations with the
United States if penalties are to be avoided.
   Mitsuzuka said he hoped a reply could be made by May 27, when
Japan's fiscal 1989 budget is to take effect.
   He said, however, the telecommunications issues were up to the
Ministry of Posts and Telecommunications.
   Armacost, 52, was undersecretary of state for political affairs,
the State Department's highest-ranking career official, before
being named ambassador to Japan by President Bush.
   He was ambassador to the Philippines in 1982-84 and deputy
assistant secretary of state for East Asian and Pacific affairs in
1980-82.
   He served as deputy assistant secretary of defense in 1978-80,
and for one year prior to that was senior staff member for East
Asia at the National Security Council.
   Armacost taught government at Pomona College in Claremont,
Calif., in 1962-68, was a visiting professor at International
Christian University in Tokyo in 1968-69, and a lecturer at Johns
Hopkins University in 1970-71 and at Georgetown University in
1971-72.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
