<FILEID>AP-NR-05-08-89 1550EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Hamadi     05-08 0464</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hamadi,0479</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Vows to Resist Pressure, Sets Hamadi Verdict for May 17</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE BOEHMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chief judge said Monday a
verdict on TWA hijacker Mohammed Ali Hamadi will be delivered May
17 and pressure from kidnappers who seized a West German in Lebanon
won't affect the case.
   Reports have linked the abduction in south Lebanon on Thursday
of Markus Quint, a young West German relief worker, to the Hamadi
case.
   ``It should be said that if anyone thinks this can influence us,
they are wrong,'' said Judge Heiner Mueckenberger at the opening of
court Monday. ``Here we are dealing with German law and it shall
remain so.''
   Hamadi, a Lebanese Shiite Moslem, is charged with murder and air
piracy in the June 1985 TWA hijacking.
   U.S. Navy diver Robert Stethem was killed and 39 Americans were
held hostage for 17 days after TWA Flight 847 was seized between
Athens and Rome and diverted to Beirut.
   Prosecutors demand a life sentence for Hamadi, who admits taking
part in the hijacking but denies shooting Stethem.
   ``The verdict will be on the 17th,'' Mueckenberger said. If
Hamadi is convicted, he also will be sentenced on that day.
   Security sources in Bonn said privately there was ``a certain
connection'' between the Quint kidnapping and the Hamadi case, but
gave no details.
   A spokeswoman for ASME-Humanitas, the private relief agency for
which Quint worked, said the kidnappers demand that Hamadi be given
a sentence of five years or less.
   Hamadi went on trial July 5, 1988, in a heavily guarded
courtroom inside Frankfurt's Preungesheim prison. In addition to
determining whether he is guilty, the court must decide whether he
was an adult when the hijacking occurred.
   He could receive a lighter sentence if the court rules he was
under 21. Hamadi claims he is younger than court records indicate.
   Defense lawyer Hans-Burkhardt Steck told the court Monday his
client ``must be judged as a juvenile or adolescent.'' Even though
court documents show Hamadi was born June 13, 1964, he said,
planning of the hijacking began before he was 21 so he should not
be deemed an adult at the time.
   Steck argued that the planning phase was the actual beginning of
the hijacking. The plane was seized June 14, 1985.
   The lawyer said Hamadi acted ``with limited reponsibility''
because he was influenced by those who ordered the hijacking, and
should get no more than five years for his part in the operation
and three years transporting explosives.
   Stethem, 23, of Waldorf, Md., was shot at Beirut airport and his
body thrown from the plane.
   His parents, Richard and Patricia, and their sons Kenneth and
Patrick listened quietly to the closing defense arguments Monday
with no show of emotion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
