<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Thailand-Drugs     05-08 0166</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Thailand-Drugs,0170</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Seize U.S.-Bound Heroin, Marijuana Shipments</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police and drug agents seized 100
pounds of heroin and four tons of marijuana worth more than $80
million in the United States, where the narcotics were to be sold,
a U.S. diplomat said Monday.
   The drugs were packed in cans labeled as containing noodles and
stored in a warehouse near Bangkok's airport, said U.S. Embassy
spokesman Ross Petzing.
   Officers from the U.S. Drug Enforcement Agency and a local
narcotics unit raided the warehouse Sunday and Monday, Petzing
said. Thai police Lt. Col. Amarerit Watanavibool said one person
was arrested.
   The drugs were brought by road from northern Thailand and were
to be shipped via Mexico to the United States, he said. There, the
heroin would have a street value of about $80 million, and the
marijunana would be worth about $320,000, Petzing said.
   Thailand is a major conduit for heroin, made from opium grown in
the hills of Burma, Thailand and Laos.
</TEXT>
