<FILEID>AP-NR-05-08-89 1600EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-BoatPeople     05-08 0313</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Boat People,0323</SECOND>
<HEAD>364 Vietnamese Refugees Arrive In Philippines In Six Days</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At least 364 Vietnamese refugees
arrived in the Philippine in the last six days, the U.N. High
Commission for Refugees said Monday.
   Pierce Gerety, the commission's representative in Manila, said
1,286 Vietnamese boat people landed in the Philippines in April,
compared with 276 in the same month last year.
   All have been transferred to refugee centers for medical
attention, rehabilitation and interviews, Gerety said.
   The Philippine government announced March 21 it would screen
boat people to determine if they suffer political persecution in
their homeland. Under a new policy adopted by the six-member
Association of Southeast Asian Nations, those who fail to prove
persecution will be turned back.
   Other member nations are Brunei, Indonesia, Malaysia, Singapore
and Thailand. Association officials say the refugees seek better
economic conditions.
   The refugees brave the seas in flimsy boats and increasing
attacks by pirates who since March have killed more than 200 boat
people.
   Hong Kong blames the influx of refugees on the Hanoi government.
Security Secretary Geoffrey Barnes said Friday he believes Hanoi is
allowing the exodus to achieve ``benefits'' at an international
conference on Indochinese refugees in Geneva next month.
   Barnes spoke after announcing more than 1,400 refugees from
Vietnam arrived in the British colony this month, forcing the
government to set up tents at a detention center because of a lack
of accommodation.
   In Seoul, maritime police said a South Korean fishing boat
rescued 78 Vietnamese refugees adrift in a wooden boat in the
Yellow Sea.
   They were rescued Sunday morning in South Korean territorial
waters and taken to a nearby island for protection, the police said.
   They quoted Unha-ho, captain of the rescue boat, as saying the
refugees looked healthy and were waving a flag on which ``S.O.S.''
was painted in red when he found them.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
