<FILEID>AP-NR-05-08-89 1649EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Brites     05-08 0394</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites,0409</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WILLIAMSON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ted and Heddy Hess say they've never
had second thoughts about having a human pacemaker implanted in
their pet pooch, Susie.
   ``She is just like our baby, since all of our children have left
home,'' Mrs. Hess said. ``She is one of the family.''
   The 12-year-old Dalmatian underwent the procedure in late March
after being diagnosed as having total blockage of the blood vessels
to her heart.
   Veterinarian Michael Koch referred the Hesses to Ohio State
University's veterinary college teaching hospital in Columbus,
where researchers are experimenting with pacemakers in small
animals.
   ``I'd be willing to bet that this is the only dog in the state
with one,'' Koch said. He said pacemakers used in animals come from
humans who no longer need a pacemaker, have changed pacemaker
styles, or have died.
   ``It's a shame to throw a good, working pacemaker away,'' he
said.
   Hess, owner and operator of a jewelry store in Williamson, said
he and his wife got Susie from a Charleston pound 11 years ago.
She's doing well with her new pacemaker, he said.
   Hess said doctors in Columbus were anxious to try the procedure
on Susie and donated their time. Mrs. Hess said when the dog dies
she and her husband plan to donate the pacemaker back to Ohio State.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It may sound like sending coals to
Newcastle, but Arizona and Texas nurseries are shipping palm trees
to Florida.
   That's because so many home owners and developers want that
Florida-postcard look of streets lined with swaying palms that
demand has outstripped supply.
   ``Orlando, Florida, is not tropical. But they want to look
tropical,'' said Tom Wallis of the architectural firm of Wallis,
Baker &amp; Verlander P.A. in Orlando. His company placed more than 300
palms around Orlando International Airport during its expansion
project.
   Gateway Gardens, a nursery in Oviedo that grows palms, has
doubled the acreage devoted to palm trees in the past eight years,
said nursery manager Kathy Cox.
   ``Everybody thinks when they come to Florida from up north they
have to have palm trees,'' Cox said.
   Enter imports to the rescue.
   Gerald Marston, a senior associate with Sasaki Associates Inc.,
said the 30-foot Washingtonia and Canary Island date palms that
grace the perimeter of the Orlando Arena were grown in Texas and
Arizona.
  
</TEXT>
