<FILEID>AP-NR-05-08-89 1650EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Iowa-Drought     05-08 0307</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iowa-Drought,0318</SECOND>
<HEAD>National Guard Delivering Drinking Water To Six Counties</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE GLOVER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Iowa National Guard began delivering
drinking water Monday to communities in six southern Iowa counties
parched by two consecutive years of drought.
   Officials said the number of communities getting water is sure
to grow, possibly later this week.
   ``It's a growing problem in other counties, and we're going to
continue to monitor that situation,'' Gov. Terry Branstad said at
his regular meeting with reporters.
   Guard trucks dropped off 1,850-gallon water tanks in eight small
farming communities whose wells have gone dry in the six counties
and planned to replenish the tanks daily. The water delivery
program is the first in the state.
   Cities on the delivery list are Grand River, Pleasanton, Maloy,
Benton, Redding, Delphos, Beaconsfield and Thayer. Packwood will be
added later this week, said Ellen Gordon, Disaster Services
director.
   Water has been rationed in the communities and residents have
been traveling as far as 30 miles to bring in drinking water, Ms.
Gordon said.
   The water is being delivered free. State officials are
negotiating with the Army Corps of Engineers about laying water
pipes to drought-stricken areas.
   Branstad said the cost to the state would be about $500 a day.
   Department of Natural Resources officials are still developing
plans to ship in water for livestock.
   Officials are checking quarries, gravel pits, abandoned wells
and other areas as possible sources of water, Branstad said.
   Although drought has struck several sections of the state, it
has hit hardest in southern Iowa where areas of several counties
have been declared disaster areas. Just before it adjourned, the
Legislature approved a $250,000 drought relief program that is
trigged when 15 counties are declared disaster areas.
   ``We recognize the problem is severe in these counties,'' said
Branstad.
</TEXT>
