<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Yugoslavia-Soldiers     05-08 0145</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Yugoslavia-Soldiers,0149</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nine on Trial for Alleged Nationalist Action</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nine soldiers went on trial Monday
on charges of trying to burn down the military academy in Belgrade
last year, the state Tanjug news agency said.
   The military prosecutor's office accused the soldiers of trying
to cause extensive damage to the facilities when they set the fire
in August, Tanjug said. The blaze was extinguished and damage was
minor, the agency said.
   The prosecutors also accused the soldiers of belonging to an
illegal Albanian nationalist organization that seeks to gain
control of southern Kosovo province and secede to join neighboring
Albania.
   Five of the soldiers are ethnic Albanians, who form a 90 percent
majority in Kosovo. Christian Serbs allege they are harassed by the
Moslem Albanians in the province.
   If convicted, the nine face a maximum prison term of 15 years.
</TEXT>
