<DOCNO> AP890508-0122 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-08-89 1705EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Tawian-China     05-08 0407</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tawian-China,0422</SECOND>
<HEAD>Taiwan Officials Return From Historic China Trip</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SHIRLEY LAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The first Taiwanese officials to visit
China stood for the communist nation's national anthem, but this
did not imply recognition of Beijing, a government official said
Monday.
   Finance Minister Shirley Kuo, who led the 12-delegate team, said
they stood because they feared they would ejected from the annual
meeting of the Asian Development Bank in Beijing.
   ``We did not pay any respect to the anthem at all. I even made a
gesture by crossing my arms to signal that I do not recognize
(China),'' Kuo told a news conference on her return Monday from the
three-day meeting.
   The action sparked controversy in Taiwan. Some lawmakers and
newspapers labeled it tacit recognition of the communist regime.
   Analysts say the six-day China trip is part of a Taipei
initiative to break its diplomatic isolation with a more flexible
foreign policy.
   In an editorial Monday, the China Times said the trip signaled
Taipei has readjusted its relations with Beijing by abandoning its
conservative, staunch political ideology to face reality.
   ``The breakthrough has not only won praises from this nation and
abroad, but also triggered worries and dissatisfaction from the
conservatives,'' it said.
   President Lee Teng-hui said Sunday the delegates completed their
mission successfully.
   The liberal Independence Evening Post reported Monday that 82.3
percent of 407 readers questioned said in a telephone survey they
were satisfied with the delegation's performance. Only 3.2 percent
of those polled said they were disappointed. The rest declined
comment.
   The Asian Development Bank, which Taiwan helped establish in
1966, is the only major international organization in which Taiwan
is a member.
   Only 23 countries have diplomatic ties with the Nationalist
government on Taiwan, while 136 countries recognize China.
   Taiwan boycotted the bank's meetings in 1986 and 1987 after
China became a member. It attended last year's meeting, but its
delegates covered their name plates with Nationalist flags and
placed signs that read ``Under Protest.''
   ``The trip is a significant step toward thawing the longtime
hostilities between both sides of the Taiwan Straits,'' said Chang
Ling-chen, a political science professor at National Taiwan
University.
   ``It indicated that we no longer ignore the fact of communist
rule on the mainland,'' she added.
   The Nationalists, who fled to this island in 1949 after losing a
civil war on the mainland, still are technically at war with the
Chinese communists.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
