<FILEID>AP-NR-05-08-89 1629EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>b a PM-SpaceShuttle 7thLd-Writethru a0628 05-08 0582</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Space Shuttle, 7th Ld - Writethru, a0628,0592</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shuttle Lands Safely After Sending Probe to Venus</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES with reason for runway landing. Minor editing. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE SIEGEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EDWARDS AIR FORCE BASE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Atlantis' astronauts
glided out of orbit to a safe landing in the Mojave Desert today
after a four-day mission that sent a robot spacecraft streaking
through the solar system toward Venus.
   Commander David Walker guided the 97-ton winged spaceship to a
stop on a concrete runway at 12:43 p.m., concluding a flight that
covered 1.68 million miles and launched the first U.S.
interplanetary mission in 11 years.
   ``Congratulations and a nice landing, and you've extended the
shuttle reach far beyond Earth orbit now. Magellan would be
proud,'' said Mission Control, referring to the 16th century
Portugese explorer for whom the unmanned Venus probe is named.
   About 27,500spectators, the smallest crowd ever to watch a
shuttle landing, were on hand in 90-degree heat. The smallest
previous crowd was 35,000, in 1985. An estimated 460,000 were here
for Discovery's landing March 18, a Saturday.
   An hour before landing, Walker fired braking rockets 184 miles
above the Indian Ocean to drop Atlantis out of orbit and start it
on a blazing dive through the atmosphere on a course over the
Pacific and across the California coast.
   Two sonic booms crackled over the desert as Atlantis swooped
powerless through the clear sky, making wide circles as it
descended. NASA selected a concrete runway because of crosswinds
gusting up to 28 mph on two hard clay runways.
   As the five astronauts ended the journey, the Magellan probe
they released on Monday was more than 640,000 miles from Earth on a
15-month, 800-million-mile voyage to Venus to map its cloud-veiled
surface with super-sharp radar.
   Scientists say the images should tell them about the history of
Venus and the evolution of its sister planet, Earth. Sulfuric acid
clouds and a carbon dioxide atmosphere have had a ``greenhouse
effect'' on Venus, with surface temperatures of 900 degrees, and
some scientists fear Earth may similarly overheat.
   On Sunday, the astronauts stayed up an hour past bedtime to stow
equipment after replacing one of its four main computers, which
failed briefly in the only major glitch of the journey. The
computers actually fly the shuttle most of the time.
   The problem posed no threat to the flight _ the shuttle has four
computers, a backup and a spare and can land on one computer _ but
NASA decided to take no chances and had the crew cut short their
experiments and install a spare.
   The crew took 4{ hours to install the computer and then got
about seven hours of sleep.
   ``We send our congratulations. Good work,'' said Mission Control
communicator Tammy Jernigan. ``We wanted to point out that this is
the first time that such a changeout has ever taken place on
orbit.''
   The astronauts' wake-up call this morning consisted of a barking
dog and the Beatles' song ``A Hard Day's Night,'' a reference to
the repair work the night before.
   ``Good morning. It's time to come home,'' Mission Control
communicator Ken Cameron told the crew, whose members also included
pilot Ronald Grabe and mission specialists Norman Thagard, Mark Lee
and Mary Cleave.
   The crew abandoned plans to melt and then crystallize a metal
sample in a furnace and to photograph lightning and polluted areas
on Earth.
   Before the problem, Walker noted, ``You couldn't ask for a
better flying machine.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
