<DOCNO> AP890508-0129 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-08-89 1751EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-US-Chirac     05-08 0481</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Chirac,460</SECOND>
<HEAD>French Conservative Opposes Elimination of US Nukes in Europe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALEXANDER G. HIGGINS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former French Premier Jacques Chirac on Monday
said the United States insist on modernizing short-range nuclear
missiles in Europe despite broad West German opposition.
   ``Nuclear deterrent is the only means to insure peace,'' Chirac
told reporters. ``For people to be sensible, they have to be
frightened. ... Anything that would lead to denuclearization is too
dangerous.''
   He said he thought Soviet President Mikhail Gorbachev would
succeed in his reforms, but that made no difference to the nuclear
question because ``we will never eliminate the risk of war.''
   Chirac, who met with President Bush on Monday, in in the United
States on a nine-day visit.
   The French conservative leader said he understood the fears of
West Germans about upgrading the Lance missiles, most or all of
which would be based on their territory.
   But, he said, West German Chancellor Helmut Kohl ``is a sensible
man, a European and a man of peace, and I am absolutely convinced
that he will find a way to have the modernization of the Lance
accepted by German public opinion and that there will be no crisis
in NATO.''
   ``Naturally,'' Chirac said, ``this means that the Americans must
be very firm.''
   He said he was fully in accord with Bush and with British Prime
Minister Margaret Thatcher that the missiles should be modernized
and that he didn't think West Germany would withdraw from NATO if
the alliance does build new weapons.
   ``There is absolutely no question'' that Mrs. Thatcher will
remain adamant in her support, Chirac said, adding that French
President Francois Mitterrand ``must also use his influence on the
Germans.''
   He recalled that, at Kohl's invitation, Mitterrand made a speech
in 1983 to the West German Parliament. The speech played a decisive
role in winning German agreement to the deployment of medium-range
U.S. Pershing 2 missiles in Germany, Chirac said.
   ``It's true that that today we do have the impression that Mr.
Mitterrand is less firm,'' he said, but added that he thought the
French president would in the end come out strongly for
modernization.
   Chirac said Mitterrand appeared to be showing restraint out of
concern for Kohl and because of his own policy toward the Soviet
Bloc, ``which perhaps would leave him to be more open that in the
past in negotiations.''
   ``I personally feel that he (Mitterrand) will be firm and in the
spirit of very deep friendship with the Germans he will make use of
his influence to support a solution which will lead to a
modernization of the Lance.''
   Kohl, Chirac said, ``is faced with serious domestic policy
problems. Naturally we don't want to interfere because this perhaps
might entail the risk of a Red-Green coalition, which certainly
wouldn't be an improvement of the situation from our point of
view.''
</TEXT>
