<FIRST>r i AM-Irish     05-08 0256</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Irish,0269</SECOND>
<HEAD>Masked Man Shot, Linked to Attack on Military Van</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A masked gunman demanded car
keys from a farmer and was shot in the face Monday, police said.
   Press Association, Britain's domestic news agency, said the
wounded man and a companion who also wore a mask apparently were
fleeing the scene of the explosion 20 minutes earlier.
   The bomb near Clogher, a small town 45 miles west of Belfast,
blew an unmarked military van onto its side and slightly injured
two soldiers. Police said the bomb may have been a land mine.
   Press Association said the masked men abandoned a motorcycle
close to the farm house outside Clogher and told the farmer to hand
over his car keys.
   The seriously wounded intruder was hospitalized.
   British Broadcasting Corp. television reported he was confronted
by a resident of the farm, who was carrying a shotgun. However, it
was not clear who that person was.
   Police provided no other details. They did not say who shot the
farmer and whether the other man escaped.
   A spokesman for the Royal Ulster Constabulary, speaking on
condition of anonymity, also said police had not identified the
wounded man or determined whether he belongs to the Irish
Republican Army.
   Soldiers have been a frequent target of the outlawed IRA in its
20-year campaign to end British rule in Northern Ireland.
   There was no immediate claim of responsibility for the van
attack.
   On Saturday, nine soldiers were injured in two separate
explosions in County Armagh, police said.
