<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-SBA     05-08 0455</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-SBA,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Small Firms Urged to Help With Child Care</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush on Monday challenged small
businesses to ``take the lead'' in finding more creative ways to
provide child care for working parents.
   He said small business ``is at the cutting edge of the economic
expansion that's 77 months old and still going strong.'' Small
businesses during the past decade have created two out of every
three new jobs in the U.S. economy, Bush said.
   The president spoke during a White House ceremony at which he
announced the selection of Tad Bretting of Ashland, Wis., president
of a family-run machinery business, as National Small Business
Person of the Year.
   He said the issue of child care ``should be on the top of the
list for all all small business people,'' claiming: ``A small
business is less a corporation than a family.''
   ``I urge America's small businesses to take the lead in
developing creative solutions in child care,'' Bush said.
   The president has proposed legislation to give low-income
working families up to a $1,000 tax credit for each child under age
4.
   However, rival legislation sponsored by Sen. Christopher Dodd,
D-Conn., under which the government would provide more direct help
to businesses and individuals providing child care, is headed for
Senate action.
   Bush indicated opposition to such an approach. ``I think it has
to be decided by the federal government making as flexible as
possible the use of child care tax credits,'' he said.
   Speaking of this year's award winner, Bush said Bretting had
entered the business in 1958, ``and those 30 years have seen the
Bretting Company grow adn prosper from 11 employees to 260 today,
from $120,000 in sales to $30 million.''
   ``And today his company is the world's leading producer of high
tech custom-designed machinery for making paper products,'' Bush
said. ``And the secret of Tad's success is the one small business
people know so well _ it all comes down to taking good care of
customers.''
   The business has been in Bretting's family since 1890, when it
produced machinery for sawmills.
   Bush presented Bretting with a plaque in a ceremony in the East
Room attended by other small business leaders and many of the 52
men and women who were in contention for the award.
   ``This room is full of success stories today,'' Bush said.
   The award is given annually by the Small Business Administration.
   Bush also announced other finalists in the competition,
including first runner-up Richard Barlow of Salina, Kans, president
of REMA Bakeware Inc.; and second runners-up Carolyn Stradley,
president of C&amp;S Paving Inc. of Marietta, Ga; and Chad H. Olson,
chairman of The Pro Image Inc., in Bountiful, Utah.
</TEXT>
