<FIRST>r w AM-HUD-Abuses     05-08 0551</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-HUD-Abuses,540</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Panel Told Blame for Abuses Goes Beyond What Investigator Reported</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BARKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A House panel asked former Housing and Urban
Development Secretary Samuel R. Pierce Jr. to testify so it can
evaluate statements by one of his associates Monday that the blame
for abuses in a federal housing program goes beyond what an
investigator has reported.
   Former federal housing commissioner Thomas T. Demery told the
House Government Operations subcommittee on employment and housing
that problems existed in a low-income housing rehabilitation
program before he gained the post in October 1986.
   Demery told the panel that one of his HUD predecessors, Silvio
Debartolomeis, had been reluctant to sign funding requests for the
so-called moderate rehabilitation program in 1986. Once, Demery
said, Debartolomeis left town rather than sign a funding request.
   Demery said a HUD inspector general's report two weeks ago with
his name on the cover was motivated by ``malice, negligence and a
cover-up, or a combination of the three'' by the inspector
general's office.
   He questioned why Deborah Gore Dean, former executive assistant
to Pierce, was mentioned only briefly in the 700-page report, even
though he considered her one of the program's major participants.
   Demery's statements that he has been ``singled out'' will be
assessed by the committee, which has asked Pierce to appear, said
panel member Christopher Shays, R-Conn.
   Demery ``is saying his direct predecessor had problems with the
program and just left town and had someone else sign. We need to
check that out, and it happened on (Pierce's) watch,'' Shays said
after the hearing.
   The inspector general's report two weeks ago alleged ``a
perception of favoritism'' in the awarding of funds to fix up
housing for the poor. HUD Secretary Jack Kemp shut down the program
temporarily and blocked some $100 million of pending contracts.
   Part of the problem was poor documentation in the
decision-making process, Inspector General Paul Adams told the
committee. Another, he said, was the volume of highly-paid
consultants _ many of them former HUD or other government officials
_ who used clout to win contracts for developers.
   ``Your view of the role of the consultant was really not one of
providing technical expertise, but of providing inside information,
privileged information, special access to the individuals who made
the decisions?'' subcommittee Chairman Tom Lantos, D-Calif., asked
Adams.
   ``Yes, sir, that's correct,'' Adams replied.
   The committee has asked former Interior Secretary James Watt to
testify about his work on behalf of a 312-unit project in Essex, Md.
   Watt earned a $300,000 fee despite indicating that he ``had
little if any knowledge of the program,'' Adams said. But Adams
said he knew of no instance where laws were broken by consultants.
   Most projects selected during the past five years were done
without open competition, and appeared to be concentrated in
Florida, Puerto Rico and a few other areas, Adams testified.
   But Demery said Florida and Puerto Rico simply had ``long
waiting lists'' and that other areas were also funded on the basis
of need. Still, Demery said he recognized problems with the
program, and sought in May 1988 to ensure the selection system was
fair and well-documented.
   He said he never stated or implied ``an ability on the part of
HUD to favor a specific project.''
</TEXT>
