<DOCNO> AP890508-0139 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-08-89 1917EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Army-Reserves     05-08 0539</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Army-Reserves,530</SECOND>
<HEAD>Study Says Army Relying More on Reserves</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Army has responded to budgetary
constraints by relying more on reserve units which are less capable
than regular forces, said a study released Monday.
   ``Because so many assets are in the reserve components, it is
not in particularly good shape to execute a worldwide `strategic
concept' of multiple contingencies,'' said a report written for the
Brookings Institution by analysts Martin Binkin and William
Kaufmann.
   Reserve units account for 43 perent of Army combat units and 70
percent of tactical support personnel, said the study by the
liberal think tank.
   ``Such a degree of dependence would not be a source of concern
if the reserve components came close to matching their active-duty
counterparts in capability and readiness. But they do not,'' said
the 162-page report, ``U.S. Army Guard and Reserve: Rhetoric,
Realities and Risks.''
   Traditionally, reserve units have been ``forces held in reserve,
with a cushion of time to complete mobilization and traiing,'' it
said. ``Today, many of the Army's reserve units are expected to
deploy along with the active forces, some with only a few days
notice and most of the remainder within weeks rather than months or
years as in the past,'' it said.
   ``Reserve units, both combat and support, would be among the
first deployed in a range of conflicts -- from fast-breaking
limited contingencies to major confrontation in Central Europe''
said the report.
   Under current plans, 40 percent of Army forces to be deployed in
the first month of a European war would consist of reserve forces,
it said.
   Reserve and National Guard units would make up 50 percent of the
service's force structure under the proposed Bush administration
budget for the 1990 fiscal year, Maj. Gen. Merle Freitag, director
of the Army budget office, told reporters on April 25.
   But the Army maintains that ``the reserve component question is
not directly related to our ability to fight on multiple fronts,''
said Army spokesman Lt. Col. John Chapla.
   The Army has acknowledged that ``we do not have a force capable
of doing everything in the world that we might face, so the ability
to fight on multiple fronts is a different issue,'' Chapla said.
   In an era of fiscal restraint, the Pentagon budget is expected
to shrink rather than expand, and the Army anticipates no reversal
of its growing dependence of reserve units.
   ``Our general position has been that the reserves play a very
vital role in any future contingency planning,'' said Chapla. ``Our
policy has been to equip units on a first-to-fight basis. In some
cases, that means that reserve units get equipment modernization
before some active units'' if the reserves are slated to go into
battle before the regular units.
   ``Of those divisions stationed in the United States slated for
deployment overseas, all of them have some kind of reserve compoent
round-out,'' said Chapla, explaining that one brigade, or about
one-third of the maneuver units in those divisions, consists of
reserves.
   Of the divisions that would be mobilized quickly in the event of
war, he said, the following front-line divisions have reserve
components: First Cavalry, Fourth Infantry, Fifth Infantry, Ninth
Infantry and 10th Mountain.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890508-0140 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-08-89 1910EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-FugitiveBanker     05-08 0461</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fugitive Banker,0475</SECOND>
<HEAD>Banker: Extradition to Greece Means Death</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHELLE LOCKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fugitive Greek tycoon accused in a banking
scandal that has rattled his Socialist government said Monday he
faces death at the hands of terrorist squads or secret police if he
is forced to return to his homeland.
   George Koskotas, 35, a former chairman of the Bank of Crete,
filed papers in U.S. District Court seeking to be released on bail
and fighting extradition to Greece, charging that senior officials
of the Greek government authorized plans to embezzle millions from
the bank and would kill him to ensure his silence.
   The $200 million scandal has embarrassed Greek Prime Minister
Andreas Papandreou's government, prompting the conservative
opposition to file a censure motion that was narrowly defeated in
Parliament.
   ``As the `Koskotas Affair' began to unfold in Greece last
October, Mr. Koskotas was given strong reason to believe that he
would be killed before he could give testimony incriminating the
(Greek) government and its leaders, including, in particular, Prime
Minister Papandreou,'' the petition said.
   A spokeswoman for the Greek Consulate in Boston declined to
comment on Koskotas' charges.
   Koskotas is being held without bail at a Salem jail pending the
extradition process.
   ``I am the one individual in the United States most
knowledgeable about the improper political motivations that the
PASOK government of Greece has in bringing charges against me and
in seeking my extradition,'' he said in court papers.
   Koskotas said he fled Greece for Brazil last November, ``because
I was informed that I would be killed either by terrorists or by
PASOK agents desiring my silence.''
   He left Brazil, he said, for the United States shortly after
that because he learned Greek secret police were dispatched to
Brazil with orders to kill him.
   Federal prosecutors say the reciprocal nature of international
extradition treaties demand cooperation despite the political
ramifications.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Victor Wild said Monday prosecutors
received the proceedings and will review them.
   ``We will be opposing his various motions,'' Wild said.
   A conference was scheduled May 17 before U.S. Magistrate Joyce
Alexander to discuss the extradition proceedings, he said.
   Papandreou, who is up for election in June, filed a libel
lawsuit against Time magazine last month over an article involving
allegations of financial wrongdoing at the bank that quoted
Koskotas saying he had passed millions from the Bank of Crete to
Papandreou and other government officials.
   Koskotas was arrested by FBI agents in Bedford last November
when he landed in a private jet with his wife and five children. He
fled Greece shortly before he was to face charges of forgery and
embezzlement.
   Meanwhile, the Bank of Crete has brought a civil lawsuit against
Koskotas seeking more than $100 million.
</TEXT>
