<FIRST>r a AM-Near-Collision     05-08 0279</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Near-Collision,0288</SECOND>
<HEAD>Small Plane Misses Jumbo Jet by Less Than 500 Feet Over Pacific</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The pilot of an Air New Zealand jetliner
carrying 350 people swerved to avoid hitting a twin-engine plane
that was less than 500 feet away over the Pacific Ocean, officials
said Monday.
   ``It was close,'' said Gary Mucho, regional director for the
National Transportation Safety Board, which was leading the federal
investigation into the near-collision at 7,000 feet.
   One passenger and one crew member, both male, aboard the Boeing
747 airliner suffered minor arm injuries as a result of the
near-collision about 5:30 p.m. Sunday, said an Air New Zealand
spokesman.
   Air traffic controllers told the Air New Zealand crew that
another plane was near it, ``and the Air New Zealand crew took
evasive action by making a left evasive turn,'' Mucho said.
   ``The other aircraft came within less than 500 feet,'' he said,
pinpointing the incident about 20 miles offshore over the Pacific
Ocean.
   Air New Zealand Flight TE6 from Auckland to Los Angeles was
traveling at about 7,000 feet when it had to bank sharply to avoid
a plane believed to be a Cessna, said the airline spokesman, who
declined to be identified.
   The other plane, which wasn't under the direction of air traffic
controllers, swerved to the opposite side. It wasn't identified,
Mucho said. Federal Aviation Administration and NTSB officials
spoke with the crew of the jetliner and were supplied with the
plane's flight data recorder and cockpit voice recorder.
   On Aug. 31, 1986, a small plane and an Aeromexico jetliner
collided near Los Angeles International Airport, killing 82 people
in the air and on the ground.
