<FILEID>AP-NR-05-08-89 1943EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Bennett-BootCamp     05-08 0640</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bennett-Boot Camp,620</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mixed Reviews For Bennett's Anti-Drug Proposal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal drug czar William Bennett's suggestion
that first-time drug offenders be sent to boot-camp style prisons
drew mixed reviews Monday from correctional experts.
   Prison experts said submitting offenders to rigorous programs of
military-style discipline and rigorous physical exercise might
teach self-control and discipline.
   But they disputed Bennett's assertion that such programs, aleady
being operated in Mississippi, Georgia, New York and several other
states, necessarily reduce the number of repeat offenders.
   Bennett's idea, however, drew support from one influential
member of Congress.
   ``I support the concept very strongly,'' said Rep. William
Hughes, D-N.J., chairman of the House criminal justice subcomittee.
``I don't think there is any question but that we've always
intended to develop alternatives.''
   Hallem Williams, head of the District of Columbia's corrections
department, said city officials have studied the idea and ``we
would not be averse to this as an option in the overall scheme of
things.''
   On the CBS News show ``Face the Nation,'' Bennett said Sunday he
was studying a proposal to encourage more states to set up ``boot
camp'' prisons for drug offenders as a cheaper, more effective
alternative to incarceration.
   ``It's inexpensive, it teaches good lessons and the recividivism
rate is very, very low because it so grueling and so unpleasant
people don't want to back to it,'' Bennett said.
   Jerry Miller, who heads the National Center for Institutions and
Alternatives in Alexandria, Va., questioned the research cited by
Bennett.
   ``There is almost no controlled research that shows they work,''
said Miller, who formerly ran youth corrections programs in
Pennsylvania and Massachusetts.
   While programs in Georgia and Mississippi programs claim high
success rates, ``they will put through such lightweight offenders
they generally tend not to be repeat offenders anyway,'' Miller
said.
   His comments were echoed by criminologist James Finckenauer of
Rutgers University in Newark, N.J., who said there isn't ``any
empirical evidence to support that it actually does what people
think it's going to do.''
   ``I would suspect if one looked at recidivism rates you are not
going to find any differences,'' Finckenauer said.
   In fact, the New York State Department of Correctional Services
says the recidivism rate among inmates who successfully complete
its boot-camp program is not any lower than among inmates who spend
two or three years in prison.
   But department spokesman James Flateau said that ``to the extent
you can compress a program into six months and be that successful
makes it a very successful program.''
   New York operates three camps that hold a total of 570 inmates
who are freed from the state prison system if they successfully
complete the six-month program, Flateau said.
   To qualify, an inmate must be serving a prison term of less than
three years for a non-violent crime, he said.
   ``Ours is definitely not a boot camp,'' said Flateau. ``Boot
camp by definition is a place of rigorous physical activity.''
   Besides physical activity ``there is an equal emphasis on
mandatory academic education and mandatory individual counseling
and group therapy for people with drug problems,'' Flateau said.
   ``You must complete all phases of it,'' he said.
   The legislature is considering a proposal to build more camps
and to extend the program to other inmates.
   Robert Gangi, director of the Correctional Association of New
York, gave the program high marks.
   ``The concept is good, but the key thing is to have the staff
dedication to make sure it works so that it doesn't become another
gimmick.''
   ``The key thing is that everybody in the progam, from the top
staff on down, is committed to rehabilitating the inmates,'' he
said ``That is not true of every other prison I have been into.
Most prisons see themselves as more or less warehousing people
until the time they are to be released.''
</TEXT>
