<DOCNO> AP890508-0147 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-08-89 1946EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Wallace-Truman     05-08 0503</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wallace-Truman,0519</SECOND>
<HEAD>Relative Remembers Life With Trumans On Harry's Birthday</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MELISSA CONTI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>INDEPENDENCE, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Harry and Bess Truman's white Victorian
house still stands, dish cloths still in the kitchen sink, his
beige trenchcoat and tan hat still hanging by the back door.
   And the 33rd president's sister-in-law remembers them and still
plays bridge as she did with Mrs. Truman.
   May Wallace, 94, moved to the house behind the Truman home with
her husband, George Wallace, in 1916. She remembers her trips to
Washington, time spent with Truman's daughter, Margaret, and the
president's honest nature.
   Mrs. Wallace recalled life with the Trumans in a recent
interview, before the annual observance marking Truman's birth on
May 8, 1884.
   Mrs. Wallace said Mrs. Truman, her husband's sister, was a
``cordial, good, sweet woman.''
   ``If somebody came along and tried to kid her, she wasn't in for
something like that,'' Mrs. Wallace said. ``She might wish you
weren't there but you wouldn't know it,''
   After the Trumans lived at the White House nearly a year, Mrs.
Truman invited 10 members of the Tuesday Bridge Club from
Independence to Washington. At the time, Life magazine reported
that the club's real business was to ``exchange menus, gossip, talk
about children, fashions, and husbands.''
   Mrs. Wallace isn't sure if she is the last remaining member of
the original bridge club, started by the president's wife when she
was a teen-ager.
   A White House employee once said Mrs. Truman would make more of
a fuss over her bridge club than she would over the social queens
of Washington.
   When the president's daughter, Margaret, was a child, she would
often come to the Wallace house for pre-dinner dessert. Aunt May
``Beufie'' and Uncle George ``Da'' would give her ice cream and by
dinnertime young Margaret's appetite was gone.
   When Margaret was older, the Wallaces took her to movies. ``The
Trumans didn't like to go out at night so Margaret used to sneak
out of the house,'' she said.
   The extended family converged on the Truman house at Christmas.
   ``One of my fondest memories of the `Big House' is the way the
big living room looked on Christmas morning,'' Mrs. Wallace said in
a handwritten statement for the National Park Service, which cares
for the Truman house. ``Margaret always insisted that the Christmas
tree be tall enough to reach the ceiling _ a 9-foot one at that.
   ``The tree trimming took place on Christmas Eve when all
gathered to help. Actually, my husband, George, and Margaret did
the real trimming with much comment from the sidelines.''
   Truman was thrust into the public spotlight in 1944 when he was
elected vice president. Just five months later, President Franklin
Roosevelt died and Truman became president.
   Mrs. Wallace said it was a difficult time for the Trumans, who
resisted attempts by the press and curiosity-seekers to invade
their privacy.
   ``It was hard to live. You had to be so careful about what you
say all the time,'' she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890508-0148 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-08-89 1947EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-AIDSVaccine     05-08 0382</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AIDS Vaccine,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Safety Tests Started In England On Third AIDS Vaccine</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Safety tests on a candidate AIDS vaccine will
begin soon in England, an American researcher announced Monday.
   Allan Goldstein, an AIDS researcher at the George Washington
University School of Medicine, said 24 volunteers are being sought
in London to test the safety of a vaccine known as HGP-30.
   The volunteers, he said, must be free of any AIDS infection. A
second 24, to be used as a control group, also will be selected.
   Goldstein said the purpose of the year-long trial is to
determine if the candidate vaccine is safe to use on humans.
Earlier tests on laboratory animals did not reveal any problems of
toxicity or other adverse effects, he said.
   Control trials in the United States have not started, Goldstein
said, because the drug has not been approved by the Food and Drug
Administration for human experimentation.
   HGP-30 is a synthetic copy of a protein that is part of the
internal structure of the human immunodeficiency virus (HIV), which
causes AIDS, or acquired immune deficiency syndrome.
   In laboratory tests, Goldstein said HGP-30 has been shown to
stimulate the production of antibodies which attack and kill both
the AIDS virus and cells in the body that are infected with the
AIDS virus.
   Two other vaccines, developed by other researchers, are also in
early safety trials, according to an FDA spokesman.
   The main advantage to the HGP-30 vaccine, said Goldstein, is
that the protein copy is based on a region of the HIV, called p17,
that does not change. The other vaccines are been based on proteins
in the envelope of the virus, a region that tends to change in a
process called ``genetic drift.'' Because of this change, vaccines
based on stimulating antibodies against the viral envelope may not
be as effective as HGP-30, he said.
   Developing the HGP-30 vaccine is still at a very early stage.
Goldstein said it will be at least a year before the start of any
clinical trials testing how well the vaccine actually prevents
AIDS. Those trials, he said, could last for years.
   Goldstein said it will be ``at least'' five to six years before
any AIDS vaccine is ready for general use and it could be much
longer.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
