<FILEID>AP-NR-05-08-89 1949EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-PentagonResearch 580   05-08 0598</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pentagon Research, 580</SECOND>
<HEAD>McDonnell Douglas Still Top DoD Research Company</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The McDonnell Douglas Corp. easily retained
its position as the Pentagon's top research contractor last year,
winning awards totaling almost $2.9 billion, the Defense Department
said Monday.
   The Martin Marietta Corp. ranked second for the second year in a
row with contracts totaling $2.03 billion, the Pentagon added.
   Among educational and non-profit entities, the Massachusetts
Institute of Technology continued to hold down the top ranking,
winning research contracts during the year worth $403.7 million.
The Aerospace Corp. of El Segundo, Calif., was close behind with
contracts worth $367 million, followed by the Johns Hopkins
University with $353.9 million.
   Overall, the Pentagon increased its spending on research by just
over 3 percent in fiscal 1988, with awards worth a total of $22.5
billion. By contrast, the department spent $21.8 billion on
research in fiscal 1987.
   A great deal of last year's spending appeared to be related to
work on the ``Star Wars'' anti-missile defense system. The amount
of money invested in research on ``missile and space systems''
totaled $7.8 billion in fiscal 1988, or 34.6 percent of the total,
the Pentagon said.
   Those numbers were little changed from fiscal 1987, when missile
and space systems research consumed $7.9 billion.
   The second-ranked program category was research on aircraft. It
consumed 22.4 percent of the total, or about $5.1 billion.
   The latest figures are contained in a statistical report
prepared annually by the Pentagon to rank the top 500 companies or
non-profit groups performing ``research, development, test and
evaluation'' work. The rankings are based on a review of all
contracts totaling $25,000 or more awarded during the fiscal year
that ended last Sept. 30.
   McDonnell Douglas, which earlier this year also claimed the
overall ranking as the nation's largest defense contractor, had
climbed into the top spot for research work in fiscal 1987 when it
displaced the Lockheed Corp.
   It widened its lead in fiscal 1988, with two of its units
ranking in the Top 10 on their own. McDonnell Douglas Aircraft held
down first place with $2.16 billion, while the parent McDonnell
Douglas Corp. received other contracts worth $664 million and
ranked in 8th place.
   Other McDonnell Douglas subsidiaries received $57 million in
research contracts, giving the entire corporation its total of
$2.88 billion.
   After McDonnell Douglas Aircraft and Martin Marietta, the
remainder of the Top 10 included the Boeing Co. in 3rd place with
awards totaling $878.7 million; Grumman Aerospace Corp., $843.4
million; Raytheon Co., $840.9 million; Rockwell International
Corp., $737.7 million; General Electric Co., $710.2 million;
McDonnell Douglas Corp., $664 million; TRW Inc., $658.7 million,
and Lockheed Missiles &amp; Space Co., $611.2 million.
   While Lockheed Missiles &amp; Space Co. ranked 10th, other Lockheed
units received awards worth $134.5 million, giving that entire
corporation a grand total of $745.7 million in fiscal 1988.
   The $403.7 million in research contracts won by MIT was enough
to give it the 15th ranking overall. In fiscal 1987, MIT had won
contracts worth $407.6 million and was ranked 11th overall.
   All told, the top 500 concerns accounted for 97 percent of the
total research contracts awarded, or $21.9 billion. The top 500
included 377 business firms; 103 educational and non-profit
organizations; three U.S. government agencies, and 17 foreign
contractors.
   That breakdown was little changed from fiscal 1987.
   The research awards to foreign concerns totaled $129 million, a
small increase compared to the $114.3 million reported in fiscal
1987. The leading foreign contractor was West Germany's
Messerschmitt-Boelkow Blohm, with awards totaling $27.2 million.
</TEXT>
