<FIRST>u a AM-AirlineSuit     05-08 0342</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Airline Suit,0351</SECOND>
<HEAD>Passengers May Sue Eastern For Mental Distress From '83 Flight</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: RETRANSMITTING a0675 to fix category code.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Passengers on a 1983 Eastern Airlines flight
forced to make an emergency landing after all three of the jet's
engines failed, have a right to sue for emotional injury, a federal
appeals court ruled.
   A lower court judge had ruled that Florida and federal laws did
not provide an avenue for the 25 plaintiffs to make a case. But the
11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals said the Warsaw Convention, an
international treaty drafted in 1929 that governs airline
liability, provides for such cases.
   The 11th Circuit, however, said the passengers may not seek
punitive damages.
   The case involves Eastern flight 855, which left Miami for
Nassau, Bahamas, on May 5, 1983. During the flight, one of the
plane's engines lost oil pressure. The crew shut it down and headed
back to Miami.
   During its return, the jet's other two engines failed and the
plane began to lose altitude. The crew told the passengers they
would have to ditch the plane in the Atlantic Ocean, the court said.
   The crew managed to restart one of the engines, and the plane
landed safely at Miami International Airport, court records show.
   Twenty-five of the passengers sued, contending they suffered
mental distress from the incident. Two of the passengers also
claimed physical injury.
   The Warsaw Convention sets terms under which passengers can seek
damages for problems related to air travel. It was accepted by the
United States in 1934. The original liability limit of $8,300 has
been amended several times to the current $75,000 per person.
   In its decision, made Friday but not released until Monday, the
11th Circuit said the Warsaw Convention takes precedence over local
laws.
   There has been considerable legal debate over whether the
language of the original document, drafted in French, provided
compensation for mental and emotional injury, the court said.
   The 11th Circuit concluded it did, saying it talked about
``personal injury'' rather than ``bodily injury.''
</TEXT>
