<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS lead of Madrid-dated first item to CORRECT spelling of
King Juan Carlos, sted Carolos</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   British rock singer Sting met Monday with
King Juan Carlos and Queen Sofia in his campaign to create a nature
reserve in the Amazon River basin.
   Sting led a delegation that included Brazilian Indian chief
Raoni and American Indian Sioux tribal leader Red Crow. The group
was midway through a 14-nation, 28-day tour to publicize the
campaign.
   Sting told a Spanish television network an Amazon nature reserve
would be a first step to curb the destruction of the rain forest
that generates a significant part of the world's oxygen.
   He denied news reports the group wanted to link any conservation
action by Brazil to concessions by Western creditor nations on
repayment of Brazil's $115 billion foreign debt.
   ``You can't trade debt for jungle. We are not giving money to
the Brazilian government. We're cooperating with the agency that
deals with the Indians _ buying boats, blankets, a plane,'' he told
the network TV-3.
   The group began its tour last month in Paris and plans to travel
to the United States, Japan and Australia.
