<FIRST>r w AM-TacticalWing     05-08 0334</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tactical Wing,330</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. to Pay Severance to Spanish as Base Closes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States, which agreed to Spanish
demands to remove 72 F-16 fighter bombers from Spain by 1992, will
pay severance to about 700 Spanish employees who worked at the
fleet's air base.
   Lt. Gen. E.S. Leland Jr., chief of staff of the U.S. European
Command, said Monday that under an agreement the State Department
negotiated with Spain, the United States will pay severance that
``at the very most'' could total $12 million.
   In light of Spain's pressure on the United States to remove the
jets and 3,600 U.S. troops and 600 civilians attached to the unit,
Sen. Alan Dixon, D-Ill., chairman of the Senate Armed Services
Subcommittee on Readiness, Sustainability and Support, said he
wouldn't blame Americans for feeling like fools in the deal.
   Leland said that at the time, the U.S. officials who negotiated
the agreement thought it was to the Americans' advantage. He also
reminded Dixon that there was a good chance the severance cost
would be less because the Spanish government will try to find other
jobs for the workers.
   In January 1988, the United States accepted Spain's demands that
the U.S. Air Force withdraw its 401st Tactical Wing from the joint
U.S.-Spanish air base at Torrejon de Ardoz, just east of Madrid.
   Italy has agreed to provide a new home base for the jets, troops
and civilians at Crotone.
   The cost of moving the 401st from Spain to Italy is estimated at
$830 million, with the North Atlantic Treaty Organization paying a
large share of the cost, said Cmdr. Mel Sundin, a Pentagon
spokesman. The United States is expected to pay about 28 percent of
the cost.
   Dixon questioned whether the United States could have saved
money by returning the jets and troops home. ``It looks to me like
a missed opportunity,'' the Illinois senator said.
   But Leland said NATO favored keeping the tactical wing in Europe.
</TEXT>
