<FIRST>u i AM-Lebanon 2ndLd-Writethru a0591 05-08 0768</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0591,0787</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shellfire Catches People Shopping; 16 People Killed, 53 Wounded</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 18 grafs to UPDATE casualties, details of damage.
Pickup 18th pvs, `The battle...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA ABU-NASR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   People slipped out of bomb shelters
Monday to get food and water during a lull in the fierce artillery
war, but Christian and Moslem gunners resumed shelling, killing at
least 16 people and wounding 53.
   The third day of fighting since a cease-fire collapsed raised
casualties in the two-month battle to 316 dead and 1,184 injured.
   Arab League envoys prepared to fly back to Damascus, Syria, and
Beirut to try to obtain compliance with the cease-fire called 11
days ago in the latest round of Lebanon's 14-year-old civil war.
   Police said 25,000 shells and rockets hit Beirut's Moslem and
Christian sectors from dusk Saturday to dawn Monday, then resumed
after a brief lull. The fighting escalated at dusk Monday.
   Shells blew gaping holes in scores of apartment buildings on
both sides of Beirut's sectarian dividing line. Hundreds of
burned-out cars smoldered in streets covered with debris.
   Shopkeepers banged down their shutters when the shooting started
and motorists sped away, blaring their horns at pedestrians
scurrying for cover. Police said streets emptied in less than 15
minutes.
   ``They've destroyed everything I own! I hope they roast in hell,
all of them!'' said Mahmoud Younis, 30, staring at his gutted
electrical shop in the Mosseitbeh district of Moslem west Beirut.
   Police said gunners of the Syrian army and allied Druse militia
pounded the coast around the ports of Jounieh and Byblos, blocking
the only escape routes for a million people who live in the
besieged Christian enclave north and east of Beirut.
   Christian gunners struck back with barrages of 155mm howitzer
fire aimed at seaside Moslem districts in Beirut and at the
airport, which was closed soon after the fighting began March 8.
Police said the Syrian fire came from those points.
   Lakhdar Ibrahimi, assistant secretary-general of the Arab
League, was expected in Damascus and then Beirut in an attempt to
salvage the truce called by the league April 28.
   He is accompanied by Brig. Gen. Ali Momen, the Kuwaiti commander
of a 321-man observer force to be drawn from six Arab nations to
monitor a cease-fire.
   An Arab League mediation panel made three earlier calls for
truces, but league official say this one is different because of
the provision for monitoring.
   Shells were fired only sporadically during a lull that settled
over the city at dawn Monday, but the pace quicked again before
noon, catching people in search of supplies. Shells and rockets
rained down on the city and resort towns in the mountains above
Beirut.
   One shell hit the building that houses the west Beirut office of
the British news agency Reuters. The staff reported extensive
damage but no injuries.
   Another crashed into the newsroom on the second floor of the
seven-story state TV station in the Tallet Khayyat district of West
Beirut.
   ``It was a miracle no one was hurt,'' said Leena Saidi, an
English-language announcer. ``We're now operating from the
station's bunker.''
   Several salvos exploded around the seven-story building that
contains offices of The Associated Press and the NBC and CBS
television networks in west Beirut's Hamra commercial district.
People in the offices fell to the floor and then crawled uninjured
into back rooms for shelter.
   The battle pits Gen. Michel Aoun and his 20,000 Christian army
troopers against an alliance of the Syrians and Druse militiamen
led by Walid Jumblatt. Syria has 40,000 soldiers in Lebanon under a
1976 peacekeeping mandate from the Arab League and has become the
country's main power broker.
   Fighting began two days after Aoun's forces blockaded illegal
harbors run by Moslem militias south of Beirut, which deprive
government ports of an estimated $100 million a year in customs
revenue.
   Jumblatt's men began shelling the 310-square-mile Christian
enclave. The Syrians soon joined them and sealed off the area with
the aid of Maj. Gen. Sami Khatib, who commands the 22,000 Moslem
army soldiers.
   Aoun declared a ``war of liberation to drive out the Syrian
occupation army.''
   Lebanon has had competing Christian and Moslem governments since
September, when the six-year term of President Amin Gemayel ended
and Parliament could not agree on a successor.
   He appointed Aoun and Moslems swore allegiance to Premier Salim
Hoss, who had served under Gemayel. A split in the army command
followed.
   Under an unwritten agreement since independendence from France
in 1943, Lebanon's president is Christian, the premier Sunni Moslem
and the parliament speaker Shiite Moslem.
</TEXT>
