<FIRST>r i AM-Iran-DeathCall     05-08 0322</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iran-Death Call,0337</SECOND>
<HEAD>Britain Warns Nationals to Leave Iran</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Foreign Office warned Britons Monday to leave
Iran because an Iranian official urged Palestinians to kill
Westerners to retaliate for Arab deaths in the Israeli-occupied
lands.
   The European Economic Community and the Netherlands on Monday
joined other Western nations that have already condemned the
Iranian statements. Those countries include Britain, the United
States, France and Israel.
   Iran's parliamentary speaker, Hashemi Rafsanjani, said Friday
that planes should be hijacked and five Britons, Americans or
Frenchmen killed for every Palestinian killed by Israel.
   The British Foreign Office said, ``We hold the Iranians directly
responsible for any actions taken against British or any other
nationals as a result of these remarks.''
   It said with the British Embassy in Tehran closed, it could
offer only ``extremely limited'' consular protection to its
citizens in Iran.
   It advised Britons to ``consider carefully whether their
continuing presence in Iran is essential.'' It also recommended
that Britons outside Iran not travel there.
   The Foreign Office said its warning was directed at 150 British
wives of Iranians living in Iran and 12 other British nationals
known to be there.
   In Madrid, the Spanish Foreign Office issued a statement for the
12-member EEC calling Rafsanjani's appeal ``absolutely
unacceptable.''
   The Dutch government called his remarks ``totally
reprehensible'' and urged joint EEC action. However, it announced
no concrete proposals.
   Earlier this year, the EEC nations recalled their ambassadors
from Tehran to protest Iran's call for the death of British
novelist Salman Rushdie. Many Moslems view his novel ``The Satanic
Verses'' as blasphemous.
   Most of the ambassadors, including the Dutch envoy, have since
returned to Iran.
   Both the EEC and the Dutch government applauded officials of the
Palestine Liberation Organization for joining in Western protests
of Iran's call for the campaign of terrorism.
   PLO-allied underground leaders in the occupied lands have
orchestrated many of the protests that led to Palestinian deaths.
</TEXT>
