<FIRST>u i AM-Israel 2ndLd-Writethru a0622 05-08 0615</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0622,0630</SECOND>
<HEAD>Israel Seals Off Territories; Israelis Stone Arab Cars</HEAD>
<HEAD>RETRANSMITTING a0695 to fix writethru sequence</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to include report of firebomb; picks up 3rd,
`Prime Minister...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel-Numbers, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Troops sealed the occupied lands Monday to
reduce the risk of violence in Israel during two national holidays,
and Jews angered by the killing of a soldier stoned Arab-owned cars.
   In Kiryat Malachi, police detained three teen-age Jews who threw
a firebomb at an Arab vehicle, Israel radio reported. It said the
device exploded on the road, causing no injuries or damage.
   Arab reports from the Gaza Strip said army gunfire wounded 11
Palestinians and soldiers injured three children with rubber
bullets, including an 11-year-old shot in the left eye. In the West
Bank, two Palestinians were reported wounded.
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir told Memorial Day ceremony Monday
night: ``Arab terrorism has reached new heights of violence and
murderousness against the Israeli people.''
   He accused leaders of the Palestinian uprising of escalating
violence to sabotage his election proposal for the occupied West
Bank and Gaza Strip. The uprising is entering its 18th month.
   Shamir wants Palestinians elected in the occupied lands to
negotiate a temporary peace settlement. The Palestine Liberation
Organization says elections only can be held after Israel withdraws
and as part of a comprehensive peace plan.
   The army clamped an indefinite curfew on 700,000 Palestinians in
Gaza Strip and barred 1 million West Bank residents from entering
Israel until Wednesday night. The restrictions were imposed to keep
Palestinians out during Israel's Memorial and Independence Day
holidays.
   Between sunset Monday and Tuesday, Israelis remember the 16,740
soldiers killed in wars with its Arab enemies. Celebrations marking
the 41st anniversary of Israel's independence begin sundown Tuesday
and end at sundown Wednesday.
   Earlier Monday, dozens of Israelis stoned Arab-owned cars along
the main coastal highway to protest the slaying of Avi Sassportaz,
a 21-year-old soldier whose body was discovered Sunday buried in a
field near the Gaza Strip.
   Before Sassportaz's funeral Monday, police fired tear gas to
disperse hundreds of residents from the soldier's hometown, Ashdod,
who burned tires in the streets and screamed: ``Death to the
Arabs!'' and ``No more Arabs in Israel!''
   Police arrested protesters from three vans, but stone-throwing
riots continued into the night, at one point involving hundreds of
residents, Israel Television said.
   Police warned against planned Tuesday protests.
   ``We will not permit any disturbances. We shall have forces that
will allow us to respond immediately and efficiently,'' said local
police commander Tuvia Golan.
   Thousands attended the funeral, including Defense Minister
Yitzhak Rabin and Maj. Gen. Dan Shomron, the chief of staff.
Journalists were barred by the family.
   In northern Israel, hundreds of Israeli Arab vacationers
abruptly left resort towns when the news spread that Sassportaz'
body had been discovered, a senior police commander said.
   The soldier disappeared Feb. 16 while hitchhiking home from his
army base. On Monday, more than 1,400 troops searched for a second
missing soldier, Ilan Saadon, 18, who last was seen Wednesday
hitching a ride in southern Israel.
   Police say they suspect Palestinians were involved in both cases.
   ``We are losing our patience,'' Gen. Yitzhak Mordechai, army
commander of the Gaza Strip, was quoted as saying by Hadashot
newspaper. ``We will take a heavier hand so they won't reach a
situation of making our lives intolerable.''
   In an editorial, Hadashot wrote: ``We are nearing the hour when
a society that feels itself threatened will choose its security
first, as in, `He who rises to kill you, kill him first.' We appeal
to the Palestinians, `Don't drag us to this moment.'''
</TEXT>
