<FILEID>AP-NR-05-08-89 2012EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Israel-Memorial 1stLd-Writethru a0679 05-08 0601</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Memorial, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0679,0615</SECOND>
<HEAD>Israel Mourns Soldiers Killed in Five Wars</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to ADD Herzog quote; picks up 7th, `The 24-hour...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A siren wailed for one minute Monday as Israel
mourned the 16,740 soldiers killed in its five wars with Arab
nations and in Arab guerrilla attacks on the Jewish state.
   Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin, in a letter to bereaved
families, urged them to carry on the struggle to defend the nation.
   ``I know that your nights are filled with nightmares and your
days lack the pleasures of life,'' he wrote. ``Still, I'm asking
you to persist for the sake of yourselves, your sons and daughters
who are no longer with us and, most of all, for future
generations.''
   The siren brought Israel to a standstill Monday night.
Pedestrians and motorists stopped in silent tribute. Restaurants
and movie theaters were closed and radios broadcast solemn music.
   Memorial Day officially began when President Chaim Herzog lit a
torch at the Western Wall, Judaism's holiest site, in the walled
Old City.
   ``On this day, we remember that we have paid the price of fallen
soldiers, of blood and suffering for the state of Israel,'' he
said. ``Let this memory be an order of unity for us, an order to
hate war and love peace. Let God give courage to His people. Let
God bless His people with peace.''
   A two-minute siren Tuesday marks the beginning of services in 40
military cemeteries and at the 50 monuments to fallen soldiers.
   The 24-hour mourning period will end with a ceremony at the
Mount Herzl cemetery in Jerusalem, burial place of many of Israel's
soldiers and founding fathers. This also marks the start of
Israel's 41st Independence Day celebrations.
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir, speaking at a ceremony in
Jerusalem, focused on the Palestinian uprising in the occupied
territories, saying that ``Arab terrorism has reached new heights
of violence and murderousness against the Israeli people this
year.''
   He said that ``courage, self-sacrifice and devotion'' of fallen
soldiers encouraged Israeli troops ``to repel the stone-throwers,
the firebombers... the mad murderers led by their hate of the
Jews.''
   To prevent possible Palestinian attacks over the holidays, the
army sealed off the occupied West Bank for 53 hours, beginning
Monday evening. The order barred all of the area's nearly 1 million
Palestinians from traveling to Israel.
   About 700,000 Palestinians living in the occupied Gaza Strip
were placed under an indefinite army curfew.
   Leaders of the Palestinian uprising called a general strike for
Tuesday to mark the beginning of the revolt's 18th month.
   At least seven Israeli soldiers have died in the conflict, as
well as 14 Israeli civilians and 465 Palestinians.
   The latest victim was Sgt. Avi Sassportaz, 21, whose body was
found Sunday a mile from the road junction where he was last seen
nearly three months ago trying to hitchhike home. Israeli officials
said Sassportaz was shot by Palestinian guerrillas.
   In Sassportaz's hometown of Ashdod, thousands turned out for his
funeral. Mourners later poured onto a main road and stoned
Arab-owned cars, and police arrested dozens of protesters,
witnesses said.
   ``The last year has not been good for us, and we paid a high, a
painful price,'' Rabin said in his letter.
   The army says 16,740 soldiers have died in Israel's five wars
and in guerrilla attacks, including 785 in the 1967 Middle East war
in which Israel captured the West Bank and Gaza. In Israel's last
war, the 1982 invasion of Lebanon and three-year occupation, 1,183
soldiers lost their lives.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
