<FILEID>AP-NR-05-08-89 2012EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Italy-Fascists     05-08 0225</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Italy-Fascists,0231</SECOND>
<HEAD>Neo-Fascists Gain in Local Elections in Alpine Province</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOLZANO, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The neo-fascist Italian Social Movement
strengthened its hold as the leading party in the capital of Alto
Adige province in the Alps, according to complete local election
returns Monday.
   It won 27 percent of the vote in Sunday's election, up 5 points
from the last city election in 1985. The party has tried to curb
the influence of German speakers in the province, once part of the
Austrian Tyrol.
   Finishing second was the South Tyrol People's Party, which runs
the provincial government, with 19.5 percent, down from 20.5
percent in 1985.
   Big gains also were posted by the Greens party, which runs both
Italian-speaking and German-speaking candidates. It got 12 percent
of the vote, up from 8 percent.
   German speakers outnumber those who speak Italian by
280,000-124,000 in the province, which was separated from Austria
at the end of World War I. Italian speakers are a majority in
Bolzano, however.
   The province is offically bilingual, but a quota system gives
the German-speaking majority the upper hand in jobs and public
housing. The Christian Democrats, Socialists and other mainstream
Italian parties lost votes in the Bolzano election.
   Bomb attacks blamed on German-speaking separatists marred the
provincial election campaign last year, but the city election
campaign this month was free of violence.
</TEXT>
