<FIRST>u w AM-US-Soviet 2ndLd-Writethru   05-08 0832</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Soviet, 2nd Ld-Writethru,860</SECOND>
<HEAD>US-Soviet Summit Not a Priority, White House Says</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: To update with comments from Baker, adds 3 grafs after 5th graf
previous, ``The White House</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<HEAD>AP White House Correspondent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The White House indicated Monday that a
superpower summit is not a high priority for Secretary of State
James A. Baker's talks in Moscow and said there is no guarantee his
trip will produce a date for resuming arms talks.
   Baker left Washington Monday and will arrive in Moscow on
Wednesday after a stop in Helsinki. He will see Soviet Foreign
Minister Eduard Shevardnadze Wednesday and again Thursday morning
and meet with Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev for two hours
Thursday afternoon.
   White House press secretary Marlin Fitzwater suggested Baker
would not even mention a summit without prompting from the Soviets.
   Fitzwater said Baker ``is willing to discuss a summit, should
that be raised by the Soviets and should he feel that it is
warranted by the circumstances at hand.''
   The White House spokesman said Baker ``goes there with an open
mind, but it's a first meeting, a chance to explore any number of
issues, and we just couldn't predict whether that would be an
outcome or not.''
   Baker, who arrived in Finland on Monday evening for a rest stop
before heading for Moscow, told reporters he intends to make clear
that the Bush administration is ``seeking an active, constructive,
positive and expanding relationship.''
   ``We want to test the (Soviet) new thinking across the full
range of our relations,'' Baker said. ``If we find that the Soviet
Union is serious about new global behavior, then we will seek
diplomatic engagement in an effort to reach mutually beneficial
results.''
   ``We recognized that there is real change taking place in the
Soviet Union,'' he said. ``We think this provides the United States
and the West with an opportunity.''
   Baker is expected to propose that U.S. and Soviet negotiators
resume talks the third week of June on a treaty to reduce
long-range bombers, missiles and submarines by 30 to 50 percent.
   The negotiations were suspended last November and were
tentatively set to resume in February. But the talks were put on
hold when Bush announced a review of policies toward the Soviet
Union and other issues.
   Asked if he expects Baker to reach agreement in Moscow on a date
for resuming talks, Fitzwater said he ``would not predict anything
that specific.''
   He said a review of the U.S. position on long-range nuclear arms
is not due for completion ``until probably June, July _ mid-summer
is the latest I've heard.''
   In recent weeks, the Bush administration has come under
increasing criticism for moving too slowly and cautiously toward
steps by Gorbachev to lower tensions, such as reductions in troops
and defense spending. The administration has questioned whether
those steps have done much to offset Warsaw Pact military
advantages in Europe.
   Reporting on the results of the foreign policy reviews,
President Bush will outline his position on the Soviet Union and
East-West relations in a speech Friday at Texas A&amp;M University.
   On May 21, Bush will deliver a speech at Boston University on
NATO and how the West should ``deal with the continuing threat from
the Soviet Union,'' Fitzwater said.
   The spokesman said Bush's speech Friday would talk ``in terms of
taking advantage of the changes that have been made under General
Secretary Gorbachev, would address the president's view of the
impact of glasnost (openness) and perestroika (economic reforms)
and talk about how the Western nations should define its
relationships with the Soviet Union in that changing political
climate.''
   Fitzwater acknowledged that the West will have to redefine its
relationship with Moscow.
   ``The United States, indeed all of the Western countries, have
had a certain attitude and a set of policies since World War II and
even before, based upon the Soviet threat,'' he said.
   ``There are a number of activities underway in the Soviet Union
which are changing the nature of our relationship with them.''
   Under Gorbachev, the West is discussing issues such as regional
conflicts, arms control and human rights ``with a degree of
openness that has not been possible in the past,'' Fitzwater said.
   He said it seems clear that ``we are at a point that suggests a
definition of a different relationship between the East and West''
from an economic, military and trade standpoint.
   On a related subject, Fitzwater said the presence of short-range
nuclear weapons in Europe is ``part of the equation that goes with
having our troops in Europe.
   ``There is no intention of changing that policy at this time,''
Fitzwater said. West Germany has called for negotiations with the
Soviet Union to curb short-range nuclear weapons, but the United
States has rejected the idea.
   Meanwhile, Jacques Chirac, the mayor of Paris and former French
prime minister, met with Bush and said later that Bush's opposition
to East-West talks on eliminating the short-range weapons was
widely supported by most European leaders.
</TEXT>
