<FIRST>r a AM-EdwardsCandidacy     05-08 0334</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Edwards Candidacy,0344</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Gov. Edwards Says He'll Run Again In 1991</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY COATES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Gov. Edwin Edwards, whose third
term was marked by his trial and acquittal of federal racketeering
charges, said Monday that he will seek a fourth term as the state's
chief executive in 1991.
   ``I can tell you that Buddy Roemer will not be the next
governor, so I decided to make the run,'' Edwards said of the
incumbent at an impromptu news conference at the Capitol.
   Asked why he was visiting the Capitol just over a week after
Roemer's tax revision package was rejected by voters, Edwards
replied: ``I'm going to tell the people `I told you so.'''
   ``This governor just wants to increase taxes,'' he said.
   Roemer was not available immediately for comment, said his press
officer, Sidney Coffee.
   Roemer's tax package was aimed at reducing a $700 million
deficit projected for the new fiscal year beginning July 1.
   Edwards, a Democrat, said he will again push for a lottery and
casino gambling, as he did in 1987 when he trailed Roemer in the
gubernatorial primary and bowed out of a runoff. Roemer had
campaigned calling for budget reductions, no new taxes and no
lottery.
   Pressure is mounting in the Legislature for a lottery but the
governor continues to oppose it.
   ``A lottery and casino gambling are the only answers in these
economic times,'' Edwards said. ``There are some long-range things
that can be done but the state needs something sooner, and not
taxes on the backs of the people.''
   Edwards, elected in 1971 and 1975, was constitutionally barred
from seeking re-election in 1979. In 1983, he defeated Dave Treen,
Louisiana's first Republican governor since Reconstruction.
   Edwards said he would open a campaign office in about a year.
   ``Right now, I'm handling volumes of telephone calls and mail,
strictly political things _ people wanting favors, advice and
counseling. I'm doing that out of my own pocket,'' he said.
</TEXT>
