<FILEID>AP-NR-05-08-89 2025EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Cambodia     05-08 0498</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cambodia,0518</SECOND>
<HEAD>Khmer Rouge Rejects Cease-Fire, Demands Dismantling of Government</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER ENG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TUAN SAI RIER, Cambodia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Khmer Rouge on Monday
rejected a cease-fire proposal, saying Cambodia's
Vietnamese-installed government must first be dismantled.
   ``We cannot accept a cease-fire that keeps in place a puppet
government,'' said Khmer Rouge leader Khieu Samphan. ``Once there
is is an international commission to supervise the Vietnamese
pullout there will be a cease-fire, not before.''
   Vietnamese troops invaded Cambodia in December 1978, ousted the
radical Khmer Rouge that had ruled for more than three years and
set up another communist government.
   Vietnam has said it will withdraw its estimated 50,000 to 70,000
military personnel from Cambodia by Sept. 30.
   Prince Norodom Sihanouk, head of a three-party resistance
coalition that includes the Khmer Rouge, held talks last week in
Indonesia with Cambodian Premier Hun Sen on the formation of a
provisional government.
   Khieu Samphan and Sihanouk spoke with reporters after a
diplomatic ceremony at a guerrilla base here in Cambodia's Siam
Reap province about a half mile from the border with Thailand.
   At the ceremony, ambasadors from China, North Korea and Senegal
presented their credentials to Sihanouk as president of the
coalition government.
   During the Indonesian conference Thai Prime Minister Chatichai
Choonhavan proposed that Sihanouk and Hun Sen agree to a cease-fire
before the Vietnamese withdrawal is completed.
   Sihanouk and Hun Sen agreed, but Khieu Samphan said Monday a
cease-fire could come only with the simultaneous dismantling of the
Hun Sen government. He said a provisional government ``should be
formed outside the framework of the two regimes'' _ the guerrilla
coalition and Hun Sen government.
   Sihanouk had no immediate comment on Khieu Samphan's rejection.
   Hun Sen opposes Khmer Rouge participation in any new government.
   The Vietnamese communists and Khmer Rouge came to power in the
spring of 1975, defeating U.S.-backed governments in South Vietnam
and Cambodia.
   It is estimated that under Khmer Rouge rule more than 1 million
people in Cambodia's population of 8 million were executed in
purges or died of starvation.
   Sihanouk leads the resistance coalition but the Khmer Rouge,
with as many as 40,000 combatants, is far stronger than the other
two members _ Sihanouk's supporters and the non-communist Khmer
People's National Liberation Front.
   Sihanouk, who has condemned the Khmer Rouge atrocities, said
that in Indonesia Hun Sen suggested they join forces to defeat the
Khmer Rouge.
   Sihanouk on Monday did not rule out that possibility and said he
would decide by November.
   But he also said as long as Vietnamese troops remain in Cambodia
he would insist that Hun Sen allow the Khmer Rouge a place in a
four-party provisional government.
   He said he was insisting on a four-party government ``not as an
accomplice of the Khmer Rouge but because I have to be realistic.''
   ``To make them (the Khmer Rouge) bandits and rebels would be the
worst solution for a post-Vietnamese Cambodia,'' Sihanouk said.
``What I fear most is a civil war.''
</TEXT>
