<FILEID>AP-NR-05-08-89 2026EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Nicaragua-Soviet     05-08 0361</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nicaragua-Soviet,0370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Moscow to Keep Sending Weapons to Nicaragua, Officials Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARLOS A. SANDI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN JOSE, Costa Rica (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Moscow will keep supplying
Nicaragua's leftist Sandinista government with weapons as long as
the United States sends arms to other Central American nations, two
Soviet diplomats here said Monday.
   ``Nicaragua would be at a disadvantage if all the region
continues getting weapons and Nicaragua doesn't. You must remember
that Honduras is practically a North American base in Central
America,'' said Yury Sajnin, political counselor at the Soviet
Embassy in the Costa Rican capital of San Jose.
   ``With Nicaragua we have diplomatic relations and agreements,
and these include supplying weapons, even though armament shipments
have been reduced,'' said Vadim Rozanov, the Soviet ambassador to
Costa Rica.
   They spoke at a news conference in the Soviet Embassy called to
commemorate the 45th anniversary of the establishment of diplomatic
relations between the Soviet Union and Costa Rica.
   Rozanov said Moscow ``believes the conflicts in Central America
should be solved by the Central Americans themselves, without
outside interference.''
   He said the Soviet government supports a peace effort undertaken
in 1987 by the presidents of Costa Rica, El Salvador, Honduras,
Nicaragua and Guatemala.
   ``The Soviet Union is willing to respect the agreements reached
or to be reached by the Central American governments and to
contribute to a peaceful solution to the conflicts in the area,''
Rozanov added.
   The peace initiative, begun by President Oscar Arias of Costa
Rica, seeks a negotiated end to the civil war between the
Sandinista government and U.S.-supported rebels, known as Contras,
who are based in Honduras. It also seeks negotiations to end
rebellions in El Salvador and Guatemala and calls for
democratization in Central America.
   The five regional presidents have met periodically to advance
the plan. To date, the Sandinistas and Contras have achieved a
tenuous cease-fire, while Nicaraguan President Daniel Ortega has
called for national elections in February 1990.
   Rozanov rejected a recent accusation by Salvadoran
President-elect Alfredo Cristiani that the Soviet Union supplies
aid to that country's leftist insurgency. ``No one has proof of
that. It is a deception of public opinion,'' he said.
</TEXT>
