<FILEID>AP-NR-05-08-89 2016EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     05-08 0418</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0428</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thunderstorms In Central Part of Nation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Thunderstorms developed Monday over the central part of the
nation, with showers scattered elsewhere, after a morning of record
low temperatures scattered across the Southeast.
   Light snow was scattered over parts of upstate New York a day
after 10 inches fell in Rochester, N.Y.
   Thunderstorms developed along and ahead of a warm front and
produced hail and locally heavy rain over parts of Kansas and
Missouri, and drifted into northern Arkansas.
   One thunderstorm produced hail an inch in diameter during the
morning southeast of Kansas City, Mo., in the suburb of Lee's
Summit. Afternoon thunderstorms caused hail in Arkansas.
   A cold front pushing southeastward across the central part of
the nation was expected to trigger thunderstorms in the warm, moist
air over the south-central states.
   Showers were scattered across the upper Mississippi Valley and
the northern Atlantic Coast, and across the northern Rockies and
the northern high Plains.
   These record and record-tying lows were reported by the National
Weather Service: Asheville, N.C., 28 degrees; Athens, Ga., 37;
Augusta, Ga., 36; Beaufort, S.C., 43; Bristol, Tenn., 30;
Charleston, S.C., 45; Charlotte, N.C., 35; Cincinnati, 33, tie;
Columbia, S.C., 35; Evansville, Ind., 38, tie; Greensboro, N.C.,
32; Greer, S.C., 31; Hollywood, Fla., 55; Jacksonville, Fla., 48;
Macon, Ga., 42; Montgomery, Ala., 45, tie; Paducah, Ky., 39;
Raleigh, N.C., 36; Savannah, Ga., 43; Tallahassee, Fla., 42; and
Wilmington, N.C., 38
   But in Texas, Lubbock hit a record high of 99 degrees and
Midland tied its record of 103.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 37
degrees at Bradford, Pa., to 106 at Gila Bend, Ariz., and Palm
Springs, Calif. Monday's low for the 48 contiguous states was 24 at
Gunnison, Colo.
   For Tuesday, showers and thunderstorms were forecast from
Georgia, the Carolinas and the middle Atlantic Coast states into
Kansas, Oklahoma and Texas. Scattered showers were forecast across
Maine, and across the Pacific Northwest.
   Highs in the 50s were predicted across the Great Lakes region
and the northern Atlantic Coast states; in the 50s and 60s from the
middle and upper Mississippi Valley to the middle and northern
Atlantic Coast states; in the 60s along much of the Pacific Coast;
in the 80s over much of the rest of the West, and from Florida and
southern Georgia to Louisiana; in the 80s and 90s in Texas; and in
the 90s or above 100 over southern sections of California, Nevada,
Arizona and New Mexico.
</TEXT>
