<FIRST>r a AM-TVNews 1stLd-Writethru a0676 05-08 0338</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-TV News, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0676,0344</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former CBS News President Criticizes Networks Coverage</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 5th graf, `In less...,' to CORRECT bureaus closed to Warsaw
and Bangkok; picks up 6th graf, `But Turner...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RADNOR, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   News coverage by television networks has been
deteriorating, while Ted Turner's Cable News Network is improving,
a former CBS News president said.
   Ed Joyce, who headed CBS News from 1983 to 1986, critiqued
current news coverage in the May 13 TV Guide magazine.
   The three broadcast networks changed owners in the past four
years, and the ``big losers'' in those transactions have been
television viewers who have depended on network programs as their
primary source of news, Joyce contends.
   The networks' ability to provide adequate news coverage ``has
been sacrificed to protect bloated stock values,'' he wrote.
   In less than 18 months, CBS dismissed one-third of its news
staff and closed bureaus in Warsaw and Bangkok to cut costs, Joyce
said. NBC and ABC made similar reductions.
   But Turner tightened CNN's budget in other ways and in December
announced the addition of seven new foreign bureaus, bringing CNN's
total to 18, Joyce wrote.
   For decades, the broadcast networks have made decisions on what
is major news based on where their foreign bureaus are located,
Joyce said.
   ``Labor unrest _ say, a miners strike _ in England, where each
network has a large bureau, is news. A similar story in Santiago
(Chile), where they don't have bureaus, is not.''
   The broadcast networks' cutbacks are predictable, he said,
because they are no longer being run by entrepreneurs but by people
who view them as investments. As such, network decisions are based
on the minimum risk factor, whereas Turner's strategy is surrounded
by the aura of risk.
   ``If Ted Turner can maintain an expanding global news service,
he deserves applause and a measure of gratitude,'' he said.
   ``For the networks, the failure to preserve their news franchise
is a colossal blunder. They are creating a situation in which they
will become increasingly irrelevant.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
