<DOCNO> AP890508-0170 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-08-89 2047EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Peru 1stLd-Writethru a0692 05-08 0552</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Peru, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0692,0567</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sanchez Appointed Prime Minister</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADD 10 grafs UPDATING with Garcia quotes, new violence. No pickup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Armando Villanueva resigned as prime minister
on Monday and was replaced by Vice President Luis Alberto Sanchez
as criticism of government anti-insurgency policies increased.
   Sanchez, who is 88 and nearly blind, is also a senator and is
one of Peru's most respected political figures. Despite his age,
Sanchez frequently travels abroad on state business, participates
regularly in Congress and plays a leading role in the internal
affairs of the center-left Aprista Party.
   The government said President Alan Garcia's entire 15-minister
Cabinet also submitted resignations, as is customary when a prime
minister quits.
   A Peruvian prime minister is not as powerful as in a
parliamentary system such as Britain or Canada, where the position
is the highest government post in the nation.
   Sanchez will keep both his senate seat and his vice presidential
post, which is largely ceremonial.
   Garcia is expected to replace some Cabinet members to more
effectively combat Peru's economic and insurgency woes.
   Villanueva, who also quit his interior minister's post, said a
recent increase in terrorism, including the assassination of two
congressmen in 10 days, prompted the resignation.
   Peru has fought a leftist insurgency by the Mao-inspired Shining
Path guerrilla group for nine years. More than 14,000 people have
been killed, including about 1,000 so far this year.
   Sanchez is the fourth prime minister of the Garcia government,
which holds power until July 1990. Critics said Cabinet changes
have not had much impact because Garcia is the dominant personality.
   Garcia on Monday called Sanchez a national institution who has
``the prestige and knowledge ... to unite us in two fundamental
areas: the fight against subversion and to reactive the economy.''
   Garcia, a populist, took office in July 1985 for a five-year
term. After two years of prosperity, the economy has entered a deep
recession. Analysts said the economic and insurgency problems
undermine Peru's democracy.
   Shining Path guerrillas killed seven people in attacks that also
left two rebels dead, police at Huancayo, 140 miles east of Lima,
said Monday.
   Also Monday, more than 200 soldiers swept through the state-run
University of Huancayo, seeking leftist guerrillas and hoping to
defuse a planned `armed strike,' reporters and school officials
said.
   They said 10 students were detained. Security forces call the
school a haven for rebels.
   A band of guerrillas shot and killed two police guards early
Monday at a dance in a jungle village near Satipo, 200 miles east
of Lima, then entered the dance and killed one man, Huancayo police
said.
   In the highlands, two policemen, two Shining Path guerrillas and
a civilian were slain when rebels Sunday night attacked a police
post in Huariaca, a village about 135 miles northeast of Lima,
police said.
   In La Oroya, 95 miles northeast of Lima, Shining Path assassins
shot and killed a mining labor leader Monday on a city street,
police said.
   A note left by the body demanded that people in the region
surrounding Huancayo join a three-day armed strike set to begin
Wednesday, police said.
   The Shining Path began armed strikes about a year ago as a tool
to foment economic chaos. The strikes carry with them the threat of
violent reprisal against anyone not participating.
</TEXT>
