<HEAD>Philippines Economic Recovery Loan Announced</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The World Bank said Monday it has approved a
$300 million loan for the Philippines aimed at strengthening its
economy by revamping the commercial banking system.
   The funds will be disbursed in two $150 million installments,
one shortly and the second after the government carries out agreed
reforms in trade, tax, agricultural and administrative policy, the
World Bank said.
   The new loan is for 20 years at a variable interest rate,
currently 7.65 percent.
   The World Bank gave the Philippines a $300 million economic
recovery loan in March 1987 and a $200 million loan for reforming
government corporations last June.
