<HEAD>Envoys Testify They'll be Alert to European Arms Exports</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush's ambassadors-designate to
France, Italy and Sweden assured senators Monday they will keep
alert to arms sales from those European countries to the Third
World.
   The United States has been concerned about the supply of weapons
to developing countries, prompting questions at the Senate Foreign
Relations Committe's hearing on the nominations of Walter J.P.
Curley as ambassador to France, Charles E. Redman to Sweden and
Peter Secchia to Italy.
   Redman said the Swedish record is overall a good one and Sweden
tries to avoid sending arms into areas of tension and conflict.
   The Italian government has committed itself to tightening
restrictions on arms exports, Sechhia said.
   Curley said France, a big arms exporter, has a special
relationship with Iraq and its control over and monitoring of
weapon supplies to French-speaking African countries has been
``quite tight.''
   Sen. Claiborne Pell, D-R.I., chairman of the panel, said he
intends to move quickly on the nominations of Secchia and Curley so
that they can be in their new posts when Bush visits Europe later
this month.
   The committee will likely report the three nominations to the
Senate floor Wednesday, he said, with action probable by the end of
this week.
