<FIRST>r i AM-Yugoslavia     05-08 0473</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Yugoslavia,0491</SECOND>
<HEAD>Huge Rally Protests Military Trial of Three Journalists</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SLOBODAN LEKIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LJUBLJANA, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 30,000 Slovenians marched
through downtown Ljubljana on Monday night protesting the trial by
a military court that sentenced three journalists and a soldier to
prison.
   The four were convicted in July of making public a classified
military document and were given sentences ranging from 10 months
to four years.
   The defendants contended the document outlined illegal military
actions planned against political activists in Slovenia, considered
to be the most liberal of Yugoslavia's six republics.
   Protest organizers accused Slovenian officials of bowing to army
actions.
   Participants in the peaceful two-hour march carried banners
saying, ``Freedom for the four means freedom for all of us,'' and
``Against militarism _for human rights.''
   The rally was called by newly formed opposition and human rights
groups.
   Speakers at the rally denounced military leaders and Communist
Party conservatives, saying they used the four defendants as
scapegoats in a political attack on Slovenian liberals.
   ``We demand a revision of the judicial process ... and we want
this farce to be declared null and void,'' said Joze Skolc, head of
the official Youth Forum.
   France Tomsic, leader of the new Slovenian Social Democratic
Party, said, ``An end must come to meddling in civilian affairs by
Yugoslavia's ... Soviet-style Stalinist army.''
   Earlier Monday, students at Ljubljana University voted to begin
on Thursday a boycott of classes to protest the military trial.
   One of the defendants, Janez Jansa, was taken to the Dob
penitentiary Friday after he failed to win a reversal of his
18-month sentence.
   Jansa and Franci Zavrl, editors of the Mladina youth weekly,
were sentenced to 18 months and David Tasic, a Mladina reporter,
was given a 10-month sentence. Sgt. Maj. Ivan Borstner, who is to
report to the Dob prison on May 16, was sentenced to four years.
   Zavrl and Tasic are still appealing their sentences.
   A special commission set up by Slovenia's Parliament to study
the document obtained by the defendants said some of the military
outlines it contained were ``illegal and unconstitutional.'' But it
said because the document is still classified it could not specify
what plans were contrary to Yugoslav law.
   In another development, Slobodan Milosevic was elected president
of Serbia by a unanimous vote in Parliament. Milosevic, who had
been the republic's Communist Party chief, was unopposed.
   Under Yugoslavia's system of annual rotation of key political
officers Milosevic had to resign his party post to become president.
   As party leader Milosevic led the campaign to gain more control
over Serbia's provinces of Vojvodina and Kosovo, which have ethnic
Albanian majorities.
   At least 24 people were killed in battles between ethnic
Albanians and police in March after Serbia's Parliament approved
constitutional amendments giving Serbia more control over police
forces and education in Kosovo.
</TEXT>
