<FIRST>u i AM-Panama-Scene 1stLd-Writethru   05-08 0594</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Panama-Scene, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0619,0612</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gunshots, Beatings Accompanied Vote Count, Witnesses Say</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: SUBS 3rd graf, `The soldiers...'</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   to CLARIFY that San
Miguelito is suburb, sted district.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>With AM-Panama, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>BY ELOY O. AGUILAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN MIGUELITO, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It was 3 a.m., and the vote tallies
were showing the opposition winning by a lopsided margin, poll
watchers said. Then the soldiers came.
   ``They fired a few shots and everybody scattered, everybody ran
and jumped through fences and sought refuge in nearby homes,'' said
Marcos Herrera, an opposition poll watcher who was in the gymnasium
where the votes were being tabulated Monday.
   The soldiers beat a few stragglers and seized most of the tally
sheets from the Panama City suburb of San Miguelito, where more
than 120,000 of Panama's 1.18 million voters were registered for
Sunday's presidential election.
   But the raid was not thorough. Scores of sheets were left on the
floor of the gym; some were still in the polling stations' large
yellow envelopes.
   All sheets examined by an Associated Press reporter showed a
clear lead, often by more than 3-1, for opposition candidate
Guillermo Endara over Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega's hand-picked
candidate, Carlos Duque.
   It was a brazen show of force in an election that the opposition
claimed already had been rigged by Noriega, commander of the
Panamanian Defense Forces commander and the country's de facto
ruler.
   ``You should not be surprised about this,'' said a man sitting
on the porch of his home near the gymnasium. ``This is that they
did in 1984,'' when the govenrment also was accused to rigging the
elections.
   Similar instances of tally sheet seizures took place throughout
the nation.
   It was not known where the soldiers took the sheets. But the
national tabulation board announced Monday morning it had not
received tallies from any of the 40 electoral districts.
   Said Elizabeth Escobar, whose house is about 50 yards from the
gym:
   ``A man who said he was bringing a tally sheet came running into
the house and gave it to me, saying `Hang on to this, we'll be back
to pick it up later.'''
   She showed the tally sheet of precinct 3655 and other
documentation to journalists. Endara had beaten Duque, 121-41.
   A member of the Defense Forces and a policeman watched
journalists as they walked into the gymnasium. An hour later the
doors to the gym were locked.
   ``Talk to the neighbors if you want to know what happened,'' an
officer said.
   A few blocks away government sympathizers gathered in a
politician's office. Victor Schailer, an alternate candidate for
the National Assembly, said he had not heard about the attack on
the gym.
   ``If anything happened it was probably the result of the flow of
adrenaline and the emotions of people,'' he said, adding he had not
heard any shots fired.
   When told of the scene at the gym, with ballots scattered on the
floor, Schailer said he would have to confirm it himself.
   At a news conference in Panama City, European and U.S. election
observers expressed concern.
   Voting was peaceful until 5 p.m. Sunday, when the polls closed,
said Fernando Suarez Gonzalez, a Spanish member of a parliamentary
observer group. ``Our doubts begin at five.''
   Angry residents of San Miguelito, a working-class suburb,
gathered in knots on the street Monday and vented their
frustrations at some foreign journalists.
   ``You were here in the morning'' shouted one man, referring to
Sunday, when former President Jimmy Carter visited the area.
``Where were the international observers, where were you, when the
soldiers came in?''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
