<HEAD>World Bank Aiding New Phase of Krishna Water Project</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The World Bank said Monday it will provide
$325 million in loans for an ongoing water project in India's
Karnataka state.
   Indian central and state governments and private institutions
are also providing $217 million for the second phase of the Upper
Krishna River Irrigation Project in the southern India state.
   The World Bank funds will help pay for surveying, road
construction, training, land distribution, relocation allowances,
community service facilities and dams and canals for nearly 370,500
acres of drought-prone farmland.
   The World Bank said it will lend $165 million at a variable
interest rate that is currently 7.65 percent, and provide $160
million interest-free through its International Development
Association affiliate.
   An earlier phase of the Upper Krishna project has irrigated
100,000 247,000 acres, and future stages are planned to bring the
total land under irrigation to 2.47 million acres.
