<FIRST>u a AM-WinerySlayings     05-08 0347</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Winery Slayings,0363</SECOND>
<HEAD>Toddler Who Survived Throat Slashing Doing Well</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto PETX1</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PETALUMA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A toddler whose throat was slashed in a
rampage that killed seven people is making a strong recovery and
``throwing temper tantrums'' like a normal youngster, her doctor
said Monday.
   Carmina Salcido ``is behaving like any 3-year-old,'' Dr. Ralph
Keill said at a news conference outside Petaluma Valley Hospital
about 30 miles north of San Francisco.
   Carmina, who is in good condition, has been ``playing, pouting
and throwing temper tantrums'' like a normal youngster, Keill said.
   The girl, recovering from her throat slashing, talks in a
whisper, said hospital spokeswoman Mary Frost.
   ``It sounds pretty good to us,'' Frost said, adding that Carmina
is expected to be discharged within two weeks.
   Carmina leaves the hospital for walks and rides on her new
tricycle, and has gone on an outing with her grandfather, Robert
Richards, officials said.
   The youngster was discovered in a trash heap on April 15, her
throat slashed from ear to ear and left for dead next to the bodies
of her slaughtered sisters, Sofia 4, and Teresa, 1.
   Carmina was the only survivor in the killing spree that also
took the lives of her mother, Angela, 24; her grandmother, Marian
Richards, 47; two of her daughters, Marie, 8, and Ruth, 12, and
winery co-worker Tracy Toovey, 35. They were shot, beaten or
stabbed to death on April 14.
   Carmina's father, Ramon Salcido, 28, was captured in Mexico and
deported to California to face multiple murder charges. He pleaded
innocent to the crimes and is in solitary confinement in the Sonoma
County Jail.
   Carmina's recovery has been eased by a bounty of toys she
received from the public after the ordeal, hospital officials said.
   ``Carmina has been lovingly cared for by the nurses in the
intensive care unit,'' Keill said. ``We have worked closely with
Carmina's grandfather, Mr. Richards, and with (Sonoma County) Child
Protective Services in making decisions regarding her care.''
   Richards has asked the Child Protective Services to allow him to
become the girl's legal guardian.
</TEXT>
