<FILEID>AP-NR-05-08-89 2208EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Panama-Observers     05-08 0607</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Panama-Observers,0633</SECOND>
<HEAD>Carter Says Noriega Stealing Election</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Panama, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Ancel cq in byline</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANCEL A. MARTINEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega is
stealing Panama's presidential election for his own candidate by
substituting phony vote counts, former President Jimmy Carter said
Monday.
   ``I hope there will be a worldwide outcry against this dictator
stealing this election from his own people,'' said Carter, who came
to Panama as an independent observer at the government's invitation.
   A delegation of U.S. observers named by President Bush made less
dramatic charges of irregularities in Sunday's election. The
delegation said it concluded that Noriega's soldiers intimidated
voters and carried out widespread fraud.
   Carter's charges appeared to support those of opposition
leaders, who said soldiers raided voting stations nationwide and
stole tally sheets.
   The opposition said Noriega, Panama's de facto leader, ordered
the move to prevent his candidate, Carlos Duque, from losing to
opposition candidate Guillermo Endara.
   Carter told a news conference he was permitted to examine vote
tallies at the election center and determined they were counterfeit.
   He said the military seized thousands of tally sheets in a
nighttime sweep.
   ``During the day, those records have been discarded and
counterfeit documents have been substituted,'' said Carter.
   He said the documents at the election center were not signed by
opposition poll watchers, while all sheets had been signed before
leaving polling booths.
   The tally sheets contain numbers based on a count of ballots,
which are burned afterward to prevent tampering.
   Carter said the Panamanian government stopped cooperating with
his mission as soon as he raised the issues. His news conference
was held in a hotel lobby as a crowd of Noriega supporters jeered
outside.
   At a separate news conference at the officers' club at Albrook
Air Force Base, the chairman of the official U.S. delegation, Rep.
John Murtha, said his group could not certify that the election was
``free and fair.''
   Murtha, D-Pa., said the archbishop of Panama, Marcos McGrath,
told him a church exit poll indicated the opposition won in a
landslide.
   ``This election was a terrible fraud on the Panamanian people,''
said one delegation member, Rep. Larry Smith, R-Fla.
   The 13 U.S. observers said they witnessed fraud firsthand,
watching individual Panamanian Defense Forces soldiers voting in
more than one precinct around the capital.
   Noriega is chief of the Defense Forces.
   The Panamanian Committee for Human Rights, which invited 279
observers from 21 nations, also branded the election as fraudulent.
   The committee said the military intimidated voters and tampered
with precinct tally sheets. It called on the Noriega-controlled
government ``to respect the decision of the Panamanian people.''
   Smith said his delegation saw polls open late, voter lists with
some names missing and names of dead people included
   ``It was all small, different fraud,'' he said.
   The U.S. delegation steered away from policy questions, saying
it would consult Congress and the White House before suggesting
what methods may be used to dislodge Noriega. The general was
indicted in February 1988 in Florida on federal drug-trafficking
charges, which he has denied.
   Some members of the delegation, speaking on the condition of
anonymity, said the Pentagon should withdraw 5,700 military
dependents in Panama and ``tighten the economic screws.''
   Others were more vocal. In Miami, Sen. Bob Graham, D-Fla., an
observer who left early Monday, said the United States ``should now
consider the use of force in Panama.
   Florida's other senator, Republican Connie Mack, said that if
Noriega's candidate is declared the winner, he expects to introduce
legislation this week to cancel the 1977 treaty that is to give
Panama control of the canal in 1999.
</TEXT>
