<FIRST>r a AM-People Sub a0587 05-08 0358</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People, Sub, a0587,0366</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3rd item in package to UPDATE with spokesman saying Williams
said he was slipped drugs.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hank Williams Jr. got his airplane back
after his agents agreed to pay arena owners $65,000 to cover losses
when the country singer showed up for a concert but failed to make
it through a single song.
   Centroplex management got a court order holding the plane until
they were satisfied damages would be paid, said Michael M. Pierce,
director of the 11,000-seat arena.
   The plane was released Sunday afternoon. ``They were anxious to
get out of town,'' said Pierce.
   Angry fans in the Saturday night audience of about 7,000 threw
beer bottles and burned souvenir T-shirts and a Confederate flag
with Williams' picture on it after he stumbled offstage following
20 minutes of starting and stopping songs. Nobody was arrested and
nobody got hurt, police said.
   ``We don't want any hard feelings,'' said Williams spokesman
Kent Arwood, interviewed by telephone from his home in Nashville.
``It was just an unfortunate thing that occurred. It's not the norm
for this kind of thing to happen with Hank Williams Junior.''
   Arwood later said Williams told him somebody had slipped him
drugs.
   The spokesman said Williams told him he had several alcoholic
beverages before the concert, but remembered feeling fine. ``He
said, `I wasn't drunk on stage. I know what it's like to be drunk,
and I wasn't drunk,''' Arwood said.
   ``Hank said, `I know for a fact someone slipped me some drugs or
something. I had a problem with drugs years ago and I know that
feeling. That's obviously what happened,' '' the spokesman said.
   Arwood said earlier that the incident had nothing to do with an
incident last month in which Williams, voted entertainer of the
year three times by the Academy of Country Music, stormed offstage
40 minutes into a concert in Bristol, Tenn.
   Arwood said several times that Williams, 39, whose father died
in 1953 at age 29 from the effects of alcohol abuse, is not an
alcoholic and that he put the problem with pills behind him years
ago.
</TEXT>
