<FILEID>AP-NR-05-08-89 2307EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-TheaterAwards     05-08 0235</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Theater Awards,240</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tomlin's `Search for Intelligent Life' Captures Hayes Awards</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lily Tomlin's one-woman show, ``The Search for
Signs of Intelligent Life in the Universe,'' won three Helen Hayes
awards Monday as the Washington theater world honored its best
productions.
   The Arena Stage, one of the nation's oldest regional theaters,
won five awards, including three for its production of the Luigi
Pirandello play, ``Six Characters in Search of An Author.''
   The Arena staging was best resident production and Rumanian
director Liviu Ciulei was chosen outstanding director for his
staging of the surrealist play. It also won for outstanding
lighting.
   Tomlin's touring show was named outstanding non-resident
production and the actress was picked outstanding lead actress.
Jane Wagner, the writer and director of Tomlin's show, won the
award as outstanding director for a non-resident production.
   Texas playwright Larry L. King won the outstanding new play
honor for ``The Night Hank Williams Died,'' a current off-Broadway
hit in New York that premiered last year at the New Playwrights'
Theater.
   The New York Shakespeare Festival production of ``Wenceslas
Square,'' by the late Washington writer Larry Shue, was honored for
outstanding actor, Victor Garber, and outstanding supporting
performer, Bruce Norris.
   Arena's final two awards came for its adaptation of the 1920s
Marx Brothers musical, ``The Cocoanuts,'' which was picked as the
city's top musical. Charles Janasz, who played Harpo Marx, was
chosen outstanding musical actor.
</TEXT>
