<FIRST>r i AM-Argentina-Military     05-08 0181</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Argentina-Military,0186</SECOND>
<HEAD>Air Force Officer Convicted of Human Rights Abuses Completes Sentence</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Retired Air Force commander Brig.
Orlando Agosti, convicted in December 1985 of human rights abuses
during the military's ``dirty war'' against subversion, was ordered
released from prison Monday.
   Orlandi, 64, left the Justice Palace with his lawyers after the
decision was handed down in federal court.
   Orlandi's sentence of three years and nine months was the
lightest passed on the five former commanders of the regimes that
ruled between the March 1976 coup against President Isabel Peron
and the election in October 1983 of President Raul Alfonsin.
   The other four, including ex-presidents and ex-army commanders
Jorge Videla and Roberto Viola, remain at Magdalena military
prison, 60 miles southeast of the capital, Buenos Aires.
   At lest 8,961 Argentines were arrested by security forces, never
seen again and presumed executed between 1976 and 1983, according
to a commission appointed by Alfonsin. Human rights groups say the
total could be twice as high.
   Agosti still faces separate charges stemming from his
participation in the 1976 coup.
</TEXT>
