<FIRST>r i AM-Poland-Strikes     05-08 0442</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-Strikes,0458</SECOND>
<HEAD>Air Controllers Seeking Higher Wages Stage Work Slowdown</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 150-member Association of Polish Air
Traffic Controllers began a protest action Monday seeking higher
wages and modernization of radar equipment.
   Three controllers, speaking for the group, said a
work-by-the-rules slowdown started with takeoffs allowed only at
10-minute intervals and lengthening of the distance between planes
coming in to land.
   In the first significant strike since the April 5 agreement
between the government and Solidarity union, workers at four copper
mines remained off the job.
   Negotiations continued Monday with the workers whose four-day
strike has cut ore production by 100,000 tons daily, the state PAP
news agency reported.
   Warsaw television said the strike, by about 20,000 miners, has
spread to copper mine employees working in Warsaw on the city's
subway system.
   The Solidarity Information Service said about 6,000 strikers
were occupying the four mines near Lubin.
   The strikers are seeking a 50 percent increase in pay that now
averages between $118 and $176 per months.
   Solidarity, suspended in December 1981 and subsequently
outlawed, was restored as a legal union under the April 5 accord in
which Communist authorities also agreed to political and electoral
reforms.
   The strikes began Friday at the four mines that produce most of
Poland's copper. Copper exports to the West in 1987 amounted to
$233 million, according to the government's Statistical Yearbook.
   The three air traffic controllers, speaking with the condition
they not be identified, said the controllers were on a ``strike
alert.''
   They said the protest action began because the the controllers
did not receive a satisfactory response to repeated requests for
improvements in equipment and pay.
   Flights in and out of Warsaw were running up to 40 minutes
behind schedule because of the job action, the controllers said.
   Zbigniew Dabkowski, director of commercial cargo for Poland's
LOT Air Lines, said, ``I don't think it affects us to such a degree
that anybody would want to comment on it. Talks continue.''
   The controllers said a letter was sent last month to Prime
Minister Mieczyslaw F. Rakowski complaining of the ``deterioration
over a number of years'' in the air traffic control system.
   They said that old, unreliable radar and the decline in wages
compared to the 80-percent inflation rate has caused a number of
controllers to leave the service and forced others to take second
jobs.
   Controllers now earn an average $147 per month with overtime, or
about the national average, according to the three.
   They said the controllers are seeking salaries ranging from
about $220 per month for assistant controllers to $470 montly for
senior supervisors.
</TEXT>
