<FILEID>AP-NR-05-08-89 2332EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Panama 5thLd-Writethru a0731 05-08 0948</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Panama, 5th Ld-Writethru, a0731,0980</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gunmen Attack Opposition Marchers in Panama</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 24 grafs to UPDATE with Duque comments, later figures,
detail. Picks up 25th graf, `Sen. Bob...' with minor editing</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto PAN5</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD HERZFELDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Men in civilian clothes firing
automatic rifles broke up a march on Monday by thousands of people
who were alleging massive election fraud. At least three people
were wounded.
   About 15,000 people joined the march to protest raids by Gen.
Manuel Antonio Noriega's soldiers, who witnesses said seized
thousands of vote tally sheets and prevented Sunday's presidential
election from being tabulated.
   ``I hope there will be a worldwide outcry against this dictator
stealing this election from his own people,'' said former President
Jimmy Carter, an invited observer.
   Polls closed at 5 p.m. Sunday, but it was not until 3 p.m.
Monday that the government said it received any votes to count.
   Opposition presidential candidate Guillermo Endara and
government candidate Carlos Duque both claimed victory. The new
president is to take office Sept. 1.
   Duque, Noriega's hand-picked candidate, said he was leading by
207,121 to 186,487 with 43 percent of the vote counted.
   Carter cited an exit poll by the Roman Catholic church as a
reliable indicator that Duque had lost by about 3-to-1.
   Carter said the government was in the process of creating
counterfeit tallies to replace those stolen by Noriega's soldiers
during the night.
   Noriega as Defense Forces chief is Panama's de facto ruler.
   Ricardo Arias Calderon, the opposition's vice presidential
candidate, declared, ``The government is confessing that it lost
the elections by seizing the tallies across the nation.''
   President Bush met with top advisers in Washington on Monday to
weigh what steps America should take next in its efforts to oust
Noriega. An administration official who spoke on condition of
anonymity said one possibility is to reinforce the U.S. military
presence in the Canal Zone to protect U.S. citizens.
   A delegation of official U.S. observers in Panama declared the
election fraudulent.
   Duque denounced what he called ``obvious American intervention
in affairs that only concern Panama and the abuse by observers of
Panamanian hospitality.''
   The attack on the demonstration seriously injured a TV
cameraman. A reporter for the French newspaper Le Monde and a
marcher were slightly hurt.
   The assault came as the two-hour march was breaking up near the
Electoral Tribunal. Endara and other leaders had already left when
a car bearing a large Duque poster drove into the crowd.
   Demonstrators threw stones, but the crowd scattered when the men
inside the car fired in the air. Troops nearby also began firing in
the air, and the men leaped from their car, firing AK-7 assault
rifles, carbines and shotguns.
   One, asked if he was military or civilian, replied: ``We are
from the people.''
   After the incident the crowd moved back about 500 yards and
started building bonfires in the street. Caravans of cars belonging
to rival party members drove through the city, some occupants
firing weapons in the air. Barricades of stones or rubbish burned
in some neighborhoods.
   The march, led by Endara, began near the city center and headed
for the eastern part of town.
   ``The people are going to defend their victory!'' Endara
declared. ``The people will rule.''
   The crowd surged around the heavily guarded Electoral Tribunal
building but moved back when Endara said he wanted to avoid a clash
with riot police.
   Noriega was indicted on federal drug trafficking charges last
year in Florida. Washington imposed economic sanctions, supported
anti-government leaders and reportedly gave $10 million to the
opposition election campaign.
   Noriega, who denies the drug charges, accused the United States
of conspiring with the opposition to oust him.
   The official delegation of election observers sent by Bush said
Noriega's soldiers intimidated voters and carried out widespread
fraud. They said they witnessed fraud firsthand, watching
individual Panamanian Defense Forces soldiers voting in more than
one precinct in the capital area Sunday.
   Sen. Bob Graham, D-Fla., an observer who left early Monday, said
in Miami the United States ``should now consider the use of force
in Panama.''
   The Panamanian Committee for Human Rights, which invited 279
observers from 21 nations, also condemned the election as
fraudulent.
   Before Monday's raids by soldiers, the opposition had also
charged during Sunday's voting that soldiers voted more than once
and that there were 100,000 extra names on voter rolls.
   In the Panama City suburb of San Miguelito, where Carter had
praised voting procedures the day before, troops arrived at 3 a.m.
and dispersed poll workers with gunshots and beatings.
   ``They knew the government had lost,'' said opposition poll
watcher Marcos Herrera. Tally sheets left behind and scattered
across the ground were viewed by The Associated Press, and overall
they showed a 3-1 margin for Endara.
   ``Obviously, if 120,000 votes were to disappear as a result of
violence, it would be difficult to assume this was an honest
election,'' said Fernando Suarez Gonzalez, a Spanish member of a
parliamentary observer group.
   San Miguelito served as the counting center for 120,000 of
Panama's 1.18 million registered voters.
   A spokesman for the election board, Boris Moreno, only would say
that no official complaints had been filed about events in San
Miguelito.
   In the Panamanian system, ballots for each precinct are counted
at the polls and then burned to prevent recounts. Tally sheets
listing the vote totals are then taken to a counting center.
   The opposition coalition said in a statement it had managed to
obtain figures from 1,039 of the nation's 4,255 precincts, many of
them in its own strongholds.
   The figures showed Endara with 174,510 votes to Duque's 59,729,
with 21,857 blank ballots.
</TEXT>
