<FIRST>r i AM-Nicaragua-US 1stLd-Writethru a0665 05-08 0697</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nicaragua-US, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0665,0715</SECOND>
<HEAD>D'Escoto Says Bush Lacks `Gut Commitment' To Destroy Sandinistas</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 5 grafs after 7th, `Ortega conferred...' to UPDATE with
rally and arrests. Pick up 8th pvs, `D'Escoto said...' DELETES 15th pvs,
`Ortega also...' which moved up.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAGGIE JACKSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nicaragua's foreign minister said Monday that
President Bush doesn't have Ronald Reagan's ``gut commitment'' to
destroy the Sandinista government and there are hopes for better
relations with the United States.
   In an interview with The Associated Press, Miguel d'Escoto said
he felt Bush is more pragmatic than former President Reagan.
   ``(With) Bush at least I don't think there's the degree of gut
commitment to the destruction of the (Sandinista) revolution,''
d'Escoto said, speaking in English.
   He said he also was ``led to have some optimism on the fact that
(Secretary of State) James A. Baker III I think is a pragmatic
man.'' He said Baker does not differ ideologically from Reagan's
secretary of state, George P. Shultz, but he believed Baker is in
the presidential ``inner circle'' and Shultz was not.
   D'Escoto, who is accompanying Nicaraguan President Daniel Ortega
on a 10-nation Western European tour, said Reagan ``was a man with
a pathological obsession about Nicaragua. I really think it can
only be described as that.
   ``Then he (Reagan) got himself into this so much that there was
no coming back because of a fear to lose credibility.''
   Ortega conferred with Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher on
Monday, and a British source said Mrs. Thatcher told him she was
disappointed by his government's lack of progress toward democracy.
   Ortega said Mrs. Thatcher did not promise any financial aid for
Nicaragua and he said, ``We didn't have much hope for that.''
   Later, at a rally in the Central Hall Westminster, Ortega told a
rally attended by about 2,500 cheering supporters that he was ``not
asking favors of anyone.''
   ``If I were to draw up the balance sheet of the sum of all the
wealth that market-oriented, developed countries have extracted
from all third countries of the world, all of our foreign debt
would be paid off and they would still owe us,'' he said.
   Ortega was introduced by novelist Graham Greene who said,
``Let's look at the darkness in our own country and not an
imaginary darkness in your own republic.''
   About 50 opponents of the left-wing Sandinistas gathered outside
the building and engaged in a shouting exchange with Ortega's
backers. Police kept the two groups apart but reported three
arrests.
   D'Escoto said the United States, which recently extended its
trade embargo against Nicaragua, ``is not really helping''
relations.
   He said the only positive sign was the U.S. decision to allow
Nicaragua to replace seven of its diplomats kicked out by the
Reagan administration in retaliation for the ouster of seven U.S.
diplomats 10 months ago. The Sandinistas accused the American
envoys of fomenting unrest.
   Nicaragua insists on respect from the United States, the foreign
minister said. ``All that we are asking for is a new type of
relationship with the States, in other words we want to be friends,
and their response is, `Who in the heck are you to be friends with
the United States?
   ``I believe with the United States it's a question of time,'' he
added.
   Ortega, after his 75-minute meeting with Mrs. Thatcher, said,
``It was a very frank conversation. We were both frank and direct.''
   He told reporters that Mrs. Thatcher's status as a world leader
``allows her to be ... able to contribute so that the problems
which exist between the United States and Nicaragua can be
overcome.''
   The British source, speaking on the condition he not be
identified, said the prime minister ``did not make any promises''
on that issue.
   Mrs. Thatcher expressed ``doubts about Nicaragua's commitment to
democracy,'' according to the British source.
   Ortega this year signed an agreement with four other Central
American presidents in which he promised electoral and other legal
reforms to ensure fair elections, set for February. But last week,
his government rejected an opposition demand to negotiate reforms.
   Ortega and his delegation leaves Tuesday for West Germany and
then Ireland before returning home.
</TEXT>
