<FIRST>a a BC-History Adv20   05-08 0504</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-History, Adv20,0528</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv20</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Saturday, May 20</HEAD>
<HEAD>Today In History</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Today is Saturday, May 20, the 140th day of 1989. There are 225
days left in the year.
   Today's highlight in history:
   Fifty years ago, on May 20, 1939, regular trans-Atlantic air
service began as a Pan American Airways plane, the Yankee Clipper,
took off from Port Washington, N.Y., bound for Europe.
   On this date:
   In 1506, Christopher Columbus died in poverty in Spain.
   In 1830, the first railroad timetable was published, in the
newspaper the Baltimore American.
   In 1861, North Carolina voted to secede from the Union.
   In 1861, the capital of the Confederacy was moved from
Montgomery, Ala., to Richmond, Va.
   In 1902, the United States ended its occupation of Cuba.
   In 1926, inventor Thomas Edison said Americans would prefer
silent movies to talking pictures.
   In 1927, Charles Lindbergh took off from Roosevelt Field in Long
Island, N.Y., aboard the Spirit of St. Louis on his historic solo
journey to France.
   In 1932, Amelia Earhart took off from Newfoundland for Ireland
to become the first woman to fly solo across the Atlantic.
   In 1947, a total eclipse of the sun crossed Brazil. Totality
began at 9:35 a.m. and lasted nearly four minutes.
   In 1961, a white mob attacked a busload of Freedom Riders in
Montgomery, Ala., prompting the federal government to send in U.S.
marshals to restore order.
   In 1963, the U.S. Supreme Court set aside the convictions of 31
students arrested for staging sit-in civil-rights protests at lunch
counters in four southern states.
   In 1970, some 100,000 people demonstrated in New York City's
Wall Street district to support U.S. policy in Vietnam and Cambodia.
   In 1985, the FBI arrested John A. Walker Jr., who was later
convicted of spying for the Soviet Union.
   In 1985, the Dow Jones Industrial Average closed above 1,300 for
the first time.
   In 1985, the United States began broadcasts to Cuba on Radio
Marti.
   Ten years ago: Iran's official news agency said the Iranian
government had asked the United States to delay sending its new
ambassador to Tehran, declaring a U.S. Senate resolution condemning
executions by Islamic firing squads to be ``clear interference.''
   Five years ago: Former Argentine President Isabel Peron, ousted
from office by a military coup in 1976, returned to her homeland
from Spain to lead a Peronist delegation in talks with President
Raul Alfonsin.
   One year ago: Laurie Dann walked into a Winnetka, Ill.,
elementary school classroom, shooting to death 8-year-old Nicholas
Corwin and wounding several other children. After wounding a young
man at his home, Dann, 30, took her own life.
   Today's birthdays: Actor James Stewart is 81. Comedian George
Gobel is 70. Actress Constance Towers is 56. Singer Joe Cocker is
45. Singer-actress Cher is 43. Ron Reagan is 31.
   Thought for today: ``We must have ... a place where children can
have a whole group of adults they can trust.'' _ Margaret Mead,
American anthropologist (1901-1978).
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End advance for use Saturday, May 20</NOTE>
