<FILEID>AP-NR-05-08-89 1307EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a i AM-UN-Lebanon'sVoice Adv16   05-08 0461</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UN-Lebanon's Voice, Adv 16,0478</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv16</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Tue AMs, May 16 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Divided at Home, Lebanon Speaks With One Voice at U.N.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In Lebanon, two rival governments _ one
Christian, the other Moslem _ battle each other for power, but at
the United Nations Lebanon speaks with one voice.
   The division raised questions at the United Nations over which
faction Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar and other U.N.
officials should deal with.
   ``The secretary-general deals with the permanent representative
of Lebanon at the U.N.,'' said U.N. spokesman Francois Giuliani.
That representative is Ambassador Rachid Fakhoury.
   But to whom does Fakhoury and all other Lebanese diplomats
around the world answer?
   ``Under a mutual understanding, without any public declarations,
the secretary-general of Lebanon's Foreign Ministry transmits
positions from both factions,'' said Clovis Maksoud, the Arab
League's ambassador to the United Nations and the United States.
   The secretary-general of the Foreign Ministry in Beirut, Farouk
Abilama, ``is the de facto foreign policy adviser for the divided
government, but this is being strained now, in the current
crisis,'' said Maksoud.
   ``There is no attempt on the part of the governments to
challenge the unity of the embassies or missions abroad, or to
embarrass them by getting them to take a factional position,'' he
added.
   Since there is no way the divided government could agree on
appointing any new ambassadors for overseas posts, the Lebanese
diplomatic corps has been frozen pending the outcome of the current
crisis.
   ``All embassies are getting a new lease on their tenure,'' said
Maksoud.
   ``The assumption is that this is a transitory stage, and
hopefully a short one.''
   Ambassador Fakhoury declined to be interviewed.
   Lebanon's U.N. mission consists of four diplomats, two
Christians and two Moslems who, from all indications, work together
amicably.
   Arab League mediators have tried to arrange a cease-fire to halt
the violence in Lebanon, which has claimed at least 278 lives since
March 8.
   Maksoud noted that a few key government institutions survive in
Beirut, the Central Bank in particular.
   ``The Central Bank pays for the expenses of both factions of
government impartially, and for the missions and embassies,'' he
said.
   The government crisis broke out Sept. 22, when the Christians
rejected Moslem nominees for president to succeed the outgoing
President Amin Gemayel, a Christian.
   Gemayal then chose Gen. Michel Aoun, commander of 20,000
Christian troops, to lead the government and the Moslem faction
picked Acting Prime Minster Salim Hoss to head the rival government.
   By tradition, Lebanon's president is Christian, the prime
minister a Sunni Moslem and the Parliament speaker a Shiite Moslem.
But this time, the Moslems wanted one of theirs to be president.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Tue AMs, May 16</NOTE>
</DOC>
