<FILEID>AP-NR-05-08-89 2033EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--HomeVideo Adv00   05-08 0625</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--Home Video, Adv 00,0650</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv00</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Anytime</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Video View: Home Video Reviews</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOLORES BARCLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Arts Editor</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Gorillas in the Mist'' (MCA Home Video. VHS-Beta, $89.95.
Rated PG-13)
   
   Dian Fossey was a driven, committed woman _ a woman who gave up
the comforts and safety of home, her love life and her appendix to
live with gorillas in central Africa.
   But she crossed that fine line between commitment and obsession,
between a illusion and reality and paid for the voyage with her
life.
   ``Gorillas in the Mist'' attempts to examine the life of the
anthropologist who dedicated her life to saving an endangered
population of gorillas in Rwanda. She fought poachers, government
officials, animal traders and her own colleagues.
   Sigourney Weaver stars as Fossey. But her performance is more a
character study for a drama class than a finished product. She
stumbles through an array of emotions, from joy to enthusiasm to
wonder to rage, but simply doesn't have the depth to be convincing.
Fossey was a complex, unconventional woman; in Weaver, we see only
a silly shrill.
   But the gorillas are cute, and far more interesting than the
star.
   Bryan Brown puts in an admirable performance as a National
Geographic photographer and Fossey's sometime lover. There also are
good support jobs by John Miluwi as Fossey's house man and tracker,
and Julie Harris as a white local who befriends the anthropologist.
They overpower Weaver, who seems an amateur out of her league,
despite an Academy nomination for the role.
   If you can suffer through Sigourney Weaver's acting, you'll
enjoy the stunning vistas and beautiful photography of ``Gorillas
in the Mist.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Punchline'' (RCA-Columbia Pictures Home Video. VHS-Beta,
$89.95. Rated R)
   
   The manic, melancholic, merry world of stand-up comedy is
studied in David Seltzer's ``Punchline,'' starring Tom Hanks and
Sally Field.
   Critically acclaimed when released theatrically last year, it
was overlooked by the Academy at Oscar time. Too bad, because Hanks
gives a much better performance as the brilliant comic Steven Golda
than he did playing a 12-year-old in ``Big.''
   And the movie itself is a tightly written, fast-paced portrait
of that special world of comedy. It is a movie that will make you
laugh, cry and think.
   Everybody tells Lilah Krytsick (Field), a housewife from New
Jersey, how natually funny she is. More than anything else, Lilah
would love to be comic. So she spends her nights in a Manhattan
comedy club called the Gas Station.
   But the personable Lilah isn't too funny on stage _ she's a yawn
with her Polish jokes and her New Jersey jokes. Enter Steven, the
hit of the club with his Lenny Bruce-type deliveries and acerbic
satirical stabs. He wants to make it big. Lilah just wants to make
it.
   She enlists his help. He sees her potential and encourages her.
She sees his pain and befriends him. Along the way, she and her
husband weather a crisis in their marriage (over Lilah's avocation)
and become closer still.
   The movie climaxes with two amazing monologs by the stars,
especially Hanks' brilliantly paced diatribe against ``stylists.''
   ``Punchline'' is a must-see. Rent it, if you must, but try to
buy it. It's a worthy addition to your movie library.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Motion Picture Association of America rating definitions:
   G _ General audiences. All ages admitted.
   PG _ Parental guidance suggested. Some material may not be
suitable for children.
   PG-13 _ Special parental guidance strongly suggested for
children under 13. Some material may be inappropriate for young
children.
   R _ Restricted. Under 17 requires accompanying parent or adult
guardian.
   X _ No one under 17 admitted. Some states may have higher age
restrictions.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Release Anytime</NOTE>
</DOC>
