<DOCNO> AP890508-0225 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-08-89 1312EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--RecordReviews Adv00   05-08 0625</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--Record Reviews, Adv 00,0648</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv00</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Anytime</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>In the Groove: Record Reviews</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Like a Prayer'' (Sire) _ Madonna
   
   The perfumed inner sleeve is a tip-off, if any is needed, that
this is not just a record but a Pop Culture Event. But put aside
the hype, the soft drink commercials, the soap opera marriage and
the controversial videos, and what are we left with? Ah, yes, the
music.
   The fact is, Madonna knows how to make ear-catching pop music.
This is not high art, but neither is it the pasteurized processed
music substitute that fills the airwaves of radio stations with
such names like as 101. It may be bubble gum, but with a spicier
flavor than most.
   The most interesting track is ``Love Song,'' a collaboration
with Prince. The two flamboyant stars work surprisingly well
together, their vocal tricks backed by sinuous guitar and
synthesizer music to create a mood of sexual tension. Less
successful is ``Express Yourself,'' imitation Motown that calls for
a huskier voice _ Madonna is no belter.
   Several songs deal with family relationships: the death of a
mother in ``Promise to Try,'' a cruel parent in ``Oh Father,'' a
violently crumbling marriage in ``Till Death Do Us Part.'' However
close the stories may be to Madonna's own life, a bit of genuine
emotion does come through amid the slick production and stylized
singing. But don't look for insight; the lyrics are simple and
sentimental. The cause of marital strife: ``He's not in love with
her anymore.''
   Then there's the hit title track with its quasi-religious
imagery (``When you call my name it's like a little prayer'').
There's really nothing new about that _ references to heaven and
angels abound in teen love songs. The viewpoint here, as throughout
the album, is adolescent. But then, consider the audience.
   _ By Dan Murphy, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Don't Tell a Soul'' (Sire) _ The Replacements
   
   The Replacements' gradual switch from a raucous punk sound to a
more mature, melodic rock has drawn plenty of complaints from old
fans who snipe that they're selling out.
   It's all rather silly.
   If the music's good, it will find an audience. But in this case,
the audience won't be terribly large. ``Don't Tell a Soul'' isn't a
breakthrough because too many of its songs lack the bite and wit of
leader Paul Westerberg's best work, whatever the style.
   Westerberg's a critic's darling because he combines the scruffy
attitude of lower middle-class punk, a weary voice roughened by too
many cigarettes and a keen writer's eye that frequently explores
the vulnerability of himself and others.
   His band used to thrash Westerberg's songs out in a drunken orgy
of noise, but they're getting older now. Slower tempos and acoustic
guitars are showing up in the Replacements repertoire.
   Westerberg's strengths are used best on the country-flavored
``Achin' to Be,'' about trying to unwrap the mysteries of a woman
who ``dances alone in a nightclub.''
   The album opener, ``Talent Show,'' is extremely effective in
capturing the mood of anticipation that comes with a rock show. The
jaunty ``Asking Me Lies,'' which talks about a Mexican bar mitzvah,
and ``I'll Be You'' are also strong.
   But songs such as ``Back to Back'' and ``We'll Inherit the
Earth'' sound tentative and self-conscious. It's not the style
changes; it's just a lack of strong material. And the Replacements
aren't adept enough at covering up the lost feeling that comes when
they're working on a sub-par composition.
   Despite the occasional flashes, ``Don't Tell a Soul'' is flat, a
workmanlike album from a band that probably has better days ahead.
   _ By David Bauder, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Release Anytime</NOTE>
</DOC>
