<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--Stewart Adv19-21   05-08 0717</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--Stewart, Adv 19-21,0737</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv19</HEAD>
<HEAD>$Adv20</HEAD>
<HEAD>$Adv21 ^For Release Weekend Editions, May 19-21 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Nashville Sound: He Walked 1,600 Miles to Sing on Opry</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE EDWARDS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For country music singer David Stewart,
nothing will ever beat how he was given a guest spot on the Grand
Ole Opry: He walked 1,600 miles,
   Stewart, at age 37, spent about three months last year walking
from Wyoming to Nashville to try to impress Opry officials how much
he wanted to sing on the fabled country music show. He left his
home in Gillette, Wyo., on April 30 and arrived in Nashville July
22, having lost 25 pounds and worn out three pairs of walking shoes.
   As a reward, the Opry gave him a one-time guest shot on the show
and he sang two songs last July 23.
   ``We all have dreams,'' he says, looking back on his ambitious
adventure a year later. ``But not all of them come true. Mine did.''
   Since his walk and the Opry performance, he has moved to
Nashville. He has taken voice lessons, pursued a songwriting career
and made a music video about his trek.
   ``If nothing else happens, I've fulfilled my dream,'' he said in
an interview. ``There's not a thing I can complain about.''
   Stewart, who has been singing country music most of his adult
life, walked through Wyoming, Nebraska, Iowa, Missouri, Illinois
and Kentucky before reaching his destination.
   Accompanied by his dog, Snicker, he averaged 22 miles a day, six
days a week. A friend followed him in a motor home, where he slept
except for occasional complimentary lodging that was offered.
   ``The chamber of commerce in a couple of places arranged for a
room and a hot bath,'' he recalled. ``That was nice.''
   After reaching Nashville, he placed a call to Opry manager Hal
Durham, who had heard about the walk through news reports.
   Stewart, born and raised in Bradenton, Fla., recounted the
conversation: ``He said, `I understand you walked 1,600 miles to be
on the Opry. That's a long way son.' I said, `Yes sir.'''
   Durham then invited him to sing the next night, and Stewart sang
``In the Wings of the Grand Ole Opry'' and ``Jambalaya.''
   ``I had all the emotions of excitement and anxiety,'' he
recalled. ``I hear the recording of that night and I can hear that
I was on the edge of breaking up. I have to pinch myself to realize
it's true. I still get chills when I think about it.''
   He was received warmly by the audience after finishing his first
song, and did an encore.
   He decided not to return to his job in Wyoming at a fast food
restaurant which he partly owned. But he still realizes income from
it, which has helped him to meet expenses while trying to further
his singing career in Nashville.
   ``For the first couple of months here, I just unwound,'' he
said. ``I gathered my thoughts and figured out where I was going
with my career.''
   He has visited backstage at the Opry, but not performed any more.
   ``I realize it's for established stars,'' Stewart said.
   He has not pursued a recording contract, preferring to finish
the video which he plans to use as a selling point for a contract
with a major label. In case a music career doesn't pan out, he's
passed the exam for a real estate license.
   ``I found people here receptive, but it's still hard to break in
because there's so much talent here,'' he said. ``It's a matter of
getting the right breaks at the right time and meeting the right
people.''
   ``I still don't feel like I've broken in in a big way. My
biggest dream has come true _ singing on the Opry. Now I intend to
work hard to become a (regular) member of the Opry. I want to be
able to walk on that stage many more times.''
   Most of the 25 pounds he lost on his walk have returned to his
tanned frame.
   ``My wife tells me every day I need to get this weight off,'' he
said. ``I have a weakness for catfish. That fried food will put it
on you.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, May 19-21</NOTE>
