<FIRST>a a BC-SPE--Careers:Nursing     05-08 0605</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-SPE--Careers: Nursing,0631</SECOND>
<HEAD>SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>Careers: Nurse Salaries</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP LaserPhotos NY700, NY701</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Nurses' salaries are beginning to improve in response to the
critical nursing shortage.
   Salary increases during l988 averaged 6.9 percent for
entry-level nurses and 10.6 percent for more experienced nursing
staff, reports Richard McKibbin, who handles research for the
American Nurses Association in Kansas City.
   Advancement opportunities, flexible scheduling, tuition
assistance and other enticements also are being brought into play
to help hospitals replenish their nursing staffs.
   About 165,000 jobs were open for registered nurses at the
beginning of l989, according to the Secretary's Commission on
Nursing of the Department of Health and Human Services.
   The recent wage settlement for nurses at New York's
Columbia-Presbyterian Hospital may be a harbinger. The hospital
agreed to raise starting salaries for nurses to $31,500, and nurses
with more than 20 years' experience will receive $47,000. The pact,
negotiated with the New York State Nurses Association, eliminates
both mandatory overtime and assignment of nurses outside their
specialties. Some of the money to pay for the settlement will come
from New York state, which recently set aside $193 million to
increase nursing salaries statewide for the year.
   The settlement for the first time ``addresses nurses as
professionals,'' said Sheila O'Rourke, Columbia-Presbyterian nurse,
as the agreement was made.
   The figures are well above the $22,416 entry-level and $32,160
senior nurse averages for l988 reported by the ANA. Spokeswoman
Carol Grimaldi says these figures are still more realistic for most
of the country, which doesn't share the high cost of living with
metropolitan centers on both coasts.
   Specialist nurses like anesthetists can expect salaries
averaging slightly more than $45,000 per year, says Mary Jeannette
Mannino, president of the American Association of Nurse Anethetists
in Park Ridge, Ill. Starting salaries for anesthetist nurses is
estimated at between $31,000 and $40,000.
   ``The money didn't make any difference at the time I chose nurse
anesthesia, but it does make a difference now, and I think it
should make a difference,'' says Margaret Faut, associate
chairperson of surgical nursing at Rush Presbyterian St. Luke's
Medical Center in Chicago. `` Personally, I think salary should be
a consideration in making career choices.
   ``I'm a single parent with two children, and I'm thankful that I
have this career. You don't want to pick a profession because the
pay is good, but it doesn't hurt, either.''
   The University Hospital Consortium, Inc., a network of 48
not-for-profit teaching hospitals and clinics, has launched a
recruitment campaign that emphasizes improved pay, advancement and
working conditions.
   ``By and large, today's nurses look for more than a steady
income,'' says Kristi Kelsey, a nursing personnel specialist and RN
who directs UHC's Recruitment Network, based in Oakbrook Terrace,
Ill. ``They want opportunities to progress through their work to
the point where they can specialize, manage, conduct research or
teach.''
   She says that many of the teaching hospitals are offering nurses
continuing education for advancement, tuition reimbursement,
nursing rounds and in-depth orientation and internships.
   ``In light of a steadily growing population of older Americans,
expanding medical technology and the greater incidence of
catastrophic diseases, we will need more, not fewer, nurses as we
enter the next century,'' Kelsey says.
   The shortage is letting experienced nurses ``pick and choose
exactly what they are looking for,'' she says.
   Salaries for nurses have risen faster than for any other
profession during the past year, says Dr. Carol A. Brooks, vice
president for nursing at Long Island Jewish Medical Center in New
Hyde Park, N.Y. ``At last, the money's getting there to provide a
lifestyle to go with a busy professional life.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
