<DOCNO> AP890508-0233 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-08-89 0839EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a BC-SPE--Careers:Women     05-08 0760</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-SPE--Careers: Women,0788</SECOND>
<HEAD>SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>Careers: Women Entrepreneurs</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP LaserPhoto NY702</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HERBERT G. McCANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Judi Devin's career ladder had hit a ceiling.
Joan Lieb needed more rewards from her job.
   Their reasons were different, but the result was the same _ both
women decided to start their own businesses.
   And their numbers are growing _ both in people and in profits.
   An estimated 5 million women now own businesses in the United
States, says the Chicago-based National Association of Women
Business Owners.
   Statistics compiled by the association show women contributed
$250 billion to the economy in 1988. Of that, $37 billion went into
the U.S. Treasury and $13 billion into state and local coffers.
   Devin, who serves as a spokeswoman for the association, says
women are starting businesses at three to five times the rate of
their male counterparts. Many of the new female entrepreneurs
entered the corporate world in the 1970s, she said in a recent
interview.
   ``These women were the most educated in history,'' she added.
``Many were feeling frustrated for not being allowed to reach their
full potential in a business sense and started looking for
alternatives.''
   That condition is known as the ``glass ceiling,'' and it's a
condition Devin herself knows well.
   In 1975, she was the first woman manager in her division at one
of the country's largest computer and data service companies. But
four years later, she felt her options were ``not as many as I
would have liked.''
   So she started her own Minneapolis company, Medium Well Done,
which designs and develops instructional projects. And now her list
of international clients includes her former bosses.
   Lieb was unhappy at a large Chicago real estate company, so in
1980, with five other women, she founded Beliard Gordon &amp; Partners,
a residential real estate company.
   She and her partners felt their take-home pay should have been
increased as their sales volume increased _ something their
previous company did not offer. So they decided to work for
themselves.
   ``We sell homes from $50,000 to $2 million, and we lead all the
other real estate companies in the area in the sale of single
family homes,'' Lieb said.
   She said the firm sold $140 million in residential property in
1988, though she would not give profit figures.
   Ironically, Lieb said, most of the top producers in residential
real estate sales are women _ one reason all but one of the firm's
25 sales associates also are women.
   ``Buying or selling a home is an emotional experience,'' she
said. ``Sometimes it's done in the worst period of life for the
customer, who many times is buying or selling because of
relocation, divorce or death.
   ``We are dealing with people at a time of upheaval, you have to
be sensitive. We are not dealing with just two bedrooms and a bath,
which is why women are good at it.''
   And the increasing number of women business owners serves as an
incentive to other women.
   Peggy Leonard, president of the 14-year-old National Association
of Women Business Owners, says the organization offers forums for
women to ask questions and give advice in running businesses.
   Ms. Leonard, who operates Computer Training and Support Services
in Lake Geneva, Ill., says many of the women in the organization
came from the corporate world, though the group does not keep track
of the reasons its members start their own companies.
   ``We like our remedy, which is business ownership,'' Ms. Leonard
said.
   The association is involved in extensive lobbying in Congress on
issues affecting women business owners, and it helped convince
Congress to approve the Women Business Ownershp Act last year.
   That law requires the federal government to collect data on
female-owned businesses, something not done in the past.
   The bill also allows the Small Business Administration to give
out loans, and it established a task force look into problems faced
by women-owned businesses.
   However, Congress dropped a provision that would have created a
government outreach program to bring women-owned businesses into
federal contract procurement.
   ``Government had $200 billion in procurement contracts last
year,'' Ms. Devin said. ``Women's businesses got less than 1
percent.''
   ``Access to U.S. contracts is a big negative,'' added Ms.
Leonard. ``There is much inequality.''
   She noted that the government never has had an outreach program
to encourage women-owned businesses to obtain government contracts.
   ``In addition, women are not traditionally in the circle in
which such contracts are obtained,'' Ms. Leonard said.
   ``There is an old boy network, but that is starting to change.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
