<SECOND>BC-SPE--Careers: Disabled,0230</SECOND>
<HEAD>SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>Careers: ^Disabled Opportunity</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE CORAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new fast-food franchising company is
targeting the disabled as potential owners or operators of its
stores.
   Heavenly Hot Dogs, Inc., has designed its stores to be operated
by physically disabled franchisers. ``A Heavenly Hot Dogs franchise
can be successfully operated by any entrepreneur, including an
individual whose handicap confines him to a wheelchair 100 percent
of the time,'' says Lee Lanktree, the president and chief executive
officer of the new, publicly traded company.
   Lanktree says he expects disabled people to operate at least 25
percent of all Heavenly Hot Dog franchises. The first store with a
handicapped operator opened early this year in West Palm Beach, Fla.
   The Florida Council of Handicapped Organizations and the Florida
Paraplegic Association have been working with the company and Sun
Belt banks to line up financial packages that will make ownership
possible for handicapped individuals.
   The self-contained modular Heavenly Hot Dog units, being
manufactured by Molded Fiberglass Shapes, Inc., are designed with
ramps, indented counters, cooking equipment that can be reached
from a sitting position, and aisles wide enough to provide
clearance for wheelchairs. The buildings, in the shape of giant
wooden barrels, each have 300 square feet of internal space to
support an inventory of 3,000 hot dogs and related items.
</TEXT>
