<FIRST>a a BC-SPE--Careers:Welders     05-08 0266</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-SPE--Careers: Welders,0275</SECOND>
<HEAD>SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>Careers: Welder Shortage ^LaserPhoto NY704</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Welding _ one of the older skills of civilization _
is also a sure bet for the future.
   Skilled welders are almost an endangered species, and the
shortage of welders and welding engineers means security and
advancement for those who choose this field, according to the
American Welding Society.
   ``Welders are leaving or retiring at an annual rate of nearly 18
percent, with a severely inadequate number of replacements coming
along in our schools today,'' says John M. Gerken, president of the
society. ``Our requirements exceed our actual replacements by
nearly three to one.''
   The society projects the shortage well into the next century,
and that will positively affect salary and advancement. Gerken says
that welders currently earn from $10 to $25 per hour, depending on
their skills and the locations. A welding engineer with a four-year
college degree can expect to start at about $30,000 a year.
   The options for welders is wide, too, Gerken says. Many welders
can become engineers, educators, designers, researchers or managers
as they add to their education and experience.
   Thought to be about 6,000 years old, the welding profession
today covers major and basic industries such as aerospace,
automotive, construction, electronics, metalwork, nuclear power and
shipbuilding. The field's newer technologies include working with
lasers, microjoining, plasmas and robotics.
   Gerken says that the potential welder should have good
mechanical aptitude, mathematical skills, a logical mind,
imagination, and the ability to work as a team member. Education
requirements range from high school vocational courses to college
degree programs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
