<FILEID>AP-NR-05-08-89 2349EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-BATUS     05-08 0419</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-BATUS,0435</SECOND>
<HEAD>Batus Reports 15 Earnings Gain in 1988</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Batus Inc. announced Monday its earnings
rose 15 percent in 1988 as its Brown &amp; Williamson Tobacco Corp.
subsidiary enjoyed record high sales.
   Batus, which also has interests in retailing, paper products and
insurance, said it earned $535 million, up from 466.2 million in
1987.
   The company, the U.S. arm of the British firm BAT Industries
PLC, said it had revenue of $6.3 billion, up from $5.83 billion the
year before.
   The company did not announce its per-share earnings.
   In December, Batus achieved its long-term goal of entering the
financial services market by acquiring Farmers Group Inc. for $5.2
billion. However, the insurance company's 1988 income figures were
not incorporated into the Batus income statement, contained in the
company's annual report.
   The report said Brown &amp; Williamson, the third-largest cigarette
manufacturer in the United States, had record sales of $2.8
billion, an 11 percent increase from 1987 with operating income up
6 percent to $651 million.
   The company said the gains represented continued development in
the international and domestic cigarette market.
   Appleton Papers Inc., a leading producer of carbonless paper,
increased sales 8 percent to $844 million while operating income
was $131 million, a gain of almost 4 percent.
   Despite intensified competition and sluggish consumer spending,
Batus' retailing companies _ Saks Fifth Avenue, Marshall Field's,
Ivey's and Breuners _ achieved modest profit gains from 1987, the
company reported. Total retail sales were up 3 percent, to $2.6
billion, with operating income advancing 3 percent to $177 million.
   Sales at Saks Fifth Avenue were particularly strong in the New
York and Florida markets, including the flagship Fifth Avenue
store, the company said. Marshall Field's had a record year,
increasing its market share in Chicago and positioning itself for
additional growth, the Batus statement said.
   The buy-out of the Farmers Group was the latest portion of a
diversification plan Batus initiated in the early 1970s, according
to the annual report. Under that plan, the business has grown from
a single tobacco company to several leading corporations in four
key industries.
   Nearly all of Batus' sales came from tobacco in the early 1970s
but non-tobacco operations accounted for almost 40 percent of the
company's sales by 1980.
   The non-tobacco operations were responsible for 56 percent of
Batus' sales in 1988, the company said, and that figure should grow
still higher when Farmers Group's sales are included in the
company's 1989 report.
   Batus employs 55,000 in the United States.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
