<FILEID>AP-NR-05-08-89 1221EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-WallStreetNoon     05-08 0363</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street Noon,0381</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market fell in relatively thin volume
today, amid continued worries about inflation.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials was down 17.77 points to
2,364.19 at noon EDT. The blue-chip indicator was 4.21 points lower
an hour earlier.
   Declining issues outnumbered advancers by about 11 to 4 on the
New York Stock Exchange, with 949 issues down, 342 issues up and
503 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 66.27 million shares.
   Analysts said an increase in hourly earnings last month and a
new agreement between Bethlehem Steel Corp. and the United
Steelworkers helped fuel inflationary fears late last week.
   The Labor Department reported Friday that unemployment rose 0.3
percentage point in April to 5.3 percent, a signal that the
economy's growth is slowing. But the report also showed that hourly
earnings rose 7 cents last month.
   Also Friday, the nation's second largest steelmaker reported it
had reached a pact with the steelworkers union that some economists
said could boost wages and benefits substantially and trigger a
wage hike throughout the industry.
   ``Today's market is driven by what happened with the Bethlehem
contract, although I don't agree that it is as inflationary or as
bad for the company as some think,'' said Dennis Jarrett, technical
analyst with Kidder, Peabody. ``The contract was perceived as a
forerunner of things to come in the industry.''
   Analysts said market participants also were turning their
attention to this week's Treasury bond auction and a report on
producer prices due out on Friday.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks was
down 1.37 to 170.77.
   At the American Stock Exchange, the market value index was down
1.14 to 345.70.
