<FILEID>AP-NR-05-08-89 0750EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Spill-TaskForce     05-08 0397</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Spill-Task Force,0411</SECOND>
<HEAD>Three States and British Columbia Meet on Oil Spill Strategy</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Tanker Spill. A version moving on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LISA E. SHUCHMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Representatives from three states and a Canadian
province are forming a task force to prevent or minimize a disaster
in their waters similar to the massive Exxon oil spill in Alaska.
   Officials from Alaska, Washington, Oregon and British Columbia
all have separate regulations and laws governing oil shipments
through their waters, as well as different plans for responding to
oil emergencies.
   Members of the newly formed Oil Spill Task Force say a regional
approach is more effective than each of the four governments
working alone.
   They plan to meet Tuesday to coordinate policies.
   ``We're all speaking in one voice,'' said Carolyn Young of
Oregon's Department of Environmental Quality, a member of the group.
   The group may recommend changing state, provincial and federal
laws to help prevent spills, said Greg Sorlie, program manager for
Washington's Department of Ecology.
   The regional approach has already been effective in putting
pressure on the Exxon Corp. since more than 10 million gallons was
spilled into Prince William Sound on March 24, said Rick Wilson,
director of Planning and Assessment for the British Columbia
Ministry of Environment.
   Combined efforts by the four jurisdictions made it ``remarkably
easy'' to demand that Exxon drain all the oil from the Exxon Valdez
before taking it to Portland, Ore., for repairs, Young said.
   ``The leverage of the four governments when combined is greater
than when each works alone,'' Wilson said.
   Task force members also plan to share information on ways to
recover costs and damages and technology for coping with spills.
One item on the agenda Tuesday is a demonstration of oil removal
equipment by Clean Sound, a cleanup consortium of oil and
transportation companies in Puget Sound.
   Wilson said government and public pressure could be a ``moral
force'' to encourage a better cleanup response.
   ``Exxon is seeing governments and the public saying certain
standards are required,'' he said.
   The first meeting occurred shortly after the spill and involved
only officials from British Columbia and Washington. Alaska and
Oregon were invited to join soon afterward.
   The task force was formed by Washington Gov. Booth Gardner and
British Columbia Premier William Vander Zalm after an oil spill in
December off the central Washington coast.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
