<SECOND>PM-WPP-Ogilvy,0286</SECOND>
<HEAD>WPP Raises Bid for Ogilvy to $50 a Share</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Ogilvy Group Inc. today said it received a
revised takeover offer of $50 a share or as much as $800 million
from British marketing and communications company WPP Group PLC.
   The latest offer is $5 a share higher than WPP's initial offer
for Ogilvy, parent of the Ogilvy &amp; Mather advertising agency.
   Kenneth Roman, Ogilvy Group chaiman and chief executive officer,
stated in a brief news release that WPP's proposal would be
considered ``in a proper manner and in due course.''
   The revised WPP proposal would be worth $800 million based on
the purchase of all Ogilvy's outstanding common stock and
equivalents, which total 16 million shares. On this basis, the
previous offer was worth $720 million.
   Wall Street had expected WPP to increase its offer possibly to
as much as $55 a share and Ogilvy stock traded above $50 a share in
national over-the-counter trading late last week.
   In early trading today, Ogilvy shares jumped $2 to $51.87{.
   When WPP Chairman Martin Sorrell made his original offer, he had
said that all terms of the proposal were negotiable, indicating
that he would be willing to pay more for Ogilvy. A merger of WPP
and Ogilvy would create the second largest advertising group in the
world after Britain's Saatchi &amp; Saatchi PLC.
   In 1987, WPP acquired JWT Group Inc. for about $566 million in
the first hostile takeover in the advertising business ever, a deal
that gave WPP a powerful presence in the U.S. market. JWT is the
parent of the New York-based J. Walter Thompson ad agency.
</TEXT>
