   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials was down 7.33 points at
2,374.63 at 10 a.m. EDT, a half-hour after trading began.
   Declining issues outnumbered advancers by about 11 to 5 on the
New York Stock Exchange, with 659 issues up, 294 down and 467
unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 18.85 million shares.
   Larry Wachtel, vice president for Prudential-Bache Securities
Inc., said a combination of Friday's close and a weaker bond market
was pulling the stock market down.
   Stock prices surged early Friday after the government reported
that unemployment rose 0.3 percentage point last month to 5.3
percent. But late in the day, the market pulled back sharply,
partly on concern that inflationary pressures still remain.
   Despite the unemployment number, average hourly earnings
increased seven cents in April.
   Analysts said investors also were awaiting the outcome of this
week's Treasury auction and Friday's inflation numbers, before
making commitments.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks was
down 0.58 to 171.56.
   At the American Stock Exchange, the market value index was down
0.36 at 346.48.
   On Friday the Dow Jones industrial average, up more than 20
points in early trading, closed with a 2.94 loss at 2,381.96.
   That left the average with a loss of 36.84 points.
   Advancing issues outnumbered declines by nearly 4 to 3 on the
NYSE, with 795 up, 608 down and 543 unchanged.
   Big Board volume totaled 180.81 million shares, against 153.13
million in the previous session.
