<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Robins     05-08 0256</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Robins,0265</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reports 13 Percent Gain in First Quarter Earnings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pharmaceutical maker A.H. Robins Co., in
its fourth year of Chapter 11 bankruptcy reorganization, reported a
13 percent increase in earnings Monday for the first quarter of
1989.
   The Richmond-based company reported earnings of $16.3 million,
or 68 cents per share, for the quarter ending March 31, up from
$14.5 million, or 60 cents per share, for the first quarter of 1988.
   First-quarter revenues totaled $226.9 million vs. $217.7 million
a year earlier, a 4.2 percent increase.
   The 1989 earnings include a write-off of $18.3 million invested
in Robins' subsidiaries in Colombia and Venezuela because of
dividend and import restrictions and exchange controls imposed by
those countries, company spokesman Roscoe E. Puckett Jr. said.
Robins will continue to operate the subsidiaries and will record
their earnings on a cash basis, he said.
   The 1988 earnings included a $30.2 million charge for
anticipated expenses related to the company's proposed Chapter 11
reorganization, under which Robins will be acquired by the New
York-based American Home Products Corp. for $3.2 billion.
   Robins filed for Chapter 11 protection in 1985 in the face of
thousands of injury claims by women who used its Dalkon Shield
birth control device. The merger plan with American Home includes a
$2.5 billion trust fund to settle those claims.
   The reorganization plan was confirmed by a federal judge in July
1988 and is now awaiting a decision by the 4th Circuit Court of
Appeals on a challenge to the plan.
</TEXT>
