<FIRST>r f PM-Boeing-SouthAfrica     05-08 0215</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Boeing-South Africa,0225</SECOND>
<HEAD>Announces Jet Sale To South Africa Airways</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Boeing Co. confirmed today that South African
Airways has ordered two 747-400 jumbo jets and taken options for
two more.
   The aircraft deal, valued at about $256 million for the two firm
orders, came under heavy criticism last week from several members
of Washington state's congressional delegation.
   Sen. Brock Adams and Rep. Jim McDermott, both Democrats,
objected to Boeing selling the planes because of South Africa's
policy of racial segregation.
   Boeing, however, said its policy is to sell aircraft, unless
prohibited from doing so by U.S. law.
   ``The company is in business to sell airplanes to airlines all
around the world so long as they are in countries the U.S.
government permits commercial sales in,'' company spokesman Dick
Schleh said.
   The two jets ordered are to be delivered in November 1990 and
May 1991, while the optioned jets would be delivered in 1992.
   South Africa Airways has chosen Rolls-Royce engines for the
planes.
   In South Africa's configuration, the planes would be capable of
carrying 385 passengers in three classes 8,350 miles nonstop.
   Boeing now has received 206 orders from 22 carriers for
747-400s, the world's largest passenger jet. Orders for all
versions of the 747 total 924 from 74 customers.
</TEXT>
