<HEAD>REPEAT FOR ALL NEEDING</HEAD>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Prices Slip Amid Rain Forecasts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices were trading
mostly lower this morning on the Chicago Board of Trade, reflecting
forecasts for rain in the Midwest and Great Plains.
   Strong thunderstorms were expected in the central United States
with showers moving east into the Corn Belt.
   A National Weather Service six-to-10-day forecast issued on
Friday called for more rain early next week in the Midwest.
   The early losses were limited by reports of frost damage to corn
plants over the weekend, and by the Agriculture Department's
announcement after the close of trading on Friday that the Soviet
Union had purchased 200,000 metric tons of U.S. corn and 300,000
metric tons of U.S. wheat.
   The frost damage occurred in the upper Midwest, where corn has
just begun to sprout.
   ``I don't know if it killed it completely, but it definitely
stunted its growth,'' said Jerry Gidel, director of research for
LIT America Inc. in Chicago.
   In early trading, wheat was 1} cents to 3{ cents lower with the
contract for delivery in May at $4.35 a bushel; corn was unchanged
to 1{ cents lower with May at $2.80{ a bushel; oats were } cent to
2\ cents lower with May at $1.95{ a bushel; soybeans were 1 cent to
2{ cents lower with May at $7.58 a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were mostly higher in early trading
on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .05 cent to .13 cent higher with June at 72.55
cents a pound; feeder cattle were .15 cent lower to .23 cent higher
with May at 77.20 cents a pound; live hogs were .05 cent lower to
.28 cent higher with June at 47.55 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .38 cent to .65 cent higher with May at 31.55 cents a
pound.
   Livestock and meat futures settled mostly higher on Friday.
</TEXT>
