<FILEID>AP-NR-05-08-89 1442EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-BordenRecall 3rdLd-Writethru f0118 05-08 0530</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Borden Recall, 3rd Ld-Writethru, f0118,0542</SECOND>
<HEAD>Borden Pulls Products From Two States Because Of Contamination</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with health official saying no
danger to the public, more detail on contaminant. PICKS UP 7th graf pvs
bg'ng, Tilton said ...; Also moved on general newswires</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RON HARRIST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Borden Inc., the world's largest dairy
company, said it pulled its products from the shelves in two
Southern states today after finding milk with traces of a toxic
substance from contaminated feed.
   Chris Tilton, a Borden spokeswoman in Columbus, Ohio, said it
isn't known if any of the contaminated products had been purchased,
but a state health official said the substance is present in
amounts too small to be dangerous.
   Borden pulled milk, ice cream and other liquid dairy items from
stores in Mississippi and the northern two-thirds of Louisiana,
where 32 dairies that apparently used feed tainted with barium
carbonate supplied milk, she said.
   It was not immediately known if the dairies supplied other milk
processors.
   Barium carbonate is a white powder used as rat poison and in
glass, ceramics, paint, rubber and electronics, said Michael
Hughes, managing director of the poison control center at the
University of Mississippi Medical Center.
   ``We've done our own testing and the state of Louisiana labs
also tested, with some of the milk testing positive in trace
amounts,'' Tilton said. ``We would not want any of our products
going out with any level of this in it, no matter how small.''
   ``The amount you can drink is far less than the amount that
would be dangerous,'' said Dr. Ed Thompson, a state Health
Department epidemiologist. A person would have to drink more than
100 8-ounce glasses of the milk in succession for it to be fatal,
Thompson said.
   Tilton said Borden discovered the contamination after learning
from Louisiana that some cattle had died or become ill.
   Louisiana Agriculture Commissioner Bob Odom said investigators
believe the feed became contaminated when it was put in a railroad
hopper that had held barium carbonate.
   Tilton said it was not immediately known how many items were
pulled and how many stores were involved. She said the company was
checking to see when the tainted products were put on shelves.
   ``We will be supplying those markets later today with products
shipped from plants outside the area until the local milk supply is
clean,'' Tilton said.
   The government allowable standard for barium carbonate in water
is one part per million, Tilton said, and ``we have found nothing
close to that, just percentages of one part per million.''
   Odom said today he had not been informed of the recall but that
state officials last week learned that 25 to 30 cows had died
mysteriously at Louisiana dairy farms. Officials ordered companies
that received milk from those dairies to hold milk from
distribution until samples could be tested.
   ``The information we got was that the milk had been bottled, but
it had not reached the shelf,'' said Odom. He said he didn't know
how many farms were affected or how many distributors might have
had to hold on to their milk.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
