<SECOND>BC-Dollar-Gold,0321</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Mixed, Gold Higher</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: A version for AMs is planned by 5:30 p.m. EDT.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar gave a mixed performance Monday as
cautious European traders stepped to the sidelines amid speculation
about the possibility of central bank intervention. Gold prices
rose.
   Dealers said the dollar moved within a narrow range in calm
trading. The dollar remained well supported by expectations that
U.S. interest rates will not decline, they said.
   In Frankfurt, dealers said some participants were fearful of
dollar-selling by the West German central bank as the dollar edged
up toward a critical level of 1.9000 marks. But there was no sign
of intervention by the Bundesbank or other European central banks.
   Earlier, in Tokyo, the Bank of Japan sold an estimated $100
million for Japanese yen in an apparently unsuccessful bid to
depress the dollar.
   The dollar closed at 134.52 yen, up 0.67 yen from last Tuesday.
Japanese financial markets were closed the rest of the week for
holidays. In London late Monday, the dollar remained at 134.52 yen.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late rates
Friday included: 1.8975 West German marks, down from 1.8988; 1.6945
Swiss francs, down from 1.6985; 6.4025 French francs, down from
6.4080; 2.1400 Dutch guilders, up from 2.1285; 1,385.00 Italian
lire, up from 1,379.00; and, 1.1850 Canadian dollars, up from
1.1842.
   In London, the British pound fell to $1.6710 from $1.6740 late
Friday.
   Gold bullion rose in London to a late bid price of $377.50 a
troy ounce, up from $376.25 bid late Friday.
   In Zurich, the metal rose to $377.75, up from $375.85 bid late
Friday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose 48 cents to close at a bid
$378.41.
   Silver bullion rose in London to a late bid price of $5.64 a
troy ounce, up from $5.60 late Friday.
</TEXT>
