<HEAD>Met Life CEO Creedon Retiring</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf, `Creedon will ...' to CLARIFY Met Life's retirement
policy.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Metropolitan Life Insurance Co. Monday announced
the retirement of John J. Creedon, president and chief executive
officer and a 47-year veteran of the company.
   Creedon will step down on Sept. 1 after holding the position
since it was created in 1983. Met Life has a mandatory retirement
policy for certain high-level executives once they reach 65.
   His successor will be Met Life Chairman Robert G. Schwartz, who
will assume the additional responsibilities of president and CEO.
   Creedon will continue as a director and chairman of the
executive and dividend policy committee of Met Life, one of the
nation's largest insurance and financial services companies.
   While Creedon has been president and CEO, Met Life has expanded
its insurance services and diversified into other fields, including
financial services. It extended its geographical presence, opening
offices in European and Far Eastern countries, and acquired new
businesses, such as Century 21, a large real estate sales operation.
   In his role as chairman of the board, Schwartz has directed all
of Met Life's investment activities and pensions operations. He
started his career at Met Life in 1947.
   ``We plan to continue on the course that has been charted,''
Schwartz said in a company announcement.
</TEXT>
