   The stock market was lower in dull afternoon
trading, as investors drifted to the sidelines to await more news
on the economy.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials was down 11.73 points to
2,370.23 at 3 p.m. EDT. The blue-chip indicator was 15.39 points
lower an hour earlier.
   Declining issues outnumbered advancers by about 7 to 3 on the
New York Stock Exchange, with 995 issues up, 428 down and 495
unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 111.53 million shares.
   Analysts said bearish forecasts about the economy, including
growing talk of a recession, sent jitters through the market and
investors to the sidelines.
   The market's nervousness follows Friday's government report that
hourly earnings rose in April despite an increase in unemployment.
   The Labor Department reported that unemployment rose 0.3
percentage point in April to 5.3 percent, a signal that the
economy's growth is slowing. But the report also showed that hourly
earnings rose 7 cents.
   Analysts said many institutional investors took to the sidelines
to await the outcome of this week's three-day Treasury auction,
which starts Tuesday, as well as Thursday's figures on retail sales
and Friday's producer price numbers.
   Softer bond prices ahead of the auction were helping to weaken
stocks, traders said.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks was
down 1.16 to 170.98.
   At the American Stock Exchange, the market value index was off
1.52 to 345.32.
   Among actively traded issues, Upjohn was up 1] to 31}, Avon
advanced { to 36| and Texaco gained [ to 53~.
   Airline stocks continued to sell actively, with Northwest
Airlines down } at 104{, Delta off 1\ at 64} and UAL losing 1{ to
123\.
   In over-the-counter trading, Ogilvy Group was up 2[ points to
52. The advertising agency said today it received a higher takeover
offer from British marketing and communications company WPP Group
PLC.
