<FILEID>AP-NR-05-08-89 1607EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Mosbacher     05-08 0369</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mosbacher,0385</SECOND>
<HEAD>Automakers' Move To High Tech Cited As Role Model</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM S. BERGSTROM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The challenge from imports that hustled Detroit
automakers into a high-technology age should be taken seriously by
other businesses, U.S. Commerce Secretary Robert A. Mosbacher said
Monday.
   The government can help by pushing to end some other countries'
restrictions on imports from the United States, Mosbacher told a
news conference before a meeting of the Economic Club of Detroit.
   He said cutting capital gains taxes and continuing tax credits
for research and development spending would give businesses more
financial and technological resources to compete.
   ``There's no panacea. We've got to realize that it's a shrinking
world and if we want to do more than flip the hamburgers for the
world we've got to come out with quality products,'' Mosbacher said.
   The auto industry and others, including aerospace,
telecommunications, biotechnology and medical products, have met
challenges from imports and improved, Mosbacher said.
   ``They woke up. They did a very good job of adapting,''
Mosbacher said.
   To help others, he said, the government is preparing to enforce
laws to penalize countries that restrict imports from the United
States.
   ``We are in the throes of deciding which countries to cite,''
Mosbacher said. He said those decisions will be made by the end of
May.
   The object is not to hurt any other country but to press for
removal of trade barriers, he said. ``The whole point is to open
other markets and level the playing field.''
   Mosbacher advocated capital gains tax cuts as a means of
reducing the cost of capital for business.
   More readily available capital would create jobs and stimulate
long-term projects by businesses, Mosbacher said.
   Mosbacher also proposed making permanent a tax credit for
research and development spending.
   Reitering comments he made in Washington recently, Mosbacher
said antitrust law changes should be considered to allow innovative
pooling of research teams from small and large companies to take on
European and Japanese competitors.
   Mosbacher said he expected economic growth to slow for the
remainder of the year but still show some increases. ``I feel very
confident about less inflation problems and continuing growth in
the economy,'' he said.
</TEXT>
