<HEAD>Stock Prices Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market declined today in fairly quiet
trading, pressured by growing talk of a recession amid ongoing
concern about inflation.
   The market opened lower on a carryover from Friday's last-minute
sell-off and in response to a weaker bond market ahead of this
week's three-day treasury borrowing.
   Prices drifted lower during the session as many big players
withdrew to the sidelines to await fresh news on the economy.
Traders said airline stocks were among the most active on the sell
list as investors took profits.
   Last Friday's employment figures touched off dual concerns about
inflation and a recession, analysts said.
   The Labor Department reported that unemployment rose 0.3
percentage point in April to 5.3 percent, a signal that the
economy's growth is slowing. But the report also showed that hourly
earnings rose 7 cents.
   Analysts said growing talk of a recession was producing jitters
in the marketplace and raising concern about future corporate
profits.
   ``The mention of a recession worries investors,'' said Philip
Puccio, senior vice president with Dillon, Read &amp; Co.
   Among other indicators of the economy's health, investors were
focusing on this week's three-day Treasury auction.
   ``The market is really going to turn on the auctions
themselves,'' said Larry Wachtel, vice president of
Prudential-Bache Securities Inc.
   Also diverting the market's attention are upcoming figures on
retail sales and producer prices, due out Thursday and Friday
respectively.
