<HEAD>Northrop Reprimands Chairman for Trying to Sell F-20s to South Korea</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Northrop Corp. Chairman Thomas V. Jones was
formally reprimanded for ``his management style'' in attempting to
sell F-20 jet fighters to South Korea, the aerospace company said
in proxy material.
   Northrop's executive committee and outside directors issued the
reprimand, divulged in proxy material dated April 24. Jones
announced earlier he would retire as chief executive officer by
Dec. 31.
   A House subcommittee and a federal grand jury have been
investigating $7.8 million in payments made by Northrop from 1984
to 1986 in connection with attempts to sell the F-20. Northrop
never found a buyer for the plane.
   Jones has been subpoenaed to testify before the subcommittee.
   ``The executive committee of the board of directors is
continuing its own investigation into these matters,'' the proxy
statement said.
   The board didn't elaborate on what it meant by Jones' management
style.
   ``In addition, the executive committee together with the other
outside directors reprimanded Mr. Jones regarding his management
style in connection with Northrop's efforts to sell the F-20 to the
government of South Korea,'' it said.
   Tony Cantafio, spokesman for the aerospace giant, said he
couldn't expand beyond the proxy statement. Jones was traveling and
unavailable for comment, the spokesman said.
