<FILEID>AP-NR-05-08-89 1732EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     05-08 0661</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0688</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Defies Intervention and Rises Broadly; Gold Mixed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON BC</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARYBETH NIBLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar rose broadly in brisk U.S. trading
Monday as Federal Reserve intervention proved ineffective in
deterring buyers.
   Gold prices fell in the United States, reversing course after
rising modestly overseas. Republic National Bank of New York quoted
a troy ounce of gold bullion at $375.40 as of 4 p.m. EDT, $1.60
lower than Friday's late bid.
   ``The market is beginning to believe now that the major central
banks are not committed to holding the dollar at current levels,''
said Jon Lopatin, a vice president in Goldman Sachs &amp; Co.'s
foreign-exchange department.
   This conviction was at least partly responsible for driving the
dollar to its highest level in months against the West German mark.
   In U.S. trading, the dollar ended at 1.9097 marks, up from
1.8977 Friday, and piercing what was described as an important
technical threshold of 1.90 marks. It was the highest closing level
since August 1988.
   A variety of factors fed the dollar's advance. Key catalysts
were comments by the president of West Germany's central bank and
the fact that the dollar remained above levels identified as
significant from a technical standpoint, despite Fed intervention.
   Bundesbank President Karl Otto Poehl indicated the dollar's
value against other major currencies is a matter being decided by
the markets and countries would have to live with the decision.
   Speaking in Basel, Switzerland, after a regular meeting of the
Group of Ten central bankers, he said the dollar's strength is
remarkable given the trade imbalances among leading industrialized
countries.
   Foreign-exchange dealers interpreted his remarks to imply that
government monetary authorities are unlikely to act aggressively to
influence the dollar.
   Dealers in the United States reported the Fed sold dollars for
marks and Japanese yen when the U.S. currency was trading at 1.9080
marks and 134.75 yen. But the intervention had no discernible
impact and the dollar continued to rise.
   Earlier, on foreign-exchange markets in Europe and Asia, the
dollar had a mixed showing.
   Dealers in Frankfurt, West Germany, said some participants were
anticipating dollar-selling by the Bundesbank as the dollar
approached 1.9000 marks. But there was no sign of intervention by
the Bundesbank or other European central banks.
   In Tokyo, the Bank of Japan sold an estimated $100 million for
Japanese yen. The dollar closed at 134.52 yen, up 0.67 yen from
last Tuesday. Japanese financial markets were closed the rest of
the week for holidays.
   Later, in London, the dollar remained at 134.52 yen. In New
York, the dollar rose to 134.89 yen from 134.25 Friday.
   The British pound fell to $1.6710 in London from $1.6740 late
Friday. In New York, sterling fetched $1.6646 compared with $1.6755
on Friday.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with rates late
Friday, included: 1.7025 Swiss francs, up from 1.6963; 6.4405
French francs, up from 6.4020; 1,392.75 Italian lire, up from
1,384.63; and, 1.1846 Canadian dollars up from 1.1842.
   Late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late rates Friday
included: 1.8975 West German marks, down from 1.8988; 1.6945 Swiss
francs, down from 1.6985; 6.4025 French francs, down from 6.4080;
2.1400 Dutch guilders, up from 2.1285; 1,385.00 Italian lire, up
from 1,379.00; and, 1.1850 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1842.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold for current delivery
settled at $376.90 a troy ounce, down from $377.70 Friday.
   Gold bullion rose in London to a late bid price of $377.50 a
troy ounce, up from $376.25 bid late Friday. In Zurich,
Switzerland, the metal rose to $377.75, up from $375.85 bid late
Friday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose 48 cents to close at a bid
$378.41.
   Silver bullion for current delivery closed on New York's Comex
at $5.588 a troy ounce, down from Friday's settlement of $5.598.
Silver bullion rose in London to a late bid price of $5.64 a troy
ounce, up from $5.60 late Friday.
</TEXT>
