<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     05-08 0692</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0715</SECOND>
<HEAD>Copper Futures Slide On Sharp Rise In Stocks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Copper futures prices tumbled Monday on New York's Commodity
Exchange following an unexpectedly large increase in warehouse
stocks of copper reported by the London Metal Exchange.
   On other markets, palladium surged while gold and silver prices
slipped; energy futures plummeted; grains and soybeans were mostly
lower; cattle futures dipped, and pork prices advanced.
   Copper settled 2.7 cents to 5.2 cents lower with the spot
contract for delivery in May at $1.259 a pound and the most active
contract, for July delivery, at $1.216 a pound.
   It was the second straight declining day for copper, a market
that reached a record high of $1.6475 a pound last December on
tight supplies and strong demand.
   Analysts attributed the sell-off mainly to the London Metal
Exchange's weekly report, which showed a 17,175-ton net increase in
warehouse stocks tracked by the exchange, to 131,275 tons.
   ``It was a very large increase and very unexpected,'' said Bette
Raptopoulos, an analyst with Prudential-Bache Securities Inc. in
New York. ``They were expecting about 4,000 or 5,000 tons.''
   Experts cited increased copper exports from Zambia and an
unusually small amount of drawdown of stocks in Singapore. But it
was not clear whether the rise in overall stocks signaled a
significant change in market fundamentals.
   The possibility of a miners' strike in Poland kept the market
from falling further, as did expectations of labor unrest as
contracts with some of the major North American copper companies
approach expiration at the end of June.
   ``By the end of May, I think we'll begin to see anticipatory
buying and enhanced demand for copper,'' said analyst George
Anagnos of Thomson McKinnon Securities Inc. in New York.
   Palladium futures rallied on renewed supply fears, while gold
and silver slipped in dull trading.
   Palladium settled $4.35 to $4.85 higher on the New York
Mercantile Exchange with May at $163 a troy ounce. On the Commodity
Exchange, gold was 60 cents to 90 cents lower with June at $378.40
a troy ounce; silver was 1 cent lower across the board with July at
$5.677 a troy ounce.
   Unleaded gasoline futures plummeted the permitted
2-cents-a-gallon daily limit on the New York Merc as the energy
market extended a steep decline begun on Friday.
   The sell-off was linked to reports last week of overproduction
by OPEC members and was fueled Monday by technical signals that the
market was due for a downward correction.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 15 cents to 58 cents
lower with June at $19.44 a barrel; heating oil was .68 cent to .79
cent lower with June at 46.69 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline was
1.96 cents to 2.52 cents lower with the nearby June contract, to
which the daily limit does not apply, at 64.98 cents a gallon.
   Grain and soybean futures closed mostly lower on the Chicago
Board of Trade amid rain forecasts, but soybean oil prices surged
on rumors of an impending sale of U.S. soybean oil to the Soviet
Union at subsidized prices.
   Soybean oil for spot delivery settled 39 cents higher at $23.78
per hundredweight and traded as high as $23.90 during the session.
   Wheat settled 1 cent lower to { cent higher with May at $4.36 a
bushel; corn was 1 cent to 2} cents lower with May at $2.79{ a
bushel; oats were 4\ cents to 6 cents lower with May at $1.92{ a
bushel; soybeans were 12} cents lower to 5 cents higher with May at
$7.64{ a bushel.
   Cattle futures prices sank on ideas that demand for beef would
slacken after Memorial Day. Pork futures advanced on expectations
of a slowdown in hog marketings as producers increasingly turn
their attention to fieldwork.
   Live cattle settled .10 cent to .30 cent lower with June at
72.15 cents a pound; feeder cattle were unchanged to .25 cent lower
with May at 76.77 cents a pound; live hogs were .15 cent lower to
.55 cent higher with June at 47.82 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .20 cent to 1.07 cents higher with May at 32.02 cents
a pound.
</TEXT>
