<FIRST>u f AM-Avon-Amway     05-08 0424</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Avon-Amway,0440</SECOND>
<HEAD>Avon Sues to Block More Share Purchases</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Stands for Grands Rapids-dated item on late news advisory.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Avon Products Inc. filed a federal lawsuit Monday seeking a
court order preventing a partnership of Amway Corp. and Minneapolis
investor Irwin Jacobs from acquiring more Avon stock.
   The suit, filed in U.S. District Court in New York, accused
Amway and Jacobs of violating disclosure requirements of federal
securities laws in their acquisition of Avon stock, Avon said in a
statement.
   The suit asked that Amway and Jacobs be ordered to sell the Avon
stock they already have purchased, the New York-based cosmetics and
household products company said.
   ``We're not familiar with it,'' Amway spokeswoman Kim Bruyn said
Monday afternoon. ``We haven't seen it, and therefore we have no
comment.''
   Earlier Monday, Amway co-founder Jay Van Andel said the Ada,
Mich.-based company had nt decided whether to pursue acquisition of
Avon, its larger rival in the direct selling business.
   Amway, a large direct seller of personal and home products, has
purchased more than 10 percent of Avon common stock in the past
month in partnership with Jacobs, a well-known takeover strategist.
   Van Andel told the Grand Rapids, Mich., Economic Club that a
takeover would have to benefit both companies.
   He compared Amway's position to that of a diver who walks out on
the diving board ``and has to decide whether to make a swan dive
... or a belly flop. We haven't made that decision yet. We're still
on the board looking around.
   ``If we were to decide to make the plunge ... the plunge would
have to be good for Amway as a company and Avon as a company,'' Van
Andel said.
   The statement released by Avon described Amway as ``a
controversial purveyor of a pyramidal direct marketing scheme that
has never made a major acquisition.''
   It also described Jacobs as ``a well-known raider who has not
completed an acquisition for many years or any acquisition for
significantly more than $500 million.''
   Amway, owned by Van Andel and partner Richard DeVos, claims 1
million distributors worldwide. Avon says it has 1.475 million
independent sales representatives.
   Avon reported 1988 revenue of $3.06 billion but lost $404.5
million due to losses from discontinued operations. The company has
been divesting unprofitable businesses in the health care services
field and concentrating on its direct selling and beauty products
operations.
   James E. Preston, Avon's chairman, has said the company is not
for sale and that shareholders stand to do better if Avon remains
independent.
</TEXT>
