<SECOND>AM-Texas Eastern,0154</SECOND>
<HEAD>Trade Commission Gives Preliminary Approval To Pipeline Deal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Trade Commission on Monday gave
preliminary approval to Panhandle Eastern Corp.'s $3.2 billion
acquisition of Texas Eastern Transmission Corp.
   The commission said Panhandle agreed, as a condition of the
merger, to sell its interest in Stingray Pipeline Co., which
carries natural gas out of portions of the Gulf of Mexico south of
eastern Texas and western Louisiana. Stingray competes directly
with a pipeline owned by Texas Eastern.
   Panhandle also agreed that, over the next 10 years, it must get
FTC approval for buying any natural gas pipeline in the Gulf of
Mexico area.
   The commission said its preliminary approval of the merger would
be subject to a 60-day public comment period. After that the
commission will decide whether to give final approval.
   Panhandle and Texas Eastern both are based in Houston.
