<HEAD>Magazine Founded By Andy Warhol Sold</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Interview, the oversized celebrity feature
magazine founded by Andy Warhol in 1969, was sold Monday by the
estate of the late pop artist to a New York publishing house.
   Brant Publications Inc. has agreed in principle to buy the
monthly magazine from Andy Warhol Enterprises Inc., the parties
announced. Terms of the sale were not disclosed.
   Interview, which includes a huge portrait of a featured
interview subject on its cover, has a circulation of 151,660. The
magazine consists of question-and-answer sessions with artists,
movie stars, politicans and other public figures.
   Brant Publications publishes Art in America and The Magazine
Antiques, which have a combined circulation of 130,000. It also
owns Stewart, Tabori and Change, an illustrated books publisher.
   Warhol, the maverick artist with white hair known for his
renditions of Marilyn Monroe and Campbell soup cans, died in
February 1987 at age 58.
