<FILEID>AP-NR-05-08-89 2015EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-BeefPurchase     05-08 0195</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Beef Purchase,0200</SECOND>
<HEAD>South Korea Buys 6.6 Million Pounds Of Beef In Denver</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The South Korean government bought 6.6 million
pounds of U.S. beef in Denver from a Los Angeles company, one of
the first times a foreign government has purchased beef on this
scale in the United States, the U.S. Meat Export Federation said
Monday.
   The Livestock Product Marketing Organization, a
quasi-governmental group responsible for Korean meat imports,
bought the U.S. boneless boxed beef valued at $11.4 million from
the All American Corp. of Los Angeles, the Denver-based federation
said in a news statement.
   The federation said the purchase, which was completed last
Friday, came after bids were made by 16 U.S. companies.
   ``This purchase is important because it represents the opening
of a significant market for U.S. beef producers and packers,''
federation President Alan Middaugh said. ``Koreans have
demonstrated a keen demand for beef products, and compose the
fastest-growing market for U.S. beef exports next to Japan.''
   Korea is expected to buy more than 100 million pounds of beef in
1989. Australia is one of the United States' largest competitors
for this market, according to the Meat Export Federation.
</TEXT>
