<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-TBS     05-08 0173</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-TBS,0181</SECOND>
<HEAD>Turner Broadcasting System Losses Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Turner Broadcasting System Inc. on Monday
reported a net loss of $421,000 for the first quarter, the lowest
shortfall since the company acquired MGM-UA three years ago.
   The loss, which came on revenue of nearly $232 million, compared
with a $14.1 million deficit on revenue of $182.6 million a year
earlier.
   TBS Chairman Ted Turner said in a statement greater operating
profits and a $3 million gain from land sales offset some of the
company's losses.
   Revenue for TBS' entertainment segment for the quarter ended
March 31 rose to $82.3 million from $57.8 million, mainly because
of the addition of Turner Network Television, the company reported.
   TBS' news division, which includes Cable News Network, had
revenue of nearly $79 million, up from $59.8 million a year earlier.
   The company's syndication and licensing division brought in
first-quarter revenue of $57.4 million, up from $51.5 million. The
company said that growth came from a new wrestling operation,
increased home video sales and merchandise licensing.
</TEXT>
