<FILEID>AP-NR-05-08-89 2233EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Halliburton     05-08 0140</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Halliburton,0148</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dallas Oil Field Services Company Has Slow Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Halliburton Co. reported Monday its earnings
declined nearly 57 percent to $13.7 million during the first
quarter because of intensified competition among oil field service
companies.
   Halliburton said it earned $13.7 million, or 13 cents per share,
down from $31.8 million, or 30 cents per share, reported for the
same period last year.
   Halliburton officials said lower worldwide oil field activity
has intensified competition in oil field services.
   In the first three months of 1989, there were about 15 percent
fewer rotary rigs working worldwide than there had been a year
earlier.
   ``We expect our oil field markets to strengthen in the second
half of 1989 as our customers increase spending, particularly for
natural gas development in the United States,'' said Halliburton
President Thomas H. Cruikshank.
</TEXT>
